<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ESMG Explosion doors with air-cushion
</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../esmg.gif" ALT="ESMG Logo">
<H1>Products</H1>
</CENTER>
<H2>Explosion doors with air-cushion</H2>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>Pressure relief devices are used wherever ignitable dust 
materials are stored (silos, bunkers etc.) or conveyed (dust collectors). In 
case of an explosion the pressure is vented and the vessel or the collector 
housing protected from adverse effects. This can be accomplished with various 
means. The following systems are commercially available and well known:
<DL>
<DT>RUPTURE DISKS
<DD>Advantage: high venting efficiency.
Disadvantages: labor-intensive replacement with downtime after an explosion 
and no automatic closure. Air (oxygen) is free to enter the vessel and 
supports fires for a long duration. In addition, premature failure due to 
fatigue from fluctuating pressures i.e. conveying cycles and jet 
filter cleaning may occur.<BR><BR>
<DT>HEAVY EXPLOSION DOORS
<DD>Advantage: fully automatic closure after each explosion. 
Disadvantages: low venting efficiency because of the heavy weight of the 
lid (inertia) and, for the same reason, substantial mass forces stemming from 
its sudden deceleration against a rigid buffer.
</DL>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><STRONG>SIT air-cushioned explosion doors</STRONG><BR>
are entirely different. Because for their different working principle they offer significant advantages:
<UL>
<LI>high efficiency
<LI>fully automatic closure
<LI>large opening angle exceeding 90
<LI>suitable for a wide range of reduced explosion pressures Pred
<LI>low impact on base, even in case of violent explosions
<LI>fully functional at all times due to stainless steel construction of retaining device and of all essential components
</UL>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>In a comprehensive study, carried out by Mr. M. Faber of 
"Bergbau-Versuchsstrecke" Dortmund - published under ZKG No. 4/83 -, the 
following statement is made:
<BR>"Up to this date, the door is the only device known to be suitable for 
venting low- and high pressure vessels without reducing the relief efficiency 
to uneconomically low values."
<BR>In addition, the study found that an efficiency of 50-60% is 
normal for weight-loaded explosion doors on vessels of limited 
strength (<1.5 barg). SIT air-cushioned explosion doors of the type RLE 
however have a documented efficiency of 85-96%. All efficiency values are 
compared against values obtained from low-mass rupture disks.

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><STRONG>Principle of operation of the SIT air-cushioned explosion door</STRONG><BR>
The tremendous advantage of the patented SIT air-cushioned explosion door is shown 
in the simplified sketch. The three-step action is as follows:
<OL>
<LI>The retaining devices release the explosion doors lid once the explosion 
pressure reaches the pre-set static response pressure. Whilst the lid opens 
around its hinge axis and accelerates in this movement, an air-cushion is 
built-up against the resilient baffle plate assembly. The air-cushion decelerates 
the lid. The higher the explosion forces, the better the effect of the air-cushion.
<LI>Due to the low weight of the aluminium lid, hitting against the heavy mass of 
the resilient baffle plate, most of the impact energy is absorbed (inertia).
<LI>The remaining energy is absorbed by a spring assembly supporting the 
baffle plate. The springs also assist in re-closing the lid that falls back 
into its original position and is automatically held by the retaining devices 
again. The quick re-closing avoid free access of oxygen from the atmosphere into 
the vessel and chimney effects that would support a fire. Each venting action 
can be signalized remotely by means of an optional sentinel switch monitoring the 
lid. 
</OL>

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>Immediately after the explosion a vacuum will occur in the 
closed vessel due to rapid cooling-down of the gas. This has deformed or 
destroyed many vessels in the past. A SIT air-cushioned explosion door prevents 
this as the built-in vacuum in the vessel of as low as 0.01 bar. SIT 
air-cushioned explosion door are available in various designs and sizes:

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><STRONG>Type TT-Uni (round door)</STRONG>, preferably for Pred  
values &gt; 1.5 barg, for vertical or inclined venting and with optional vacuum 
breakers.

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><STRONG>Type RLE and RLE-S (rectangular doors)</STRONG> for Pred  
figures below 1.5 barg and large venting areas for horizontal, inclined and 
vertical venting.</P>
StuvEx GmbH<BR>
Wilhelmstr. 2<BR>
D-59057 Hamm<BR>
Tel.: +49-2381-271480<BR>
Fax: +49-2381-271248<BR>
<BR>
For further information please contact us by e-mail: 
<A HREF=mailto:ober@prosicht.hamtec.de>ober@prosicht.hamtec.de</A>

