<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ESMG Round air-cushioned explosion door
</TITLE>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../esmg.gif" ALT="ESMG Logo">
<H1>Products</H1>
</CENTER>
<H2>Round air-cushioned explosion door
preferably for educed explosion pressure &gt; 1.5 barg</H2>


<STRONG>Design features</STRONG>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>SIT round air-cushioned explosion doors, type TT-UNI, are 
mainly used for venting in situations where the calculated reduced explosion 
pressure Pred exceeds 1.5 barg. Due to their light construction, they perform 
with an efficiency close to rupture disks. A low overall height - in line 
with BVS recommendations - avoids the negative effects known from venting ducts.

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>The following design features are important:
<OL>
<LI>The air-cushion, which is formed between the lid and the baffle plate, 
acts as a shock absorber.
<LI>The impact force of the lid is absorbed by the heavy resilient baffle plate 
using its inertia.
<LI>The low weight of the lid results in little inertia and quick opening, 
i.e. high efficiency.
<LI>In addition, the spring-mounted baffle plate facilitates an opening 
substantially in excess of 90 and a reliable closure after an explosion.
</OL>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>The low weight and smooth deceleration without significant 
impact on the base allow for installation of the doors on unreinforced structures.

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>The spring-loaded retaining devices can be adjusted for 
static response pressures Pstat in the range of 1.03 - 1.10 barg. 
Therefore, the explosion doors are very well suited for large dust 
collectors. An optional sentinel switch enables remote signalization of 
a venting action.

<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY><STRONG>Vacuum relief</STRONG>
Test results at BVS Dortmund have shown that a vacuum of more than 0.8 bar 
will result from a rapid cooling-down of the gas after an explosion inside 
a silo. No pressure shock resistant round silo will withstand such vacuum. 
Therefore, as an option, the SIT air-cushioned explosion doors, type TT-UNI, 
may be equipped with vacuum breakers. Such automatic safety device will respond 
at a vacuum of as low as 0.01 bar inside a silo.
<BR>The vacuum breaker is designed and built to provide satisfactory 
performance even under poor maintenance conditions.

<P ALIGN=LEFT><STRONG>Sizes and technical data</STRONG><BR><BR>

<TABLE WIDTH=400 BORDER CELLPADDING=5>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=TOP>
<TD>Types nominal size<BR><BR></TD>
<TD>inner &oslash; mm</TD>
<TD>relief area  m&sup2;</TD>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=CENTER>
<TD>TT 600 Uni</TD>
<TD>590</TD>
<TD>0.27</TD>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=CENTER>
<TD>TT 800 Uni</TD>
<TD>790</TD>
<TD>0.50</TD>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=CENTER>
<TD>TT 1150 Uni</TD>
<TD>1150</TD>
<TD>1.00</TD>
<TR ALIGN=LEFT VALIGN=CENTER>
<TD>TT 1400 Uni</TD>
<TD>1385</TD>
<TD>1.50</TD>
</TABLE>
<P ALIGN=JUSTIFY>Already existing explosion doors - competitors brands not 
excluded - can be retrofitted with SIT vacuum breakers by using SIT adapter 
series AD-U in order to protect installations against a vacuum collaps after 
successful venting.<BR>
A special version of TT-Uni series can be used on explosion stacks.</P>

