</CENTER>

<P>H. de Vries: On the current situation of Fire Prevention in England
<P>In July 1994 the Fire Legislation & Enforcement Report was published by the Department of Trade and Industry. This socalled Fire Scrutiny Review aimed at deregulating Fire Prevention Legislation, reducing responsibility overlaps between authorities, and lessening legal burdens for builders, owners and occupiers. The investigation focused on whether the responsibility of the Fire Service for their safety matters is still adequate and necessary. The 61 recommendations of the Report indicate a way to a simplification and rationalisation of fire safety matters. The Repon states that the European Union's Health and Safety Directives should be implemented into revised fire safety laws. It is found that the Fire Service and their expertise are a crucial part of fire prevention. This finding of the Interdepartmental Review Team is of interest for Germany, too, for it confirms the importance of the Fire Service's statutory role.<BR>
The author quotes several statistics in order to demonstrate that it is not feasible to lessen the fire preventive requirements for occupied buildings. Finally, the findings of the Fire Scrutiny Report are discussed under the aspect of the circumstances in Germany:<BR>
It is shown how West Midlands Fire Service has an overall approach to fire safety, consisting of Building Fire Safety, Fire Investigation, Fire Statistics, and Public Relations.

<P><HR SIZE=6>
<CENTER>
<FONT SIZE=-4>
[ Letzte Aktualisierung, Last Update 26.11.96 ] </FONT>
</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>


