<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ACCIDENTS DURING MARINE TRANSPORT OF DANGEROUS GOODS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199510449
Quality valid. date   :1995-04-11
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :ACCIDENTS DURING MARINE TRANSPORT OF DANGEROUS GOODS
       : DISTRIBUTION OF FATALITIES
Author                :ROMER H
       HAASTRUP P
       PETERSEN H J S
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA (IT)
       JRC ISPRA (IT)
       TECHNICAL  UNIVERSITY OF DENMARK, DEPARTMENT OF CHEMICAL ENGINEERING,
       LYNGBY (DK)
Bibliogr reference    :ARTICLE: JOURNAL OF LOSS PREVENTION IN THE PROCESS
       INDUSTRIES,     VOL.     8     (1995)     NO.     1,     PP.    29-34
Abstract              :The numbers of fatalities from 1780 marine accidents
       during  transport  of  dangerous  goods have been compared with those
       from  other  transport  modes.  Accidents  from  marine  transport of
       dangerous  goods  have  been  found  to have a larger proportion with
       fatalities in the range of 10-50. This is probably due to the size of
       the  potentially  affected  population, reflecting the number of crew
       members  on  one  or two vessels; further, the population potentially
       affected  is placed in a limited area. Almost all accidents with more
       than  40 fatalities were collisions, and accidents with more than 100
       fatalities  were due to collisions between tankers and ferries, which
       significantly   increases  the  population  at  risk.  The  hazardous
       substance  involved  in  these  accidents was oil. The high number of
       fatalities  is  not  surprising,  as oil at sea has the potential for
       surrounding a vessel and catching fire.
Facet codes           :007 Safety
       210 Marine science and technology
       314 Transportation
Availability in lang  :en English
Publication year      :1995
Publication type      :ART An article in a journal
Euroabstracts number  :EAB13379500
Subject index codes   :SAF (SAFETY)
       TRA (TRANSPORT)
       SEA (RESOURCES OF THE SEA, FISHERIES)
 
            --------------------------------------------------
 
 
</PRE>
