<HEAD>
<TITLE>
LEARNING FROM MAJOR ACCIDENTS INVOLVING DANGEROUS
SUBSTANCES
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199311072
Quality valid. date   :1994-11-29
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :LEARNING FROM MAJOR ACCIDENTS INVOLVING DANGEROUS
       SUBSTANCES
Author                :DROGARIS G
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA (IT)
Bibliogr reference    :ARTICLE: SAFETY SCIENCE, VOL. 16 (1993) PP. 89-113
Abstract              :By the end of 1991 a total of 121 accidents had been
       reported  to MARS, the Major Accident Reporting System established by
       the  CEC  in  the  Seveso  Directive.  The accident reports have been
       analysed  and  the  accidents  classified  according  to  a number of
       parameters.  Both  immediate and underlying accident causes have been
       identified   for   the   vast  majority  of  accidents  notified  and
       consequently,   lessons   for   preventing   similar  recurrences  or
       mitigating  accident  consequences have been extracted. This analysis
       shows  that  the vast majority of the accidents notified could easily
       have been prevented by proper application of available knowledge.
       Managerial/organisational  omissions  and design inadequacies are the
       most dominant underlying causes.
Facet codes           :102 Chemical engineering
       312 Safety engineering
Availability in lang  :en English
Publication year      :1993
Publication type      :ART An article in a journal
