<HEAD>
<TITLE>
A CONSEQUENCE MODEL FOR CHLORINE AND AMMONIA BASED ON
A FATALITY INDEX APPROACH
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199211025
Quality valid. date   :1994-12-02
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :A CONSEQUENCE MODEL FOR CHLORINE AND AMMONIA BASED ON
       A FATALITY INDEX APPROACH
Author                :BROCKHOFF L
       HAASTRUP P
       STYHR PETERSEN H J
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA (IT)
       JRC ISPRA (IT)
       TECHNICAL  UNIVERSITY OF DENMARK, DEPARTMENT OF CHEMICAL ENGINEERING,
       LYNGBY (DK)
Bibliogr reference    :ARTICLE: JOURNAL OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (1992) NO. 29
        PP. 405-425
Abstract              :In this paper, a simple and transparent consequence
       model for chlorine and ammonia is proposed based on a fatality index.
       The  parameters  for  the  model  can  be  estimated  from historical
       accident  data and avoid the large number of assumptions necessary in
       traditional models. This approach was attempted for two values of the
       exponent of the mass (0.75 and 1.0), from which a simple linear model
       (with  exponent  1.0)  is  proposed.  This estimates consequences for
       three  different  population  density  classes: rural, semi-urban (or
       industrial)  and  urban. The distribution of the number of fatalities
       relative  to  the estimated average number of fatalities was found to
       approach  an  S-shaped  distribution  function. A simple distribution
       function gives, however, results comparable to the more complex form.
       For  the  particular  case of assessing the risk of transportation of
       chlorine  by  rail  in  the USA, the fatality index model seems to be
       less  conservative  and  closer  to  empirical  observations than the
       traditional models.
Facet codes           :312 Safety engineering
       706 Mathematical models
Availability in lang  :en English
Publication year      :1992
Publication type      :ART An article in a journal
Euroabstracts number  :EAB130151900
Subject index codes   :SAF (SAFETY)
       MST (MATHEMATICS, STATISTICS)
 
            --------------------------------------------------
 
 
