<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ADAPTATION OF SMALL GRINDING MILLS TO DIRECT HEATING
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199111163
Quality valid. date   :1994-12-02
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :ADAPTATION OF SMALL GRINDING MILLS TO DIRECT HEATING
Original title        :ADAPTATION DES PETITS BROYEURS  LA CHAUFFE DIRECTE
Note                  :RAPPORT FINAL
Author                :INERIS
Affiliation           :INERIS, PARIS (FR)
Bibliogr reference    :EUR 13587 FR (1991) 106 PP., MF, ECU 8, BLOW-UP COPY
       ECU   13.75   OFFICE   FOR  OFFICIAL  PUBLICATIONS  OF  THE  EUROPEAN
       COMMUNITIES, L-2985 LUXEMBOURG
Abstract              :In this study the emphasis was placed on direct
       heating  combustion tests in the CERCHAR flame study furnace, as well
       as  on  a  fire-tube  boiler.  Previously, a test bench was set up to
       receive   different   grinding   mills  and  carry  out  the  various
       measurements  required  for  the study. The aim of this project is to
       lay  down  the  various  methods  to  be  followed to adapt the small
       grinding   mills   to  direct  heating  by  establishing  a  schedule
       specifying  the  characteristics of these materials. By means of this
       test bench it was possible to determine the behaviour during grinding
       and  combustion  by  direct  heating  of two small attrition grinding
       mills  which may be equipped with selectors, and to conclude that the
       choice  of  a  grinding  mill  cannot  be  made  without  taking into
       consideration the characteristics of the burner.
Facet codes           :410 Coal research, general and miscellaneous
Availability in lang  :fr French
Publication year      :1991
Publication type      :EUR A report issued by the Commission as an EUR
       report      and      identified      by      its      EUR      number
Euroabstracts number  :EAB13017600
Subject index codes   :FFU (FOSSIL FUELS)
 
            --------------------------------------------------
 
 
</PRE>
