<TITLE>
ACCIDENTS AND NON-RANDOM ERROR PROPAGATION
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :198910133
Quality valid. date   :1994-12-01
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :ACCIDENTS AND NON-RANDOM ERROR PROPAGATION
Author                :TURNER B A
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA ESTAB. (IT)
Bibliogr reference    :PAPER PRESENTED: SRA CONFERENCE ON UTILITY OF RISK
       ANALYSIS  IN  DECISION  MAKING,  LAXENBURG  (AT),  NOV.  10-11,  1988
       AVAILABLE  FROM EUROPEAN COMMISSION, DGXIII/D-2, L-2920 LUXEMBOURG AS
       PAPER EN 34356 ORA
Abstract              :Although accidents are frequently associated with
       randomness, the impact and effects of accidents are not random.
       Errors  or  'corruptions  of  intent'  generate  chains of structured
       events within the socio-technical system in which they are generated,
       following the axiom that 'errors make non-random use of the structure
       of  the  system  in which they occur'. The patterned response is thus
       constrained  by  pre-existing  features  of  the system, although the
       precise  form  of response will depend upon the relative strengths of
       the   system  structure  and  the  disruptive  chain.  The  model  of
       'socio-technical   system   structure/error/system  intervention'  is
       discussed  and  illustrated  in  connection  with a fire in a railway
       sleeping car at Taunton, England, in 1978.
Facet codes           :007 Safety
