<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
HYDROGEN, AN ENERGY VECTOR FOR SOLAR ENERGY
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199011182
Quality valid. date   :1994-12-01
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :HYDROGEN, AN ENERGY VECTOR FOR SOLAR ENERGY
Author                :GRETZ J
       WINTER C-J
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA (IT)
       DFVLR, STUTTGART (DE)
Bibliogr reference    :PAPER PRESENTED: WORLD ENERGY CONFERENCE, MONTREAL
       (CA),  SEPTEMBER  17-24,  1989  AVAILABLE  FROM  EUROPEAN COMMISSION,
       DGXIII/D-2,    L-2920    LUXEMBOURG    AS    PAPER   EN   35530   ORA
Abstract              :The intermittence and the geographical distribution
       of solar energy require it to be stored and transported to the user.
       An  ideal  means  of  doing this is to split water in order to obtain
       hydrogen,  a  carbon-free  fuel which oxidises to water as combustion
       product  in  a  carbon-free,  natural  cycle.  Hydrogen  can  then be
       transported  from  solar energy rich countries over long distances by
       ship  to  Europe,  stored  underground  or  in containers and used in
       gaseous  or  liquid  form  in  industry, by household users, in power
       stations,  in  motor  cars  and  for aviation fuel. Solar energy as a
       primary  energy  source is discussed, and in particular the cheapest,
       and  by now widely available form, hydropower. Techniques of hydrogen
       production, vectorisation and end use are discussed as well as safety
       aspects,  costs and strategy for its implementation. Three main pilot
       projects/programmes are described.
