<HEAD>
<TITLE>
ON THE SOCIAL ACCEPTABILITY OF INHERENTLY SAFE
TECHNOLOGIES
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :198911063
Quality valid. date   :1994-12-01
Update date           :1996-01-20
Title in english      :ON THE SOCIAL ACCEPTABILITY OF INHERENTLY SAFE
       TECHNOLOGIES
Author                :OTWAY H
       HAASTRUP P
Affiliation           :JRC ISPRA ESTAB., 21020 ISPRA (VA) (IT)
       JRC ISPRA ESTAB., 21020 ISPRA (VA) (IT)
Bibliogr reference    :ARTICLE: IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON ENGINEERING MANAGEMENT,
       VOL. 36 (1989), NO. 1, PP. 57-60
Abstract              :Some technologies have encountered public opposition
       which has delayed their implementation or even blocked it completely.
       Inherently  safer  technologies  are valuable as a means of improving
       safety,  but research on public perceptions of hazardous technologies
       suggests that safety is only loosely coupled to social acceptability.
       It  is  concluded  that  the  notion  of  inherent  safety  does  not
       necessarily  make  technologies  more acceptable. It is proposed that
       the  inherent  safety  concept  be extended to embrace procedural and
       institutional  innovations  that  involve  lay  and  expert groups in
       decision making and improve communications between the two groups.
Facet codes           :006 Social sciences
       007 Safety
Availability in lang  :en English
Publication year      :1989
Publication type      :ART An article in a journal
Euroabstracts number  :EAB12793600
Programme acronym     :JRC-INDHAZ 2C
Reference to project  :JRC-INDHAZ 2C
Commission service    :JRC
Subject index codes   :SOC (SOCIAL ASPECTS)
       SAF (SAFETY)
 
