<HEAD>
<TITLE>
KINETICS IN SEVERE REACTOR ACCIDENTS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number   :199511397
Quality valid. date   :1995-10-31
Update date           :1996-01-19
Title in english      :KINETICS IN SEVERE REACTOR ACCIDENTS
Note                  :NOTE OF THE THIRD MEETING OF THE EUROPEAN SEVERE
       ACCIDENT   CHEMISTRY   GROUP,   JRC   KARLSRUHE,   JUNE  16-17,  1992
Author                :BENSON C G
Affiliation           :JRC KARLSRUHE (DE)
Bibliogr reference    :EUR 15056 EN (1993) 20 PP., FS, FREE OF CHARGE
       AVAILABLE FROM JOINT RESEARCH CENTRE, PUBLICATION DEPARTMENT, I-21020
       ISPRA (VA.) (IT)
Abstract              :The third meeting of the European Severe Accident
       Chemistry Group (ESACG) was held on the subject of kinetics in severe
       reactor  accidents.  There  were  a  number  of presentations on fuel
       release and primary circuit kinetics. Various experimental programmes
       on  fission  product  release  and transport were described, together
       with  modelling  studies  using  the MITRA, FUTURE, FPREKI and FPCHEM
       codes.   The   results   from   the  latter  clearly  show  that  the
       instantaneous  equilibrium  assumption  used by thermochemistry-based
       codes  needs  to  be  validated.  Experimental  programmes on primary
       circuit  reaction  kinetics were presented. The results from the AEA,
       Winfrith Technology Centre programme show that it is unlikely that an
       accident  situation could arise where reaction rates could be limited
       by passivation of the surface (i.e. parabolic reaction kinetics), and
       mass  transfer  effects  (i.e.  linear  reaction  kinetics) were more
       likely to have an effect and prevent the attainment of equilibrium.
       However,  quantification  of mass transfer rules was difficult due to
       inadequacies   in  gas  diffusivity  data.  The  DEVAP  programme  of
       experiments  was  shown  to  have  the  potential  for producing very
       important   separate-effects   data,   that   may   be   useful   for
       interpretation of the forthcoming Phebus-FP programme.
Facet codes           :816 Reactor physics
       818 Reactor safety
Availability in lang  :en English
Publication year      :1993
Publication type      :EUR A report issued by the Commission as an EUR
       report      and      identified      by      its      EUR      number
Euroabstracts number  :EAB13415200
Subject index codes   :FIS (NUCLEAR FISSION)
       SAF (SAFETY)
 
            --------------------------------------------------
 
 
</PRE>
