<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Behaviour of low level radioactive waste under fire accident conditions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :27222
Quality valid. date    :1995-03-23
Key words              : Transport, fire, accident, radioative waste
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Behaviour of low level radioactive waste under fire
                        accident conditions
Subject index codes    :RWA (RADIOACTIVE WASTE)

General information    :It  is  likely  that  low  level  radioactive 
waste (LLW) will be transported and  stored,  either  uncompacted  or 
supercompacted, without immobilisation. In view of the  high  volumes
and the presence of highly combustible materials, it is necessary  to
provide input data for probabilistic safety assessments for transport
and  operations at a epository. The  proposed  project  will  provide 
information on the behaviour of  LLW  under fire accident conditions,
and on the releases of radioactivity  that  could  occur  under  such 
conditions. Small scale studies will be  made of  typical  individual 
components  of  low  level waste streams, to quantify the releases of
radioactive material. Illustrative mixed waste compositions will then
be studied in active experiments.Temperatures of 1000 degrees C  will
generally be used.  Some  experiments  will  be  conducted  at  lower 
temperatures.  Uncompacted  and  supercompacted wastes will be  used.
Large scale fire tests will also be made using  simulated  (inactive)
mixed waste formulations. The waste formulations will be selected  to
correspond  to  the  worst  cases of activity releases  identified in
the small  scale  experiments.  The  waste containers  will be  fully
instrumented for the analysis of released  volatile  and  particulate
material, and for measurement of temperature profiles throughout  the
waste. The internal temperatures reached will be  used  in  designing 
small scale tests at lower temperatures. Uncompacted and supercompac-
ted wastes will be used. The data will cover a wide  range  of  waste 
materials, radionuclides and conditions. This will  provide  a  basis
for the estimation of activity releases under conditions  other  than
those studied. Co-ordination of the project will be undertaken by  UK
Nirex Ltd. Nirex  will  bring  to  the  project the perspective  of a 
user of the information, particularly with respect to accidents  that
may occur during  transport  and  at the repository. The experimental
programme will be carried out by AEA technology at two of their  ope-
rating sites large scale tests will  be  conducted  at  the  Winfrith
Technology  Centre using the pool fire  test  facility.  Small  scale 
active tests will be conducted in the radiochemical facilities at the
Harwell Laboratory.
The  project  will  be based on previous work (on the fire testing of
intermediate level waste), carried out by the  same  organisation  on
behalf of the Commission. The results will be useful  throughout  the
Community  in planning  and  implementing  the  safe  and  efficient 
management of radioactive waste.

Start date             :1991-10-01
End date               :1994-03-31
Duration in months     :30
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :RADWASTOM 4C
Project reference      :FI2W0014
Prime contr org        :United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority
Prime contr dept       :Winfrith Technology Centre
                        Radwaste Treatment Division
Prime contr postcode   :DT2 8DH
Prime contr town       :Dorchester
Prime contr region     :R7631 Dorset
Prime contr country    :GB (UNITED KINGDOM)
Contact person         :Name:         BUSH, R P (Dr)
 
            --------------------------------------------------
</PRE>
</BODY>
