<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Scientific Model Evaluation of Dense Gas Dispersion Models
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :31876
Quality valid. date    :1996-06-24
Update date            :1996-07-13
Title                  :Scientific Model Evaluation of Dense Gas Dispersion
       Models
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
       MET (METEOROLOGY)
       SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :It is proposed to carry out a Scientific Model
       Evaluation  (SME)  of  dense qas dispersion (DGD) models currently in
       use throughout Europe.
       Any  mathematical  representation of the complex processes associated
       with the dispersion of dense gases in the atmospheric boundary layer,
       including  the  effects  of aerosols, obstacles and variable terrain,
       involves  making  assumptions  and usually the representation is only
       valid  over  a  limited  parameter  range. Questions then immediately
       arise  as  to  the  suitability  of  a DGD model to a particular flow
       scenario. Are the relevant physical processes included and, if so, is
       the representation correct? Are the approximations reasonable? Is the
       parameter  range  appropriate?  Has the model been validated, and for
       what conditions?
       An  SHE  is  an  objective  measure  of whetber a particular model is
       suitable for the particular use made of it.
       The specific objectives of this proposal are;
       (i) to develop further and test a protocol for an SME of DGD models,
       (ii)  to  carry out an SME of all current DGD nodels in Europe, using
       this  protocol  with  particular  emphasis  on the complex effects of
       aerosol      formation     complex     terrain     and     obstacles,
       (iii) to leave in place a methodology for Scientific Model Evaluation

       The  structure  of  the  consortium  is  designed  to  achieve  these
       objectives  efficiently.  The  three main partners have the followinq
       responsibilities.  HSE  will coordinate the project, EDF and HSE will
       coordinate the DGD model tests and CERC will carry out the Scientific
       Model  Evaluation. The associated partners, representing institutions
       from  nine  European  countries and thereby having access to most DGD
       models  currently  in  use  throughout  Europe,  will  run models. An
       invitation  will  be  extended  to any European DGD udel developer to
       bave tbeir nodel evaluated by tbe consortium.
       To  achieve objective (i), CERC will adapt current SHE protocols from
       the  CEC  Hodel  Evaluation Group, the CEC project REDIPHEM and their
       own  experience.  Objective  (ii) will involve both an 'active' and a
       'passive'   approach.  The  latter  uses  all  information  currently
       available  about DGD models, while the 'active' approach will use new
       information  obtained  from  'definitive' runs of the models. EDF and
       HSE  will  coordinate the running of the models and the collection of
       all  information  in  a  common  format.  Hodels will be run by model
       developers;  the consortium will agree the 'definitive' tests and the
       rules  for  running  models  so  that  objective  information will be
       obtained.  A published form of the SHEs and the protocol will achieve
       objectives  (ii)  and  (iii).  The  process  of  SHE  is an essential
       ingredient of the transfer of technology from research into technical
       use  of  models.  This proposal enables that transfer to occur and to
       provide  an  assessment  of the effectiveness of current European DGD
       models.
       KEYWORDS
       Scientific Model Evaluation, Dense Gas Dispersion,
       Aerosols, Obstacles, Complex Terrain
Start date             :1996-06-01
End date               :1999-05-31
Duration in months     :36
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 2C
Project reference      :ENV4960245
