<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Dispersion studies of high pressure jets impacting on to flat plates
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Key words              : LPG, dispersion, jet release, modelling, explosion, 
Record cntrl number    :23973
Quality valid. date    :1995-02-22
Update date            :1995-08-28
Title                  :Dispersion studies of high pressure jets impacting
                        on to flat plates
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :Natural gas is transported at high pressure
throughout the European Community and much experimental and modelling
work  has  been  undertaken  to  enable assessments to be made of the
consequences of an accidental release of gas.
One  potential consequence of a loss of containment is the release of
pressurised  gas  into  a  confined  environment.  Whereas  there  is 
extensive data available on the  dispersion  of  free  jet  releases, 
there is little experimental workor modelling available to assist  in
characterising an unignited  impeded  release.  An  impeded  release, 
particularly onto a flat surface, will result in  a  flammable  cloud 
quickly  spreading out along the impinged surface presenting  a  risk 
of ignition leading to a fire or explosion. Releases  in  a  confined
environment  present  an  even greater hazard. The  present  proposal
seeks  to rectify the lack of data on impeded releases  by  providing
experimental data,obtained at both large scale and  in a  windtunnel, 
which is accurate and reliable and which can be  used to  validate  a 
predictive computer model which will be developed.
Validation  at  both  experimental scales willlead to confidence that
the  model  predictions  can  be  applied  over  the wide  range   of
conditions and release sizes of practical interest.  The  study  will 
also improve the understanding of the physical mechanisms involved in 
impacting jet dispersion.By sponsoring this project, all  members  of
the EC will benefit through  he  provision  of  validated  predictive
methods capable of providing realistic  estimates of  the  dispersion
of such gas escapes, and hence through the safer design and operation
of  industrial  plant.  The  work  proposed  is   also   sufficiently
fundamental to be of value  to  a  number  of  other  safety  related
problems.

Start date             :1994-09-01
End date               :1996-08-31
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0534
Prime contr org        :British Gas PLC
Prime Organization Type:IND Industry
Prime contr dept       :Gas Research Centre
