<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Uncertainty in modelling of major industrial hazards
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :27180
Quality valid. date    :1995-06-14
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Uncertainty in modelling of major industrial  hazards
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :The consequences of major industrial accidents
involving  releases  of  toxic  and  hazardous gases are increasingly
being analysed using computational fluid dynamics (CFD) techniques.
The problem of near-field gas dispersion in the immediate vicinity of
buildings is of great importance when the rate of spread and build-up
of  gas  concentrations  must  be  predicted  for  selected  accident
scenarios.   The   availability  and  capabilities  of  sophisticated
commercial  CFD codes and powerful computlng workstations has enabled
users  to  tackle  increasingly large and complex scenarios. However,
the  validity  of  these  predictions  is generally uncertain for two
important  reasons:  
(i)  the way in which a CFD code is applied to a
specific problem can have a critical impact on the final results;
(ii)  there  is a considerable disparity between the scope of current
model   validation  and  the  complexity  of  the  actual  industrial
scenarios.
The  first  point relates closely to the expertise of the CFD user in
specifying  the 'best possible solution' within the usual constraints
of time, cost and computer resources, while the second aspect relates
to  the  pace  and  direction of current model validation efforts. In
view  of  the  growing  extent  of CFD usage in industry, there is an
urgent  need  for both these aspects to be examined in depth; that is
the aim of this project. The objectives of the proposed programme are
therefore  (within  the  context of typical industrial gas dispersion
scenarios):
(i)  to  quantify the spread in results of CFD predictions due to the
 way in which a CFD code is applied;
(ii)  to  quantify  the validity (ie. accuracy) of CFD predictions in
large, complex gas dispersion situations.
To  achieve  these  objectives,  the  proposed programme of work will
consider  a number of test cases using CFD and wind tunnel modelling,
together with an evaluation of the uncertainty in the CFD predictions
The  research  will  provide better understanding of the accuracy of
CFD  techniques obtained in practice, and hence information on how to
evaluate,  with  greater confidence, the overall quality of modelling
results.
Start date             :1994-07-01
End date               :1996-06-30
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0531
Prime contr org        :WS Atkins Consultants Ltd.
Prime contr dept       :Science and Technology
Prime contr address    :Woodcote Grove, Ashley Road
Prime contr postcode   :KT18 5BW
Prime contr town       :Epsom - Surrey
Prime contr country    :GB (UNITED KINGDOM)
Contact person         :Name:         DEAVES, DAVID
Contact name           :ROBINS, ALAN
Department             :Department Mechanical Engineering
Organization           :University of Surrey
Organization type      :EDU Education
Address                :Stag Hill
City                   :Guildford
Postcode               :GU2 5XH
Region                 :R7532 Surrey
Country                :GB (UNITED KINGDOM)
Contact name           :CARTAGE, THIERRY
Department             :Research and Technology
Organization           :Solvay S.A.
Organization type      :IND Industry
Address                :310 Rue de Ransbeek
City                   :Bruxelles
Postcode               :1120
