<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Vapour Cloud Dispersion and Combustion, 1992-1994
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :17145
Quality valid. date    :1992-12-10
Update date            :1995-10-09
Title                  :Vapour Cloud Dispersion and Combustion, 1992-1994
Subject index codes    :SAF (SAFETY)
Objectives             :Development and further improvement of computer
models   describing  dispersion  of  denser-than-air vapour clouds in
irregular terrains with obstacles.
Development   of  advanced  numerical  tools  which  simulate  multi-
component,  multidimensional gas flows undergoing chemical reactions,
and which describe detonation and deflagration processes.
General information    :Progress to end 1991
Shallow layer model for vapour cloud dispersion
Development  of  a  1-D shallow layer model describing a 3-D cloud by
integration  over  the cloud height and width. Conservation equations
for mass, energy, lateral and longitudinal momemtum for the cloud and
for  the  mass  of  the dense gas are solved implicity. The turbulent
mixing   is  described  by  the  entrainment  velocity  concept.  The
programme is in test phase and  validation with wind tunnel and field
test data has been initiated.
3-D Model
The  3-D  code  ADREA-HF has been implemented at the JRC. It allows a
detailed  description  of  the  interactions  between  the  cloud and
atmosphere  by  means  of a one-equation turbulence closure model and
describes  the effects of obstacles and complex terrain. The code has
been  improved  by  introducing new turbulence models and a two-phase
flow  capability. Code validation for single-phase has been initiated
applying the Thorney Island field test data.
Advanced "reacting gas flow" computer code
A  pilot  version  of a computer code was developed for the numerical
simulation of two-dimensional  multicomponent reactive transonic flow
Much  attention  has  been  given  to  the  selectin  of appropriate
numerical  solution  strategy  which  allows the accurate tracking of
flow  discontinuities.   The  use  of unstructed grids allows a large
flexibility to represent complex geometrical boundaries.  Confined as
well  as  external  flows  with  obstacles  can  be  described.   The
numerical  results  obtained  so far demonstrate the superioty of the
concept chosen over standard numerical techniques.
Fast  and  effective  techniques  have  been  designed  to  solve the
chemical  kinetics  equation  and  allow  coupling  of  this  set  of
equations with the fluid dynamics solver.
A preliminary implementation of a parabolic solver has been performed
for  the  simulation  of  diffusion  processes  (viscous shear, heat
conduction, species diffusion).
Valorisation
The  shallow  layer  model for dense vapour dispersion is intended to
become  a  substitute  for  the  "box" - models with a more realistic
physical modelling.
The  dispersion code ADREA-HF is expected to become a useful tool for
to  design of accident mitigation devices in view of its capabilities
to handle two-phase situations and to describe effects of obstacles.
For the reacting gas computer code the two major applications areas are :
- safety studies where detonation processes are of major concern : 
e.g. combustion of vapour clouds, flame front and detonation/blast wave
propagation in industrial environment,
-  optimisation  of  combustion process with respect to energy saving
and reduction of pollutant emissions, e.g. NOx.
External Collaboration
The  work  on  vapour cloud dispersion is carried out in frame of the
collaboration contract with the Demokritos Research Centre in Athens,
and  is  closely  associated with the CEC Shared Cost Action Activity
FLADIS  (Research  on  the dispersion of Two-Phase Flashing Releases)
under  the STEP programme.  A collaboration is planned with two other
research  institutes  involved  in  STEP (University of Cambridge and
Risoe National Laboratory) in order to combine the efforts on shallow
layer modelling.
Detailed description of work foreseen in 1992 (expected results)
Shallow layer model for vapour cloud dispersion
The work will focus on:
a) Implementation of different entrainment models, (b) Validation of
the  code  by  making comparisons with laboratory and field test data
with  obstacles  (Thorney  Island,  STEP),  (c)  Completion  of  user
documentation, (d) Inclusion of an interface in view of a development
of a user-friendly input and output processor.
3-D vapour cloud dispersion code ADREA-HF
This  work  is  closely  related to the FLADIS project under STEP and
regards  mainly: (a) Comparative studies between ADREA-HF, MERCURE-GL
(EDF  and  GDF),  and  the  shallow  layer  model, (b) Assessment and
possible  improvement  of the existing two-phase model for describing
droplet fallout.
Advanced "reacting gas flow "computer code
The  two  major tasks foreseen for this period are: (a) the selection
and  implementation  of  turbulence  models for compressible reactive
flows  (collaboration  foreseen with CEA/DAM limeil Valenton Research
Centre), (b) the implementation of implicit flow solvers, (c) further
improvements  and  extension  of  prediction  capabilities  based  on
experience with industrial application.
Short description of evolution of work in 1993
Vapour cloud dispersion
A  2-D  extension  for the shallow layer model, where variations over
the  width  of the layer is calculated. Extension of the capabilities
of  the  ADREA-HF code to quantify mitigation effects associated with
water curtains.
Advanced "reacting gas flow" computer code
Extensions envisaged at present concern:
. introduction of a dispersed phase (gas/reactive particles flow)
. adaptative grid management
.  design and implementation of algorithms for three dimensional flow
. predictions (unstructured grid based on tetrahedra).
Acquisition of adequate informatic tools for data processing.
Start date             :1992-01-01
End date               :1994-12-31
Duration in months     :36
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :INDHAZ 3C
Project reference      :0004
Prime contr org        :Joint Research Centre Ispra
Prime contr dept       :Institute for Safety Technology
Prime contr address    :Sito di Ispra
Prime contr postcode   :21020
Prime contr town       :ISPRA
Prime contr region     :R3201 Varese
Prime contr country    :IT (ITALY)
Contact person         :Name:         NIJSING R.
                    Tel:          +39-332-7889306
                    Fax:          +39-332-789001
                  Telex:        380042 EUR I
 
            --------------------------------------------------
</PRE>
</BODY>
