<HEAD>
<TITLE>
EFFICIENT DRYING OF BYPRODUCT IN STARCH PRODUCTION
FROM WHEAT 
</TITLE>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Key words              :Starch production, explosion, dust explosion, 
                        evaporator
Record cntrl number    :23417
Quality valid. date    :1995-01-24
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :EFFICIENT DRYING OF BYPRODUCT IN STARCH PRODUCTION
FROM WHEAT
Subject index codes    :ESV (ENERGY SAVING)
                        FFU (FOSSIL FUELS)
                        RSE (RENEWABLE SOURCES OF ENERGY)
Other indexes          :ENERGY (PHYSICS)
                        ENERGY CONSUMPTION
                        ENERGY CONSERVATION
                        INDUSTRIAL SECTOR
                        HEAT RECOVERY
                        DRYING
                        INDUSTRIAL PROCESSES
                        VAPOURS
                        HEAT TRANSFER
                        HEAT EXCHANGERS

Drying of by-products form the wheat starch production with an indirect 
steam drying for the finished by-products with a volume of 140,000 t per 
year (based on 88% dry substance), the evaporation will be about 100,000 t 
per year. The finished product will be sold as feed to the naimal feed 
industries.The main innovative part of the project is that the drying 
happens without any air, so that normally existing energy losses due to air 
outblow to the environment do not occur. In addition to this advanatge due 
to the airless drying the reuse of the vapours in a 3-stage evaporator will 
be possible so that a further reduction in steam consumption is expected. 
In total the airless drying will reduce the energy consumption eliminates 
the fire and explosion risk and will also eliminate the odours caused by 
dryers in the wheat and corn starch industry.

This project is part of a complete new wheat starch production plant in 
Barby in the Eastern part of Germany. At Barby, 1200 t of wheat are milled 
each day on a four-shift system, equaling to an annual capacity of more 
than 400,000 t and an wheat producing area of around 80,000 ha.The bran 
from the wheat mill will be mixed with the fibre, pentosanes and evaporated 
soluble parts from the wet process. This mixture will feed the new dryer. 
Including the moisture a total volume of 19.2 t/hour have to be dried. The 
dryer evaporates 12.5 t per hour, the finished product has a volume of 16,6 
t per hour.Behind the drying process a cooling system will be installed. 
Due to the new drying technology, drying in an airless area, now the 
possibility exists to reuse the vapour in an efficient way. The temperature 
of the vapour is 100 deg. C , at this temperature a further economic use in 
evaporators or heat-exchangers is given.The new dryer has four rotating 
bundles which are stacked above each other in a common housing. These 
rotating bundles can be operated independently form each other. Each bundle 
has his own electric drive. The heating tubes in the upper bundles are 
spaced wider apart than in the lower ones, due to the poor flow ability of 
the humid feed entering the drying process. This also results in a smaller 
heating area of the upper bundles. The larger heating area of the lower
bundles results in a better water evaporation of the remaining fixed
water molecules in the product.The heat transfer surface of the tube 
bundles is heated with 15 bar(absolute) steam, corresponding to 198 deg. C. 
The steam enters the tube bundle through an axial central tube to the end 
of the bundle, where the steam is distributed over the individual tubes. At 
the other end a water scoop collects the condensate and leads it into a 
condensate draining pipe. Steam supply and condensate removal occur at the 
same side of the tube bundle via a "Maier"- or "Johnson" head (1 per 
bundle). The amount of steam required for the drying process is controlled 
by a pressure regulator. The product takes out the steam, steam condenses 
and the pressure drops. The pressure regulator reacts by opening the valve 
and more steam flows through the tubes. The more steam required, the more 
water evaporation from the product. Flow and temperature of the steam are 
continuously recorded.

Start date             :1992-01-01
End date               :1994-03-31
Duration in months     :27
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :THERMIE 1
Subprogramme area      :ENERGY SAVING - INDUSTRY
Project reference      :IN./01043/91/DE/..
Prime contr org        :CERESTAR DEUTSCHLAND GMBH
Prime contr address    :GEORG MARSHALL STRASSE 210
Prime contr postcode   :47747
Prime contr town       :KREFELD
Prime contr region     :R1514 Krefeld, krfr.St.
Prime contr country    :DE (GERMANY FEDERAL REP.)
Contact person         :Name:         KUETTNER ALBERT
                    Tel:          +49-2151-575340
                    Fax:          +49-2151-572583
PAR   :
Organization           :WILHELM SCHULZ GMBH
 
            --------------------------------------------------
</PRE>
</BODY>
