<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Safe handling of renewable fuels and fuel mixtures
</TITLE>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :30634
Quality valid. date    :1996-04-01
Update date            :1996-04-15
Title                  :Safe handling of renewable fuels and fuel mixtures
Subject index codes    :FFU (FOSSIL FUELS)
       RSE (RENEWABLE SOURCES OF ENERGY)
       ESV (ENERGY SAVING)
General information    :The objective of this research project is to create
       new  data on the safety-technical characteristics of renewable fuels,
       wastes,  low-rank  coals and mixtures of these. The safety aspects of
       fuel  storage,  handling  and  feeding  are an important issue in the
       development of new energy production technologies. Knowledge of basic
       handling  and  safety-technical  characteristics  of  fuels  and fuel
       mixtures  is  of  crucial significance for the design of handling and
       feeding  equipment,  for  the  design  of  safety systems and for the
       assessment of explosion and fire hazards.
       The main technical objectives of the study are:
       - to characterise the selected fuels and fuel mixtures with regard to
       their safety-technical characteristics
       -  to  create  a  criterion  based  on  simple analyses to assess the
       reactivity  of  the  fuels  with  regard  to  their  safety-technical
       properties
       -  to  study the spontaneous ignition behaviour of these fuels and to
       assess the necessary preventive actions in various ambient conditions
       -  to  determine  the  explosion characteristics of the most critical
       dusts  in  both  normal  conditions  and  at  elevated  pressure  and
       temperature
       -  to  experimentally  verify  explosion-prevention  concepts in both
       ambient and elevated conditions.
       The  work  will  be  carried  out  in close co-operation between five
       partners:  VTT Energy (FI) (co-ordinator), LOM (ES), INERIS (FR), TNO
       (NL) and DMT-IRB (DE). The partners possess a unique set of equipment
       within  EC with regard to experimental research on dust explosion and
       self-ignition  characteristics.  Selected materials, woody biomasses,
       agrofuels,  low-rank  coals and mixtures of these will chemically and
       physically analysed. The analyses will also include thermal analyses,
       flammability   and   explosibility  determinations.  The  spontaneous
       ignition  behaviour of these fuels will be studied in atmospheric and
       elevated (1-40 bar) pressure. The required safe level of inertisation
       to  inhit  self-ignition  in  fuel  handling and storage will also be
       determined.  Tests  will  be carried out with several sample sizes to
       facilitate the extrapolation of the results to large bin sizes and to
       evaluate  the  time  of ignition. Dust explosion tests methodology is
       developed  to enable repeatable and comparable testing of "difficult"
       biomass dust. Tests are performed in 20 litre sphere and 1 m3 vessels
       to determine the explosion indices and the safe level of inertisation
       in atmospheric conditions as well as elevated pressure (1-15 bar) and
       temperature  (20-200   degrees  C).  The  application  of a explosion
       suppression  system will be studied in elevated conditions and partly
       inert atmosphere.
Start date             :1996-01-01
End date               :1997-12-31
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :JOULE/THERMIE
Project reference      :JOR3950032
Prime contr org        :Technical Research Centre of Finland
Prime Organization Type:ROR Research
Prime contr dept       :Energy Gasification Research Group
Prime contr address    :PO Box 1601
Prime contr postcode   :02044
Prime contr town       :Espoo
Prime contr region     :FIU Uusimaa
Prime contr country    :FI (FINLAND)
Contact person         :Name:         WILEN, Carl
    PAR   :
           Contact name           :TIMMERS, Petrus Gerardus Joha
           Department             :TNO Prins Maurits Laboratorium
