<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Extended modelling and experimental research into gas explosions
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Key words              :Explosion, gas explosion, modelling, large-scale 
                        explosion
Record cntrl number    :6224
Quality valid. date    :1995-03-06
Update date            :1995-08-11
Project acronym        :EMERGE
Title                  :Extended modelling and experimental research into 
                        gas explosions
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)

Background: Major industrial explosions can have a large impact on public 
life and the environment. To improve safety it is necessary that industrial 
hazard engineers have an effective consequence assessment technology. 
Predictive techniques are used by plant designers for evaluating the 
consequences of explosions. The safe design of plant relies upon such 
techniques to provide an accurate description of the loading that 
explosions can impart in full-scale realistic scenarios.Recent independent 
reviews have concluded that explosion science is insufficiently mature, 
when compared to that of gas dispersion and structural response. This 
unsatisfactory situation must therefore be rectified. The current CEC MERGE 
programme is taking an initial step toward this end. The work to date has 
identified new and important areas which need to be addressed which form 
the basis of this proposal.
Objectives: To increase confidence in the use of the 3 principal
explosion predictive techniques by both improving and evaluating their 
accuracy and applicability:

1) Experimental scaling techniques which provide the most practicable
   means of studying large-scale explosions in small-scale rigs. 
2) Simple theoretical models for routine use by hazard engineers.
3) Models based on Computational Fluid Dynamics which provide the most 
   practicable method for extrapolating from experiment to full-scale 
   scenarios.

To extend the existing data set of properly instrumented realistic large-
scale experiments to fill out areas which are presently deficient. These 
data are essential in order to achieve proper model validation. To provide 
a substantial extension to the existing, and presently inadequate, 
fundamental data set. These data are essential to enable the accuracy of 
the underlying sub-models to be evaluated and improvements developed.
(Co-operation: This project involves all of the groups in Europe who are 
leading research into vapour cloud explosions. The complementary approaches 
in the proposed theoretical and experimental research at both practical and 
fundamental levels provides a balanced and integrated research programme 
which can build upon the experience,information and working relationships 
currently being developed under CEC project MERGE.

Start date             :1994-01-01
End date               :1995-12-31
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0274
Prime contr org        :Nederlandse Organisatie voor Toegepast
                        Natuurwetenschappelijk Onderzoek
