<HEAD>
<TITLE>
The effect of dust explosion pressures on industrial plant, buildings work areas, public places and environment 
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Key words: Explosion, dust explosion, explosion pressure, venting, modelling, pressure blast, fire ball size
Record cntrl number    :5176
Quality valid. date    :1995-03-06
Update date            :1995-08-11
Title                  :The effect of dust explosion pressures on 
                        industrial plant, buildings work areas, public 
                        places and environment
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)

The effect of Dust Explosion pressures on Industrial plant, Buildings Work 
Areas, public Areas and Environment Widespread concern has been expressed 
bY industry and regulatory authorities at the environmental problems 
associated With, and the high industrial cost of, dust explosions. Because 
of the unsatisfactory state of knowledge on dust explosion technology and 
the means of controlling and eliminating hazard from this source, European 
industry and research institutes, under the aegis of the International 
Explosion Liaison Group and the British Materials Handling Board, have 
produced four co-ordinated research programmes,involving all interested 
industrial and research bodies. This activity has enabled proposals to be 
formulated that meet the requirements of industry, maximise the use of 
existing Facilities and prevent the duplication of effort in terms of 
equipment and manpower. Research topics have been structured to provide the 
information that will enable powder handling operations to be designed to 
be more intrinsically safe and lead to explosion protection systems less 
likely to result in extensive damage to external buildings and public areas 
or to cause noxious substances to be emitted into the general atmosphere to 
harm the environment. An important technique used to protect plants from 
dust explosion hazards is the provision of explosion vents. However, When a 
vent operates, flame, pressure Waves and noxious substances are discharged 
into surrounding areas, presenting serious damage problems to adjacent 
plant, people and the environment. To overcome these problems the following 
key topics are to be studied: 

(a)  Modelling of pressure Blast Effects and Fireball Sizes
     from Vented Dust Explosions
(b)  Measurement  of  pressure  Blast Effects and Fireball Sizes from
     Vented Dust Explosions
(c)  Determining the strengths of buildings and structures to the
     transient pressures produced bY a dust explosion.

An important feature is the combining of modelling studies With large
scale tests on realistic structures to develop guidelines that can be
used to site safely explosion vented installations.

Start date             :1993-01-01
End date               :1994-12-31
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0082
Prime contr org        :British Materials Handling Board
