<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Fire Detection and Suppression Simulation
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :30957
Quality valid. date    :1996-04-01
Update date            :1996-04-15
Title                  :Fire Detection and Suppression Simulation
Subject index codes    :AER (AEROSPACE TECHNOLOGY)
       IND (INDUSTRIAL MANUFACTURE)
       MAT (MATERIALS TECHNOLOGY)
General information    :The ban of production of Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs)
       means  that  alternative  methods  must  be  considered for effective
       suppression  and  extinguishment  of  fires in those applications for
       which  CFCs  (including  halon) are presently the only solution. This
       programme  has  been proposed to ensure continued European commitment
       to  the safety of potential halon replacement systems. Investigations
       are  ongoing  to  find  a  replacement  agent  for halon. Water mist,
       alternative  gases and powders are all being considered. All of these
       potential replacements are significantly different in their operation
       and  behaviour to halon based systems. Current Fire Detection systems
       in  aircraft are quite basic in their operation and present one major
       drawback.  An  estimated  95% of all reported warnings are false, and
       these  warnings  have  a  direct effect on the operational cost of an
       aircraft. This proposed research programme investigates both problems
       of  a  replacement agent for halon, and a more reliable and effective
       detection  and  control system. This proposal describes an innovative
       approach  to  obtaining  an  environmentally friendly, cost effective
       replacement   of   halon   based   systems   by   understanding   the
       characteristics  of  such  fire  hazards,  development of appropriate
       software  models  and by validating the models using actual fire test
       facilities.  The  proposal  concentrates  on  water mist as the agent
       since  it  is cheap, environmentally friendly and requires no special
       handling  for  use.  An  analysis of the test results will enable the
       design  of  an  improved control and detection system to be performed
       which  will  be  capable  of  using  the  agent  more effectively and
       economically, and thus containing the fire without a major release of
       the  agent.  In addition, certification of fire detection systems are
       both  costly  and  time  consuming because of the numerous fire tests
       required.  One  benefit  envisaged  from  this  programme  will  be a
       software  modelling  tool  which  will  assist  both industry and the
       authorities in certifying detection systems. This will allow for more
       timely certification at reduced costs to industry.
       The  software  models to be developed and validated will comprise the
       following:
       -  A  fire  model  capable  of  predicting the spread of fire hazards
       throughout  the  atmosphere of a forced ventilated enclosure, subject
       to a fire of prescribed characteristics.
       -  A  model  which  predicts  the activation of fire sensors within a
       forced ventilated enclosure.
       - A water mist/fire atmosphere interaction model.
       - A fire suppression model
       This   suite   of  software  models  will  allow  for  fire  scenario
       predictions  in  various  geometric  environments  and  to be used to
       reduce  design  cycle  of a fire suppression system. Initial research
       has  been  conducted  by  the  members of the Consortium to prove the
       feasibility  of  the  proposed  models and the water mist system. The
       research  activities  for  the  work  programme  provide a structured
       approach and builds on this early work.
       In summary the programme comprises:
       -  Generation  of  requirement  specifications  for  the  generic and
       specific  models,  performance  requirements  specification  for  the
       suppression/detection  system  and  experimental  data to develop and
       verify the models.
       -  Design  and  development  of  software models which will allow the
       simulation   of   various   fire  locations,  fire  growth,  and  the
       interaction  of  the  fire  suppression system and the fire detection
       system
       - Validation of the software models by using the models to optimise a
       fire  suppression  and  detection  system  against  a  specified fire
       scenario.
       A  hardware and software demonstrator of the optimised system will be
       developed  and fire trials conducted to verify the performance of the
       models  and  the  system.  A  full description of each element of the
       research  programme  is provided within the proposal, together with a
       programme schedule.
       Consortium   partners  involvement  in  each  work  package  is  also
       described  with  designated  work  package  managers.  The Consortium
       partners have been very carefully chosen to provide the highest level
       of expertise in areas
       - Software modelling/validation,
       - Fire detection,
       - Water mist suppression systems,
       -  Fire  testing,  to  ensure the views of regulation authorities and
       airline  operators  are considered, and to ensure the benefits of the
       programme  are  available  to  a wide spectrum of European industries
       Composition of the Consortium is described in detail and the benefits
       for  each Consortium partner, as a result of this research programme,
       is provided. The consortium comprises two manufacturers of water mist
       suppression technology, GEC-Marconi Avionics (GB) and Ginge Kerr (GB)
        a  manufacturer of fire detection technology, Cerberus Guinard (FR),
       two fire test facilities, (SINTEF NBL (NO) and DLR (DE), two software
       developers,  University  of  Greenwich  (GB) and University of Athens
       (GR) and a regulatory authority, Civil Aviation Authority (GB).
       Brite/EuRam III Areas covered by the proposal are 3A.5.7, 3B.5.2S and
       3A.1
Start date             :1996-01-01
End date               :1998-12-31
Duration in months     :36
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :BRITE/EURAM 3
Project reference      :BRPR950040
Prime contr org        :Gec-Marconi Avionics
Prime Organization Type:IND Industry
Prime contr dept       :Instrument Systems Division
Prime contr address    :Airport Works
