<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Guidelines for management of fires in chemical warehouses
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :6054
Quality valid. date    :1995-03-06
Key words              :Warehouse, guidelines, accident prevention, fire 
                        protection measures
Update date            :1995-08-11
Project acronym        :TOXFIRE
Title                  :Guidelines for management of fires in chemical
                        warehouses
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :
The objective of the project is to develop the basis for two  sets of
guidelines in relation  to fires in  chemical warehouses;  guidelines
for  the  safety engineers  to be  used in accident  prevention,  and
guidelines Eor the  fire brigade to  be used if an accident neverthe-
less  occurs.  The  guidelines  Will  be the outcome  of  a  detailed
and  systematic  study  of  Chemical  Warehouse  fires.  The  project
comprises studies of the following items:
Substance  classification,  source  characteristics,  fire scenarios,
suppression  systems, consequence modelling and risk assessment. This
Will  be  done  as  follows:  Based  on  a  number  of parameters the
substances  Will  be  classified.  The  classification  of substances
requires  studies  and  experiments  of  ignitability,  heat release,
burning  rate, smoke evolution, combustion products and the influence
on   the   combustion   products  of  the  packaging  materials.  The
characterisation  of  the  source  Will  use  parameters  obtained by
carrying  out combustion experiments of various scale and by studying
the  effects  of  scaling.  In  addition  the  fire scenarios will be
characterized  by the degree of ventilation, the packaging materials,
the  Stacking of the materials and the response of the building. Also
the  suppression  is  an important parameter, i.e. active and passive
suppression  and the fire brigade tactics. The potential consequences
of  the  Warehouse fires to humans as Well as the environment Will be
assessed.  Finally,  existing mathematical modelling methods used Eor
risk  assessment  Will  be  studied,  along  With  the  handling  and
prevention  of  the  accidents.  These  investigations  Will  lead to
development  of  the  basis  for  guideline  documents for the saeety
engineers  and  the  fire brigades. In parallel also a quick decision
system  to  be used bY the fire chief in case of a chemical Eire Will
be developed.

Start date             :1993-10-01
End date               :1996-09-30
Duration in months     :36
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0275
Prime contr org        :Risoe National Laboratory
Prime Organization Type:NCL Non Commercial
Prime contr dept       :Systems Analysis Department
Prime contr address    :399 Frederiksborgvej
                        PO Box 49
