<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Substitutes of halons
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :5224
Quality valid. date    :1995-03-23
Key words              :Halons, fire
Update date            :1995-08-11
Project acronym        :SUBSTHAL
Title                  :Substitutes of halons
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)

General information    :The expected achievement of this project is the
promotion   of   processes   of   production  of  new  chemical  fire
extinguishing  agents  with  the purpose of avoiding in fire-fighting
the emissions of halons, compounds harmful for the ozone layer.
This  will  require  the  improvement of the present experimental and
theoretical  knowledge about halogenated compounds (perfluoroalkanes,
hydrofluoroalkanes    and   partially   chlorinated   or   brominated
hydrofluoroalkanes)j  in  order  to design viable substitutes for the
halons.  They  should have the best efficiency as chemical inhibitors
of combustions-and the lowest ozone depletion potential.
Therefore,  the  main objectives of this project can be summarized as
follows :
* Producing  reliable  experimental  data  concerning the ability of
  these halogenated compounds to inhibit different reactional systems :
- oxidations,
- flames,
- detonations.
* Theoretical understanding and modeling of this inhibiting effect to
  permit  a  most  efficient  research  of  substitutes  of  halons as
  fire-extinguishing agents. This will include :
- Design,  simulation  and  extrapolation  of  reaction mechanism, -
  Determination  of  thermodynamic and  kinetic  data by the following
  methods :
  oe Experimental determination of rate constants, oe Quantum and
  quasi-classical  calculations of rate constants, oe  Evaluation of
  thermochemical  andkinetic  data by means of Benson's techniques.
* Analysis of the potential atmospheric impacts of using the proposed
  replacements of halons, including experimental investigation of their
  reactivity with ozone.
The   experimental  facilities  include  continuous  flow  and  flame
reactors,  shock  tubes,  mass  spectrometry, laser flash photolysis,
modulation spectrometry, vector and parallel computers.
To  reach  the  targeted  objectives, the following laboratories will
associate  their  competences  :  CNRS  NANCY  and  ORLEANS (FRANCE),
HARWELL  (G.B.),  Universities of PERUGIA (ITALY), LO W AIN-LA-NE W E
(BELGIUM), ATHENS (GREECE).
Two  industrial  groups,  ATOCHEM  (FRANCE) and SOLVAY (BELGIUM), are
strongly  interested  in  the  project  and  will  ensure  the  rapid
industrialisation of promising substitute compounds.

Start date             :1993-01-01
End date               :1995-02-28
Duration in months     :26
Project status         :Completed
