<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Small Plants - Assistance with Safety and Environment
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :31845
Quality valid. date    :1996-06-24
Update date            :1996-07-13
Project acronym        :SPASE
Title                  :Small Plants - Assistance with Safety and
       Environment
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
       MET (METEOROLOGY)
       SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :Background
       This  proposal  is  aimed  at  greatly  improving  the efficiency and
       effectiveness  of  small  chemical  process  plants in complying with
       requirements for Safety Health and Environmental (SHE) management.
       Because  such plants are so numerous and so widespread, the work will
       have  very  important economic, environmental, and social impacts not
       only  for  the hundreds of thousands of workers directly affected but
       for the well-being of their surrounding communities. The scope of the
       problem
       In  1990,  92%  of  chemical  process  plants  employed less than 100
       people;  77%  employed  less  than  20  people. Such small numbers of
       personnel imply very limited financial and technical resources.
       Indeed, it is quite common for plant at the lower end of the range to
       have  only  two  people  with  any  sort of technica qualification: a
       chemist and a maintenance person.
       In  such cases, the ability of the staff to perform SHE audits, along
       the  lines  suggested  in various industry publications, is extremely
       difficult  and  time  consuming. Furthermore, small plants often lack
       the   financial  resources  either  to  implement  comprehensive  SHE
       management plans or to introduce necessary safety equipment.
       The problems afflicting small plants arise from the Golden Rule:
       Those  with  the  gold  make  the  rules. Not only is SHE legislation
       principally  drafted  with  the  larger  enterprises  in  mind, it is
       frequently  drafted with their expert assistance. Similarly, codes of
       practice  and  recommended  methods  are  drafted by teams from large
       organisations,  they being the only ones with the resources available
       to spare for such work.
       The proposal
       The  primary  objective of this proposal is to develop SHE management
       methods  applicable  to  small plants; it may also propose changes to
       the existing legislation. Although the scope of the project precludes
       the  involvement  of  divisions  of  large organisations, the methods
       developed will be applicable to such enterprises.
       The project will result in three exploitable items:
       - a methodology for SHE assurance in small plants;
       - a major report on the SHE problems afflicting small plants;
       -  a  design  for  a  computer-based  system to support the developed
       methodology.
       Because  of  the large market involved, the partners are conscious of
       the considerable economic prospects for such tools, once developed.
       KEYWORDS
       SHE  management,  small  plants,  chemical  plants,  safety,  health,
       environmental protection
Start date             :1996-05-01
End date               :1998-04-30
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 2C
