<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Human Factors in High Risk Prevention and Management 1988-1991
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :19329
Quality valid. date    :1992-04-13
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Human Factors in High Risk Prevention and 
                        Management 1988-1991
Subject index codes    :SAF (SAFETY)
Objectives             :Control of major hazards is conditioned by
individual  and  collective  human  behaviour  at  the interface with
complex  technological  systems. This activity intends to address the
human  and  organizational  aspects  of  various  high and vulnerable
technologies : chemical, transport, etc.
General information    :Progress to end 1990 Three activities have been
carried  out  during 1990 : 1) the use of ARMA (Autoregressive Moving
Average)  techniques  as  automatic  diagnosticians to monitor linear
dynamic  systems  such as industrial processes; 2) the preparation of
participation  to  two  STEP-Science and Technology for Environmental
Protection  projects  dealing  with  the  analysis  of  human working
environments; and 3) the initial development of a Dynamic Reliability
method  for Error Assessment in Man-machine Systems (DREAMS).  In the
field  of system diagnostic, an ARMA generator simulation package has
been  finished  enabling  ARMA processes to be simulated.  Artificial
changes  in  the  model  parameters are injected in order to generate
"model  rupture".   Three  statistical  tests have been developed and
their  efficiency  has  been  ascertained.  The first of the two STEP
projects,  which  will start at beginning 91 and last for 3 years, is
named  System  Response  Analyser  in  avionics. The objective of the
project  is  to  develop  a  tool  able to analyse the human decision
making  during an incident in the civil aviation area. To this aim, a
cognitive  model  of  pilot behaviour will be developed, applying the
knowledge  which  will  be  elicited  from real airlines pilots.  The
other  STEP  project  which will be carried out together with several
industrial  partners  and research centres is named HEAT (Human Error
Analytical  Taxonomy)  :  it  will  develop  a  human  error analysis
procedure,   which  involves  cognitive  as  well  as  organizational
ergonomics principles (a first taxonomy being already developed under
JRC  contract)  and  exploit  it in intensively auditing four process
industries in Europe. The development of the methodology named DREAMS
has  been  recently  initiated  with  a  critical  review of existing
methods.   This  has led to the conclusion that the new key issues to
be  tackled in human factors are the aspects of dynamicity and stress
in  the  evaluation  of  human  errors.  Detailed description of work
foreseen in 1991 (expected results) In the area of system diagnostics
the  study  of  new statistical tests will be carried out in order to
compare different time periods of the same process.  These tests will
contribute   to  the  validation  of  the  proposed  method  for  the
identification  of  small  anomalies  of  plant  behaviour  as  early
measures  of  major  faults.  In the STEPS projects SRA-Avionics, the
model  COSIMO (COgnitive SImulation MOdel), developed at JRC, will be
dedicated   specifically   to  real  civil  aviation  piloting  using
experimental  work  carried  out  in  flying simulators. In the STEPS
project  HEAT,  the  human  error  taxonomy  will be finalized and an
auditing campaign will be launched based on the developed taxonomy.
The DREAMS method will be theoretically formalised and the problem of
data  sources  will be tackled, exploiting the results of the work on
taxonomy,  developed  in the STEP project HEAT, for classifying human
errors. Short description of evolution of work in 1992 The ARMA based
methods will be applied to real cases; extrapolation to environmental
systems  will  be  studied  addressing also the problem of stochastic
processes.  The  two STEP projects will be continued. The methodology
DREAMS  will  be applied to the evaluation of human error probability
to control rooms studies.
Start date             :1988-01-01
End date               :1992-01-01
Duration in months     :48
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :INDHAZ 2C
Project reference      :0004
Prime contr org        :Joint Research Centre Ispra
Prime contr dept       :Institute for Systems Engineering
Prime contr address    :Sito di Ispra
Prime contr postcode   :21020
Prime contr town       :ISPRA
Prime contr region     :R3201 Varese
Prime contr country    :IT (ITALY)
Contact person         :Name:         CACCIABUE, PIETRO
                    Tel:          +39-332-89119869
                    Fax:          +39-332-789001
                  Telex:        380042
 
