<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Towards a better design of pressure relief systems
in chemical and petroleum industries
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :29033
Quality valid. date    :1995-07-04
Update date            :1995-09-25
Title                  :Towards a better design of pressure relief
                        systems in chemical and petroleum industries
Subject index codes    :COO (COORDINATION, COOPERATION)
                        SCI (SCIENTIFIC RESEARCH)
General information    :The basic two coupled elements of a multiple 
reactor relief  system  design after the postulation of a worst credible
case scenario,  e.g. a thermal runaway reaction, are (1) the prediction of
the characteristics of the transient mass flux (single phase/multiphase  
flow) to be discharged from the reactor and (2) the provision of  a  
discharge piping system capable of transporting off this mass flux at any
time during relief.In the proposed project, the first part will be dealt 
with by the Technische  Universitaet Hamburg-Harburg (prof. L. Friedel). 
By using the predictions of a physically more consistent code to be 
developed, more realistic input data will be provided for an extended 
version of the  FLIERS  code,  This  extended  version  will  be proposed 
by the Universite  Catholique  de  Louvain  (prof.  L.  Bolle)  following 
an experimental  campaign  in  the  same  university. In addition to the
implementation of special items  into  FLIERS  such  as  sudden
enlargements,  orifices,  tees,  etc.  there is a strong necessity to
investigate the flow mechanisms encountered in safety relief valves.
This will be done experimentally and theoretically in the commissariat a  
l'Energie  Atomique,  Centre  d'Etudes Nucleaires de Grenoble  
(Dr H.Lemonnier) Moreover, particular but important effects such as 
nonequilibrium  and  shock  waves  will be addressed at the
Institute for Fluid Flow Machinery in Gdansk (prof. Z. Bilicki).
Finally  A.S.  Veritas  Research in Hoevik (Dr. S. Selmer-Olsen) will
perform  venting  experiments  in a simplified multiple vessel relief
system  and  the  results  will be compared to the predictions of the
coupled vessel/relief line design code. This  three-year  project  will 
focus on the following objectives and achievements :
1.  improvement  of  the  accuracy  and  reliability  of  the  design
procedures for relief systems composed of multiple storage or reactor
vessels  connected  to  a downstream process unit through collectors,
safety   valves,   ventin-lines   and   other  components  (orifices,
T-junctions,  silencers,  etc.).  
2.  determination  of  the  range of applicability   and   tentative   
recommendations  on  the  degree  of extrapolation  of  existing  design 
methods outside of their assessed validity.
3. development of user-friendly tools for engineering calculations
Start date             :1995-06-01
End date               :1996-05-31
Duration in months     :12
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ICPECO C
Project reference      :CIPD940101
Prime contr org        :Commissariat a l'Energie Atomique
Prime contr dept       :Direction des Reacteurs Nucleaires - Departement de 
                        Thermohydraulique et dePhysique Service de Thermohydraulique
                        pour lesApplications Industrielles - GRETh
Prime contr address    :Ctr Etudes de Grenoble - CE-G
Prime contr postcode   :38041
Prime contr town       :Grenoble
Prime contr region     :R2714 Isere
Prime contr country    :FR (FRANCE)
Contact person         :Name:         DELHAYE, Jean-Marc
Contact name           :BILICKI, Zbigniew
Organization           :Institute of Fluid-Flow Machinery Polish Academy of 
                        Sciences
Organization type      :NCL Non Commercial
Address                :14 ul.Fiszera
City                   :Gdansk
