<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Chemical hazard evaluation and emergency relief systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :23974
Quality valid. date    :1995-06-06
Update date            :1995-10-09
Title                  :Chemical hazard evaluation and emergency relief
                        systems
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
General information    :This project forms aco-ordinated European effort to
improve  existing  emergency  relief  systems  in  the  chemical  and
hydrocarbon  process  industries. Recent incidents in chemical plants
have  shown that there is a lack:of advanced emergency relief systems
that  can  significantly  reduce  the  amount  of  reaction  products
accidentally  discharged  into  the  atmosphere. For the first time a
joint  research  project  is set up to simultaneously investigate all
topics relating to an emergency relief system, i.e. runaway reaction,
venting  and disposal. A special emphasis is put on realistic runaway
conditions  and  large  scale  experiments.  Thus a proposal has been
formulated  that  meets  the requirements of industry and authorities
and allows maximum use of existing test facilities.
According to the different topicsof an emergency relief system and to
the  demand for proper scaling rules the project is divided into four
interactive  sub  projects.  Within sub project 1 appropriate runaway
reactions are evaluated and the required kinetic and physical data is
produced   in  laboratory  tests.  These  provide  a  basis  for  the
subsequent  work  in sub project 2. The objective of this sub project
is to deduce scaling rules for vent sizing techniques, to compare
these  with  existing  methods  and to validate or adapt the rules in
large scale experiments.
In sub project 3 a quenching system is designed and tested in a pilot
plant  that  safely  disposes  vented  reaction  products and is well
suited for both single-phase and two-phase or multi-phase flow.
Regarding  that  there  is  no requirement for external energy supply
this  new  quenching  system  could  be  in  future a main part of an
advanced  emergency  relief  system.  Based on the results of the sub
projects  1- 3 large scale experiments will be performed (sub project
4).The  results  from this project will provide proper scaling rules for
vent  sizing  techniques  and  an improved, inherently safe emergency
relief  system  including  a  quenching  system  with a high disposal
efficiency  and, thus, prescribe the safety standards in the chemical
process  industries. The results will be incorporated into a handbook
on  emergency  relief  and safe disposal of runaway reaction products
(venting  and  Disposal  Handbook)  which  can  be  used as a general
guidance.  In addition the project will produce lmportant information
to support the CEC.
Start date             :1994-11-01
End date               :1996-10-31
Duration in months     :24
Project status         :Execution
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0532
Prime contr org        :Inburex GmbH Consultinggesellschaft fuer
                        Explosionsschutz und Anlagensicherheit
Prime contr address    :5 Muensterstrasse
Prime contr postcode   :59065
Prime contr town       :Hamm
Prime contr region     :R1554 Hamm, krfr.St.
Prime contr country    :DE (GERMANY FEDERAL REP.)
Contact person         :Name:         ROGER, R.
