<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Reliability and Safety of Industrial and Technical Systems.Environment
Planning,1992-1994
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :17152
Quality valid. date    :1992-12-09
Update date            :1995-10-09
Title                  :Reliability and Safety of Industrial and Technical
                        Systems.Environment Planning,1992-1994
Subject index codes    :SAF (SAFETY)
Objectives             :The objective is to improve environmental planning,
policy  making and risk management by performing relevant theoretical
and  practical studies related to the development of decision support
systems  (DSS).  This  includes  models  for  distributed  decisions,
integration  of DSS with different types of information systems (such
as   Geographic  information  system  and  others)  and  studies  of
multi-actor,  multi-objective  environmental problems, both for fixed
installations and transportation.
General information    :Progress to end 1991
In  the previous multi-annual programme (1989-1991) this activity was
carried  out  under  two  different worksheets in the industrial Risk
Programme.  The progress up to the end of 1991, divided into relevant
subheading, is as follows:
Decision Support Systems and methods for multi criteria decision aids
have  been  investigated  from  the  point of view of the fundamental
theory and of the practical. In 1990 new relevant mathematical models
of  decision  processes  were  investigated  related  to  "preference
elicitation"   including  both  interactive  methods  and  outranking
methods.  The existence of a mathematical analogy between the problem
of  the  aggregation  of  quality  parameters  and the application of
multicriteria  decision  analysis  has  been investigated, indicating
that  a new formal approach could be useful to expert in the relevant
field  (Munda  et  al,  1990). Studies on territorial risk management
dealing  with  industrial impact were initiated integrating different
approaches  and  tools as GIS (Geographic Information Systems) and ES
(expert Systems). The aim is to compare heterogeneous effects such as
major  hazards, pollution of air, water and soil, negative effects on
the   landscape,   public   opposition  ,  (Paruccini  et  al,  1991)
Risk  Management  methodological  work  has  started  to  improve the
availability  and quality of social science results, recognising that
socio-cultural aspects are as important as the technical ones in this
area  across  diverse socio-cultural groupings. Current methodologies
of  social  research  have  been  evaluated  and compared in order to
establish  their  scope and applicability. (De Marchi, 1990). Studies
done  and/or  still  underway  will  enable  the use of tested social
science data foe DSS.
During  1990  and  1991 an important study of historical accidents in
relation  with transportation of hazardous materials was carried out,
and  the  results  indicate  that  the consequences of transportation
accidents are as severe as those of fixed installation accidents.
(Haastrup  &  Brockhoff,  1990). Consequence models to be included in
transportation risk modelling were studied in detail, analysis of the
special  requirements  for  transportation  was performed (Brockhoff,
1991),  and  the  reliability  of the available data has been studied
(Haastrup & Brockhoff,  1991).  In  1989  a  TRansportation  Risk
Management  systems  TRIM was developed and in 1991 this was improved
by  including a very detailed databases for the road network from one
of the member states (Denmark).
Detailed description of work foreseen in 1992
For  1992  the work focus on three important aspects of environmental
planning  in  a  densely populated and culturally diiferentiated area
like   Europe: risk perception, management and communication,
organisations taking the  decisions  in  multi-  activity  areas,
allocation in various sectors of industrialised systems and
transportation.
- Studies of different decisions support models will continue and new
decision   support   models  for  environmental  planning,  based  on
communication and negotiation and exploiting the concept of hypertext
technology,  will  also  be  investigated  to improve the theoretical
understanding of decision making in this complex area. This next kind
of  DSS  will  be  also  based  on suited integration with Geographic
Information  Systems  and  report  systems. The particular problem of
risk  allocating,  taking  into  consideration  the  socio-economical
vulnerability  of  the  environment, will be tackled developing a new
approach  based  on hazard syndrome indicators and environmental risk
profiles.
-   Risk  perception  and  risk  communication  are  key  issues  for
successful  environmental  planning.  Previous research indicates the
need  to  study  especially the risk communication process in detail,
and starting 1992 empirical studies will be carried out in key areas.
-  A  particular  area  raising most difficult environmental planning
problems,  stems  from  the transportation of dangerous products. The
investigation of risk management problems in this sectorial area will
continue.  Previous research has produced a computer based system for
management  of  transportation risk, based on sample regions. In 1992
the  research into transportation patterns, substances and quantities
of  hazardous  material  will  be extended to all EC, with the aim of
evaluating  the overall risk contributions to man and the environment
from this source.
Short description of evolution of work in 1993
The studies of different support models, including fuzzy logic and of
the  integration  of  decision support systems with other information
systems  and  multimedia  techniques  is expected to continue, and in
1993  the  goal  is  to  have  full  geographical  information system
integrated   in  a  decision  support  system.  Risk  perception  and
communication  studies  will  continue,  with emphasis on the broader
empirical studies.
For  transportation  risk management, the goal is to have a DSS ready
in 1993, capable of evaluating  the  overall  risk  from  the
transportation  of hazardous materials to a given plant or to a given
branch of industry.
Start date             :1992-01-01
End date               :1994-12-31
Duration in months     :36
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :INDHAZ 3C
Project reference      :0001
Prime contr org        :Joint Research Centre Ispra
Prime contr dept       :Institute for Systems Engineering
Prime contr address    :Sito di Ispra
Prime contr postcode   :21020
Prime contr town       :ISPRA
Prime contr region     :R3201 Varese
Prime contr country    :IT (ITALY)
Contact person         :Name:         HAASTRUP P.
                    Tel:          +39-332-7889083
                    Fax:          +39-332-789001
                  Telex:        380042 EUR I
 
            --------------------------------------------------
</PRE>
</BODY>
