<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Reliability and Risk Evaluation, 1992-1994
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :17149
Quality valid. date    :1994-01-27
Update date            :1995-10-09
Title                  :Reliability and Risk Evaluation, 1992-1994
Subject index codes    :FIS (NUCLEAR FISSION)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
                        safety analysis
Objectives             :Develop a conceptual framework and methodology for
monitoring and controlling the level of safety of an ageing NPP.  The
work will be based on the use of probabilistic approaches and aims at
extending and strenghtening the so-called "Living PSA" (Probabilistic
Safety Assessment).
General information    :Progress to end 1991
STARS  (Software  Tools  for Analysis of Reliability and Safety) : in
this  project,  an  integrated set of informatic tools for supporting
the  various  phases of safety assessment has been implemented.  More
specifically, a methodology and related tools have been developed for
specifying  a  hierarchical,  functional  decomposition  model  of an
industrial  installation.   Knowledge based tools have been developed
to  support  the derivation of safety and reliability assessment from
this model.  STARS allows for an easy modification of the plant model
and  hence  of the analysis. This opens interesting possibilities for
the  use  of  STARS in a more dynamic safety management context where
the  plant  model  is updated when new evidence becomes available and
where  the  impact  of  changes  on  plant operation or design can be
investigated.
A first feasibility study on the use of STARS for living PSA has been
started by ABB and FRAMATONE.
CEDB  (Component  Event  Data  Bank)  :  after  the end of 1991, this
centralized  data  bank  will be supported no longer by the FWP.  The
management  of  this bank by the JRC could continue only as an action
financially  supported  by  third  parties.  No agreement between the
data  suppliers has been found so far for the financement of the CEDB
management  cost.  The WANO PC-Paris (the regional Centre of Paris of
the Wolrd Association of Nuclear Operators) gave a negative answer to
the  request  made  by  the JRC to adopt CEDB as their reference data
bank.  The JRC is investigating the possibility to continue some CEDB
activity in the framework of bilateral agreements with data suppliers
Data  analysis  :  intelligent  Selections,  (IS),  a methodology for
sampling  from  the  CEDB  and  reliability data bases in general was
established.    This   methodology   allows   for  dealing  with  the
multidimensionality  inherent  into  databases  and  was  applied  to
electric  motors  in  the  database  for  the  definition  of sets of
comparable  components (taxonomies) on the basis of database data and
experts  opinions.   Estimates  of  failures  rates  of  failures  on
electric   motors  were  derived  for  failures  of  three  different
severities  and  based  on  the  homogeneity  model.   Parametric  or
nonparametric  hypothesis  tests  for  assessing  heterogeneities  of
failure  rates  among  plantgroups  for  comparable  components  were
developed and implemented for electric motors.
System  Response  Analyser  (SRA)  :  it is a simulation tool for the
study of dynamic interaction of humans and machines.  SRA is based on
three main components, namely the driver of SRA (the DYLAM code), the
machine  model  and the operator model.  During 1991 the prototype of
System  Response  Analyser  based  on  the  case  of  control of AFWS
(Auxiliary Feed Water System) was completed.  Furthermore the Version
3 of the DYLAM has been released.
Structural  Diagnostics  :  relevant  activities  have been performed
within  the  FWP Measurement and Testing, in particular the operation
of  the Pressurized Thermal Shock (PTS) Experiment, applying repeated
thermal  transients  on  nozzle  corner  and safe end of a 1/5 scaled
model of PWR PV.  The test rig has undergone 1500 thermal transients.
A   prototype   expert  system  (RAMINO)  has  been  implemented  for
reliability  assessment  and  lifetime prediction on nuclear pressure
vessels.
The  architecture  of  an  expert  system  for  the management of the
experimental facility has been developed.
Large  experience  has been gained in signal analysis & filtering and
system identification.
Deatiled description of work foreseen in 1992 (expected results)
It  is  intended to develop an integrated system, based on the use of
the  STARS oriented to living PSA, the SRA for man-machine simulation
and  the  DYLAM  methodology  for  the analysis of dynamic processes,
codes  as COVAL and COVASTOL and expert systems like ARTIC and RAMINO
for   the   assessment   of  residual  life  of  structures  and  the
optimization of the relative inspection maintenance.
The following actions are foreseen :
1.  Development  of  a  hierarchical  conceptual  model  of  the  NPP
according  to  the  STARS  methodology.   Special  attention  will be
devoted  as  to  how  to take into consideration the evolution of the
objects with time (management of change, incorporation of experience,
etc).
2.  As  to the development of the component layer in the plant model,
this  includes  the recording of component events and analysis of the
ageing  of  the components.  The experience and know-how derived from
the CEDB project and the related data analysis will be used.
3.  A  tool  for  dynamic  reliability  analysis  of systems based on
DYLAM-III/TRETA  will  be developed.  This will also represent a user
friendly environment for the development of plant simulation models.
Different  dynamic  reliability approaches will be compared on simple
case studies.
4.  A  pilot  study will be carried out for dynamic human reliability
analysis related to the introduction in ageing plants of new types of
supervisory  systems  for  accident  management.   This study will be
based on the SRA concept with simple human behaviour cognitive models
5.  A knowledge based system (BOSS = Backtracking and Overviewing for
Structural  Safety)  will  be  developed  and  introduced  in the PSA
procedure.  It is conceived as an intelligent aid to operator for the
continuous  monitoring  of structural safety and will also constitute
the  structure  related  module  of  STARS.   It  will  constitute an
intelligent tool for structural management and maintenance.
The work foreseen for 1992 will be, first of all, focused on : set up
of  the  informatic  hardware  and  software  supports; definition of
architecture,  functions  and  knowledge representation techniques of
BOSS; development of structure and functionalities of the intelligent
interface  with  the  unit  which  collects service data and with the
standard software tools performing algorithmic data analysis.
6.  As in all the above mentioned actions the use of expert judgement
(EJ) is important, a Benchmark Exercise to compare EJ procedures used
by  various  Organizations  will  be  prepared.  The study case could
consider   aged   structures   or  systems  of  a  real  plant  under
hypothetical accidental conditions.
Short description of evolution of work in 1993
Application  to  a real plant (collaboration with plant designers and
utilities).    The development of BOSS will go on with representation
of  knowlegde,  implementation of inference engines and corroboration
tests  on  the PTS loop.  Interfaces between BOSS and other knowledge
based systems will be designed.
Start date             :1992-01-01
End date               :1994-12-01
Duration in months     :35
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :REACTSAFE 6C
Project reference      :0001
Prime contr org        :Joint Research Centre Ispra
Prime contr dept       :Institute for Systems Engineering
Prime contr address    :Sito di Ispra
Prime contr postcode   :21020
Prime contr town       :ISPRA
Prime contr region     :R3201 Varese
Prime contr country    :IT (ITALY)
