<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Environmental risk criteria
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :27089
Quality valid. date    :1995-06-14
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Environmental risk criteria
Subject index codes    :ENV (ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION)
                        MET (METEOROLOGY)
                        SAF (SAFETY)
                        risk management
General information    :The main objective of the proposed Work is to
produce a Discussion Document within the European Community, relating
to  risk  acceptability  or  tolerability  criteria  for  harm to the
natural  environment.  There  is clearly a need for considerations of
this  kind  in  the development and application of environmental risk
assessment  and  management  systems.  The  project  is  designed  to
stimulate  discussion  within the EC, which will lead, eventually, to
the  development  of  appropriate  standards.  This  will  complement
standards/criteria developed in a number of member states relating to
harm to humans.
The  project  is based on a preliminary study pereormed bY two of the
three  participants:  AEA  (UK)  and  VROM  (The  Netherlands).  This
investigated  the  feasibility  of  developing  criteria  for various
levels  of  environmental harm. The project focused on one particular
eco-system  type,  ie rivers, and indicated feasibility by deriving a
possible framework in the form of probability/consequence curves (f/n
lines  or  CCDF'S).  This is summarised in Appendix 1 of the attached
Technical Proposal.The proposal includes a contribution from a third participant:
AGEL/CBI  (Hungary).  The work will review the earlier AEA/VROM study
and,  through  discussions  between  participants  and  with external
bodies, propose an agreed, draft set of risk criteria for rivers. The
approach  will  then  be extended to two other eco-systems: estuaries
and lakes. This will then be followed by a series of trials, aimed at
testing the practicality of the criteria developed for each system in
isolation, and also at ensuring that the three systems are consistent
eg  ensuring that the relative degree of protection afforded by each
is  sensible relative to the others. A further feature of the project
is  that, since some risk assessment methods evaluate relative rather
than  absolute  risk,  a  specific  task  will  assess  the  means of
expressing  the  absolute  risk  criteria developed above in relative
risk terms.The  Discussion Document will describe all activities and 
conclusions from  the  study ana, along with other initiatives within 
the project aimed at publicising  the  work,  will  stimulate  the  
necessary discussion within the EC.
Start date             :1994-04-01
End date               :1995-03-31
Duration in months     :12
Project status         :Completed
Programme acronym      :ENV 1C
Project reference      :EV5V0417
Prime contr org        :United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority
Prime contr dept       :Warrington Laboratory Consultancy Services
Prime contr address    :Thomson House
Prime contr postcode   :WA3 6AT
Prime contr town       :Warrington
Prime contr region     :R781 CHESHIRE
Prime contr country    :GB (UNITED KINGDOM)
Contact person         :Name:         NIXON, William (Mr)
Contact name           :VAN LEEUWEN, CORNELIS
Organization           :Ministerie van Volkshuisvesting
                        Ruimtelijke Ordening en Milieubeheer
Organization type      :NCL Non Commercial
Address                :8 RijnstraatPostbus 30945
City                   :Den Haag
Postcode               :2500 GX
Region                 :R4732 Agglom 'S Gravenhage
Country                :NL (NETHERLANDS)
 
