<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Uncontrolled Reactions : Flow, Turbulence and Combustion, 1988-1991
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :19334
Quality valid. date    :1992-04-09
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Uncontrolled Reactions : Flow, Turbulence and
                        Combustion, 1988-1991
Subject index codes    :SAF (SAFETY)
To  monitor  and  to provide scientific guidance to the fluid-dynamic
research  performed  at  the JRC in co-operation with ERCOFTAC and to
act  as a scientific secretary for promoting and maintaining contacts
with  this  research association. This includes an active role in the
application  and  development  of  advanced  computer  codes for flow
simulation,   initiation  and  arrangement  of  scientific  meetings,
preparation  of scientific documents, collaboration with universities
and research organisations.
General information    :Progress to end 1990
The  creation  of  ERCOFTAC  resulted  from  the  conviction that the
competitiveness  of the European high-technology industry involved in
Flow, Turbulence and Combustion, would significantly be enhanced by a
very  high  level  of  co-operation  and  in  particular  by a strong
interaction  between  the  Research  Community  and  Industry.  It is
expected  that  the scientific, technical and industrial expertise of
the  ERCOFTAC  members  will  positively  affect  the  quality of JRC
research  actions  in  the  field  of  Flow,  Turbulence d Combustion
(including  Computational  Fluid  Dynamics  and  Aeronautics), and in
particular  in  the  field  of  industrial  hazards and environmental
analysis.  The activities for 1990 are:
- Organisation  of  the ERCOFTAC Managing Board meeting (October 25)
  and  the  ERCOF   TAC  General  Assembly  (October  26)  with  5  JRC
  contributions.
- Preparation of a proposal by which JRC applies for the status of a
  Pilot  Centr   e  (with  a  European  vocation)  within  the ERCOFTAC
  Association (end 1990).
Detailed description of work foreseen in 1991 (expected results)
Setting  up  of  an  ERCOFTAC Pilot Centre in the Institute of Safety
Technology at JRC.  An important contribution of this Pilot Centre is
to  make  available  an  infrastructure  for Visiting Scientists from
ERCOFTAC  members.   These guests should be working on subjects which
are  of  a  fundamental, exploratory or consultative nature.  Four of
the research areas of JRC are of particular relevance to ERCOFTAC.
These   are   multiphase/multicomponent   flow,  dense  vapour  cloud
dispersion,  atmospheric  and  marine modellingand the development of
computational  methods  and  software.   The  work  foreseen  in 1991
consists  of  the  preparation  of  detailed formulations of research
activities on the above-mentioned areas, the initiation of industrial
or governmental contacts.
Short description of evolution of work in 1992
