<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Uncontrolled Reactions : Numerical Simulation of Reacting Gas Flow,
                         1988-1991
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<PRE>
Record cntrl number    :19333
Quality valid. date    :1992-04-09
Update date            :1995-08-12
Title                  :Uncontrolled Reactions : Numerical Simulation of
                        Reacting Gas Flow, 1988-1991
Subject index codes    :SAF (SAFETY)
The  objective is to provide numerical tools for safety studies where
detonation processes are of major concern : e.g. combustion of vapour
clouds,   flame   front  and  detonation/blast  wave  propagation  in
industrial  environment.   Initial  and  boundary conditions might be
provided by vapour cloud dispersion models (see workschedule :
release and dispersion of chemical reactive multiphase fluids).
In  addition,  the methodology applied and the computer program under
development  is of relevance also for a wide spectrum of applications
in the area of numerical flow simulation.
General information    :Progress to end 1990
During  1991 a pilot version of a computer code was developed for the
numerical   simulation  of  two-dimensional  multicomponent  reactive
transonic flow.  The code can handle the flow of gas mixtures with an
arbitrary number of components which might chemically react according
to an arbitrary number of elementary reactions. The chemical reaction
kinetics  is  described  by  the  Van Hoff law.  Since in the present
version  of  the  code  the  major emphasis is given to high velocity
reacting flows (e.g. detonation) ratr than to flame front propagation
diffusion processes are not included at this stage.
A  large  amount  of  attention has been given to the selection of an
appropriate  numerical solution strategy.  The method applied belongs
to the class of "High resolution Techniques" which allow the accurate
tracking   of   flow   discontinuities  (e.g.  shock  waves,  contact
discontinuities).   These  methods, well assessed for one-dimensional
Euler  solvers,  had to be extended to multicomponent two-dimensional
flow processes.
Due  to  the use of unstructured grids, a large flexibility exists to
represent (even complex) geometrical boundaries.  Confined (internal)
as well as external flows with obstacles can be easily described.
The assessment of the code including test cases with non-reacting gas
mixtures as well as more complex flow conditions has started.
Detailed description of work foreseen in 1991 (expected results)
The  first  priority  will  be  given  to  the completion of the code
documentation   including  the  description  of  models,  algorithms,
informatic  structure,  users  guide and code validation reports.  In
addition,  further extension of the code planned for this time period
concern:
-  to include diffusion processes with respect to viscous shear, heat
   conduction,  species diffusion
-  to investigate the use of a generalized Rieman solver for reactive
   flows  (as a  lternative to the source term operator splitting) which
   is   expected   to  improve   the  prediction  of  detonation  fronts
-  to  improve  the  informatic  environment with respect to pre- and
   post-processing  (e.g. mesh generation, graphic capabilities).
Short description of evolution of work in 1992.
The  evolution  of  the  work  will  include further improvements and
extensions  of the prediction capabilities bases on the experience in
using  the  code  for  industrial  applications  and  with respect to
requirements  coming  from  outside.  Extensions envisaged at present
concern  the implementation of state-of-the-art models for turbulence
and  the  prediction  of multiphase flows (e.g. reactive gas/particle
flows).  2
Start date             :1988-01-01
