<!-- ------------ct 11/27/96 -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
 <H2><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif"><A><B> Who We Are</B></A></H2>
</P>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P>

<H3><A HREF="#what"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
What is the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development?</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#Service"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
A New Service for Communities</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#DOE"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
Why is DOE involved?</A></H3>
<!-- ------------------ct 11/27/96------------------>
<H3><A HREF="#Q&A"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
Questions and Answers About the Center</A></H3>
<!-- ---------------------------------------------------->
<H3><A HREF="#Center"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development Staff</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#Contacting"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
Contacting the Center</A></H3>

<H3><A HREF="#Support"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/logo6.gif" ALT=" * " BORDER="0">
Contact Support Offices</A></H3> 

<P></P>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<H3><A NAME="what">What</A> is the Center of Excellence for Sustainable
Development?</H3>
<P>The Center of Excellence for  Sustainable Development helps communities
design and implement innovative strategies that enhance the local economy as
well as the local environment and quality of life.   Created by the U.S.
Department of Energy's Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy,
the new Center of Excellence can:<BR></P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Define what
sustainable development is and how it can apply to you;
</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Show how sustainable development is
being practiced by other urban and rural communities across the nation;
</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Provide you via, the internet,
with a
&quot;tool kit&quot; of sustainable information including manuals,
workbooks,
data bases, case studies and model codes and ordinances;</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Help you identify public and
private sources of technical and financial assistance to carry out your
program;

</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Provide you with information about
the public participation processes other communities have found work best in
planning and implementing sustainable development; and</P>
<P><IMG ALIGN="TOP" SRC="/rsc/mball.gif">  Develop a menu of energy efficiency
and renewable energy programs that fit the unique needs of your community. 
<BR></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><BR>Our customers are communities and the Federal, State and local agencies
that assist them in community development.  We define communities broadly to
include cities, villages, towns and neighborhoods, as well as national parks,
industrial parks and other &quot;communities of interest.&quot;
</P>
<P>Our mission is to provide communities with world-class consultation on
sustainable development and to help them link to the other public and private
programs that can help them develop sustainably. 
</P>
<P>There are many resources available on this Web site that you can use to
assist your community.  You can also request specific technical assistance from
the Center of Excellence through our <A HREF="assist.shtml"><B>request
assistance form.</B></A></P>
<!-- ---------------------------------------------------------------------->
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3>A New <A NAME="Service">Service</A> for Communities</H3>
<P>Communities across the United States are showing interest in a new strategy
for economic well-being.  It's called &quot;sustainable development.&quot;  It
is the deliberate effort to ensure that community development not only enhances
the local economy, but also the local environment and quality of life. </P>
<P>To help communities design and implement this vibrant new approach to
planning, the U.S. Department of Energy has created a Center of Excellence for
Sustainable Development.  Together with other Federal, State and local agencies,
we will:</P>
<UL>
<LI><P>Define what sustainable development is and how it can apply
to
you;</P>
<LI><P>Show how sustainable development is being practiced by other urban
and rural communities across the nation;</P>
<LI><P>Provide you with access to a &quot;tool kit,&quot; including
manuals,
workbooks, data bases, case studies and model codes and ordinances;</P>
<LI><P>Help you identify public and private sources of technical and
financial assistance to carry our your program;</P>
<LI><P>Provide you with information about the public participation
processes
other communities have found work best in planning and implementing sustainable
development.</P>
<LI><P>Develop a menu of energy efficiency and renewable energy programs
that fit the unique needs of your community; and</P>
</UL>
<P><I>&quot;Sustainable development may be the most exciting concept ever to
come to community planning.  It's a </I><I>way for communities to bridge the
gap between economic progress and environmental quality.&quot;  </I><B><I>Christine
</I></B><B><I>A. Ervin</I></B><I>, Assistant Secretary for Energy Efficiency
and Renewable Energy.</I></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3>Why is <A NAME="DOE">DOE</A> involved?</H3>
<P><I>DOE's mission is to assure that the nation has adequate and stable
supplies of energy.  We're also </I><I>committed to helping the nation discover
and adopt cleaner and more sustainable energy resources and </I><I>technologies
&#151; in other words, technologies that improve our energy efficiency, prevent
pollution and </I><I>make use of renewable resources to diversify the nation's
energy mix.</I></P>
<P><I>We've found it makes no sense to try to isolate energy issues from
environmental and economic issues.  </I><I>They are intertwined.  Each
community's energy choices inevitably affect its economy and environment; </I><I>its
economic and environmental decisions almost always affect its energy use.</I></P>
<P><I>The Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development is an experimental
program in which DOE will help </I><I>communities adopt a comprehensive
approach to energy planning &#151; an approach that recognizes the </I><I>linkages
between energy, environment, economy and community livability.</I></P>
<P><I>We believe that this approach will allow us to more effectively carry
out our national mission.</I></P>
<!-- -------------------------ct 11/26/96 --------------------->
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A"><H3>Questions and Answers</H3></A></B>
<B>About the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development</B>
<P><B>Question:</B> Why is the Department of Energy involved in sustainable development?
<P><I>Reducing energy use, protecting the environment and encouraging the use of energy </I><I>efficiency and renewable energy technologies are central to the Department's mission. </I><I>They are also key to any discussion of sustainable development. DOE has found from </I><I>experience it makes no sense to try to isolate energy issues from environmental and </I><I>economic issues. Energy choices impact the economy and environment; economic and </I><I>environmental decisions almost always affect energy use.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Would sustainable development be more appropriately managed by some other    federal agency?
<P><I>We are not &quot;managing&quot; sustainable development activities on behalf of the entire Federal </I><I>government. Government</I><I>-</I><I>wide coordination is the job of the Council on Environmental </I><I>Quality in the White House, which has been charged with following up on the work of the </I><I>President's Council on Sustainable Development.  Meanwhile, several individual agencies </I><I>are offering sustainable development programs in line with their missions. EPA has several. </I><I>DOT operates a &quot;Livable Communities&quot; program dealing with transportation issues. Ours is </I><I>similar. If our portfolio of information seems broader than those of some other agencies, it's </I><I>because energy is so pervasive a subject in the life of communities.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Why are you not at least working in partnership with other government agencies?
<P><I>We are. We communicate regularly with both the White House and our counterparts in </I><I>other agencies. We've included every relevant Federal program we know about on our </I><I>data base of more than 800 public and private programs that can help communities engage </I><I>in sustainable development.  We're communicating closely with private sector groups we </I><I>know are also engaged in educating the public about sustainable development.  For </I><I>example, we are working with the National Association of Counties and the U. S. </I><I>Conference of Mayors on their new program, a Joint Center for Sustainable Communities. </I><I>The people who visit our Web site on the Internet will be able to hotlink to the Web sites of </I><I>all the other programs we know about.  This Fall, we plan to host a conference of the public </I><I>and private organizations most dedicated to helping promote sustainable development. The </I><I>purpose of our meeting will be to talk about how we all can collaborate more closely.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B>  What was the impetus for establishing the Center?
<P><I>DOE's work with several communities devastated by the 1993 Midwest floods served as the </I><I>testing ground for the Department's role in sustainable development. Because of DOE's </I><I>involvement, several communities used sustainable development approaches in rebuilding. </I><I> The effort was a success, and the Department realized it could play a similar, and equally </I><I>valuable role, with communities across the country.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Isn't sustainable development merely a fad?
<P><I>The concept of sustainable development has been around for as long as people have tried </I><I>to sort out their relationship to the environment. It has been around as long as people have </I><I>been concerned about the future, and about their children. At different times, it has gone </I><I>under different names &#151; for example, the appropriate technology movement of the 1960s </I><I>and 70s. In recent years, the concept seems to have taken on new significance. Perhaps it's </I><I>because so many undeveloped nations are now engaged in aggressive economic </I><I>development campaigns that, unless they are done responsibly, can have major </I><I>environmental consequences. Perhaps it's because new technologies &#151;</I><I>-</I><I> for example in </I><I>the fields of energy efficiency and renewable energy &#151;now are making it possible to </I><I>achieve economic development along with environmental quality. Maybe it's because </I><I>communities have limited dollars available, and they want to get all they can out of them &#151; </I><I>not just economic development, but also environmental health and quality of life.</I>
<P><I>Community leaders across the nation are realizing quality of life, environmental quality and </I><I>economic progress can only be sustained into future generations if we change our way of </I><I>thinking.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> It sounds like there are other organizations doing the same thing.
<P>  Why does DOE need such an organization, too?
<P><I>It's a positive sign that other organizations are involved, but we all meet different needs. The </I><I>DOE effort is focused principally on energy issues and primarily on community </I><I>development. We do provide information on other aspects of sustainable development, </I><I>but our usual practice will be to refer customers to other sources for that information.</I>
<P><I>We will make every effort to ensure that we are not engaged in unintentional duplication </I><I>with other information providers for communities. When there is duplication &#151; and </I><I>duplication is sometimes good strategy &#151; we want it to be strategic and not accidental.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Doesn't sustainable development put DOE on the side of environmental activists    and in opposition to business?
<P><I>Not at all. That question implies the old dichotomy of environment versus economic </I><I>progress. Sustainable development is based on the knowledge that we can have both. It </I><I>is pro</I><I>-</I><I>business and pro-environment. It leads to economic benefits like reduced costs for </I><I>companies as well as consumers. Companies which embrace the concept of sustainability </I><I>will find that, not only are sustainable practices good for the environment and quality of </I><I>life, but they are also good for the bottom line.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Your staff and budget are very small. Does this mean DOE isn't really serious    about sustainable development?
<P><I>DOE's contributions to sustainable development extend well beyond the Center of </I><I>Excellence. DOE is engaged in the most intensive environmental clean</I><I>-</I><I>up program in </I><I>government. The department invests nearly $1 billion in research on energy efficient and </I><I>renewable energy technologies, which are a key to sustainable development. We have an </I><I>aggressive program of promoting these new U.S. sustainable energy technologies to the </I><I>developing world, to help ensure that economic progress overseas does not mean </I><I>environmental slippage worldwide. DOE is very serious about sustainable development. </I><I>The Center of Excellence is a new effort to extend our assistance to communities, where </I><I>many key energy decisions are made and influenced. But it is hardly all that we do, or intend </I><I>to do in the future.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Do you have, or are you planning to seek, a Congressional line item for the    Center?
<P><I>We have no plans at this point to seek a special appropriation for the Center. We see it as </I><I>an educational program to help communities learn about the resources and programs that </I><I>already exist, at DOE, at other government agencies, and in the private sector.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> What will trigger DOE's decision to continue the Center beyond the     demonstration period?
<P><I>A strong response from communities across the country for our services, as measured in </I><I>requests for information and requests for advice and assistance.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> What has been the reaction of communities so far?
<P><I>So far, the response has been very good. In our first 60 days of operation, we had about </I><I>20,000 visits to our Internet Home Page, and more than 400 phone calls from businesses, </I><I>communities, agencies and others.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> What communities have you assisted in the program thus far?
<P><I>We have had requests for consultation from such major cities as Baltimore, Atlanta, Kansas </I><I>City, Ogden and Denver; several smaller cities; and the states of Florida, Iowa and </I><I>Arkansas.</I>
<P><B>Question:</B> Is financial assistance available to communities through the Center?
<P><I>The Center does not provide financial assistance to communities for sustainable </I><I>development. It performs mainly an education, information and advisory role. However, </I><I>we do put communities in touch with possible sources of financial assistance.</I><P></P>

<!-- --------------------------------------------------------------->
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Center">Center</A> of Excellence for Sustainable Development
Staff</H3>
<P><B>WILLIAM S . BECKER,</B><B><I> Director</I></B></P>
<P>William S. Becker got his start in sustainable communities in 1973 as
editor/publisher of the weekly newspaper in Soldiers Grove, Wisconsin.  When the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers proposed to build a levee around the flood-stricken
town, Becker counter-proposed that the community relocate and rebuild on higher
ground.  The project was completed 10 years later.  Soldiers Grove built the
nation's first solar-heated business district and instituted a number of other
sustainable development measures.  In 1994, Becker led a DOE
initiative that sent design teams to two other Midwest communities to help them
relocate and use sustainable technologies as they recovered from the Great
Flood.  Both of those communities&#151;Pattonsburg, Missouri, Valmeyer,
Illinois&#151;have
won awards from the President's Council on Sustainable Development.  In December
1995, Becker became director of DOE's Denver Regional Support Office.  In March
1996, he launched the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development to help
other communities learn how to adopt sustainable practices.  Becker is the
author of two books about the Soldiers Grove project.  His work is cited in two
other books (<I>Renewables are Ready</I> and <I>Restoring the Earth</I>) and a
television documentary, &quot;River Town.&quot;</P>
<P><B>GERALD F. KOTAS, </B><B><I>Industrial Technologies Specialist</I></B></P>
<P>Jerry Kotas is Senior Environmental Advisor at DOE's Golden Field Office in
Colorado, and is co-director of the department's National Climate Wise Program,
which helps businesses and industries adopt voluntary efforts to save energy,
use renewable energy technologies, and prevent pollution, including greenhouse
gas emissions linked with global warming.  Prior to joining DOE in 1992, Kotas
worked for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in Washington, D.C.,
directing its Pollution Prevention Program.  He also has worked extensively for
regional and state levels of government.  Kotas has a bachelors degree in
geology from the University of Notre Dame and a masters degree in environmental
geology and community and regional planning from the University of Texas at
Austin.  In his work with the Center of Excellence, he specializes in the use of
sustainable practices by industries.</P>
<P><B>KENNETH R. SNYDER, </B><B><I>Renewable Resources Specialist</I></B></P>
<P>Since joining DOE in 1994, Kenneth R. Snyder has specialized in helping
states carry out renewable energy programs.  He has served as Renewable Energy
Program Manager for the DOE's Denver Regional Support Office, working
principally with states, communities and organizations in the Rocky Mountain
region.  Snyder earned his masters degree in environmental studies from
the Yale
School of Forestry and Environmental Studies.  He has worked with the National
Audubon Society in international negotiations on climate change and forests, and
organized a graduate-level seminar at Yale on international environmental
negotiations.  At the Center, Snyder specializes in sustainable resource use.</P>
<P><B>PATRICK LANA, </B><B><I>Community Development and Transportation </I></B><B><I>Technologies
Specialist</I></B></P>
<P>Patrick Lana has more than 14 years of community development and sustainable
energy experience at the federal, state and local levels.  Before joining DOE's
Denver Regional Support Office, he was in charge of sustainable development
assistance at the Kansas City Regional Support Office, where he served as a
member of the design assistance team that helped Pattonsburg, Missouri, devise
its pioneering recovery plan.  Lana served as an ombudsman for rural communities
for the Farmers Home Administration at the U.S. Department of Agriculture,
resolving community development problems and helping operate Governors' Rural
Development Councils.  He has been a community planner and planning director,
and executive director of a regional planning and development agency.  He earned
a Bachelor of Science degree in urban and regional planning, with a minor in
architecture, at Iowa State University.  At the Center of Excellence, Lana
specializes in community planning processes and sustainable transportation.</P>
<P><B>JAMEY D. EVANS,</B><B><I> Building Technologies and Information
Specialist</I></B></P>
<P>Jamey Evans joined DOE in 1989 as a regional coordinator for the
department's education programs.  At the Center of Excellence, he specializes in
tracking and communicating innovative community approaches to the built
environment, including resource-efficient building designs, resource-related
mortgage policies, and green building programs sponsored by architects,
realtors, developers and other members of the building professions.  Evans
received his bachelor degree in communication from Hastings College (Nebraska).</P>
<P><B>LINDA J. YACKS,</B><B><I> Information Specialist</I></B></P>
<P>Linda Yacks joined the DOE's Denver Regional Support Office in 1986.  She
serves as the Center's information specialist, maintaining its resource library
and coordinating responses to information requests from communities.</P>
<P><B>BARBARA A. ALDERSON,</B><B><I> Information Manager</I></B></P>
<P>Barbara Alderson joined DOE's Dallas Regional Support Office in 1990, where she assisted with the administration of several DOE energy conservation programs.  She later served as Program Manager of DOE's schools and hospitals program for a five-state a






rea.  In 1996, she joined the Denver Regional Support Office as the Center's Information Manager, where she oversees the administration aspects of the Center.  Barbara attended Texas A&amp;M University-Kingsville.</P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<H3><A NAME="Contacting">Contacting</A> the Center</H3>
<P>Requesting Assistance for Your Community</P>
<P>DOE's Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development provides a variety of
assistance   to communities.  Much of the information that can help your
community develop more sustainably is available in the resource database and the
articles and ordinances that are accessible from our home page.</P>
<P>We also are developing programs to provide personalized technical assistance
to your community.  The types of assistance we can provide your community
include the following: </P>
<UL><LI>Helping you identify public and private sources of technical and
financial assistance to carry   out your individual program;</LI>
<LI>Providing you with information about the public participation
processes other
communities have found work best in planning and implementing sustainable
development; and</LI>
<LI>Developing a menu of energy efficiency and renewable energy programs
that fit
the unique needs of your community.</LI></UL>
<P>If your community would like to request sustainable development assistance,
please fill in the request form below, or contact us at the following address:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development<BR>U.S.
Department of
Energy<BR>Office of Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy<BR>Denver Regional Support Office<BR>1617 Cole Boulevard<BR>Golden, CO  80401<BR>Toll-Free Phone:  800/363-3732<BR>Fax: 30
3/275-4830<BR>
E-mail: <A HREF="mailto:sustainable.development@hq.doe.gov">sustainable.development@hq.doe.gov</A> 
<BR>World Wide Web: <A HREF="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov">
http://www.sustainable.doe.gov</A></P>
<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="middle" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER> 
<H3>Contact <A NAME="Support">Support</A> Offices</H3>
<P><B>OFFICE OF ENERGY EFFICIENCY AND RENEWABLE </B><B>ENERGY REGIONAL
SUPPORT OFFICES</B></P>
<P><I>Additional help on sustainable development programs, especially related
to energy, is available from your </I><I>state energy office and from DOE's
regional support offices.</I></P>
<P><B>BOSTON REGION</B></P>
