<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sustainable Development Projects</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>
<P></P>
<CENTER><H1>Center of Excellence<BR>for Sustainable Development<BR>Projects as of 10/3/96</H1></CENTER><P></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- -------------------ct  12/4/96------------------------------------------------------------------------>


<P><B><I>Sustainable Communities Video Series</I></B><P>
American Ideas and Designs, Inc., d/b/a Greening America, will produce a video series of thirteen 27-minute stand-alone programs designed to be a set that will provide an overall pattern of sustainable communities. An additional 25 three-to-five minute video &quot;vignettes&quot; will be developed for use as short &quot;filler&quot; videos during the course of daily programming, CD-ROM applications will be developed as well as an educational package. The educational package will include instructor's manual, exercises, contacts and resources and means to incorporate the video material into existing educational curricula and professional development continuing education programs. DOE will fund the first phase. This phase will encompass seven tasks:  (l) conduct research on the subject and summarize the findings, (2) develop story line treatments for each of the thirteen episodes in the series, (3) develop script outlines for each of the thirteen episodes, (4) conduct on-location filming and documentation in eight communities, (5) develop a full script for the first episode, (6) produce a final video for the first episode, and (7) prepare a final technical report concerning the first phase of the project.
<P><B><I>The Transatlantic Collaboration to Improve Transportation, Land Use, and Air </I></B><B><I>Quality Policy</I></B>
<P>This cooperative agreement provides the Center for Clean Air Policy with third year continuation funds to implement and document innovative policies, and demonstrate the political consensus-building and public participation processes that produce these results. They are working to ensure that these policies and processes serve as models and &quot;benchmarks&quot; for other regions throughout Europe and North America. In the coming year, the Center will articulate these &quot;benchmarks&quot; that define the current best practices in particular areas of transportation, land use, and air quality policy. More than &quot;wish list&quot; recommendations or mere case studies, these benchmarks will draw on the experiences of international experts and experiences while remaining grounded in local and regional experience.
<P><B><I>Interstate Renewable Energy Council </I></B><B><I>-</I></B><B><I> State and Local Initiatives Program</I></B>
<P>The State and Local Initiatives Program by the Interstate Renewable Energy Council is to provide education materials on renewable energy, facilitate procurement assistance and develop economic tools for decision making. The project is divided into three core activities:  (1) expanding Council's &quot;Workshop In A Box&quot; to the Urban Sector, (2) supporting educational activities to help strengthen the state and local network for renewable energy projects, and (3) writing a new chapter for the &quot;How to Value Renewable Energy: A Handbook for State Energy Officials&quot; on costs versus revenue requirements.
<P><B><I>Energy Alley</I></B>
<P>The Minnesota Environmental Initiative is a cooperative, industry-led effort committed to establishing Minnesota as a center for energy efficiency and renewable energy. Minnesota energy efficiency and renewable energy industry leaders have recognized that they share common barriers and they have agreed to collaborate on industry strategic planning through Energy Alley. The Four major projects of Energy Alley are the Sustainable City Energy Showcase, the Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy Industry Directory, Breakfast Briefings and the Success Story Energy.
<P><B><I>Environmental Technology Leadership Challenge</I></B>
<P>The Environmental Technology Challenge is a national project promoting innovative environmental technology solutions as a way to build sustainable practices in communities across America. The Challenge is led by a national coalition of local communities, businesses, federal agencies, environmental organizations and academic institutions. This Challenge coalition is working to overcome barriers to technology innovation through the identification of technology opportunities and leaders, the formation of technology projects and partnerships, and the promotion of technology success stories. The Challenge is driven by a locally-based coalition of environmental leaders in several cities who have committed to promote the use of innovative technology solutions in their communities. Challenge communities recruit businesses and institutions to &quot;take the Challenge&quot; to put technologies into action. This is a National Fish and Wildlife Foundation Project .
<P><B><I>Sustainable Development Workshops in Empowerment Zones</I></B>
<P>Under this cooperative agreement, TLC Consulting with the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development, will be responsible for the planning, organization and implementation of a series of one-day community workshops on sustainable development within up to 15 Empowerment Zones (EZ's) and Enterprise Communities (EC's). The objectives of the workshops are:
<OL>
<LI> Encourage and promote within the EZ/EC's a grassroots conversation around the challenges and available benefits to be derived from the adoption of sustainable development principles and guidelines.
<LI> Initiate a process which will support local communities in implementing sustainable development initiatives.
<LI> Help the EZ/EC's identify, secure, and put in place the necessary resources needed to build grassroots community capacity in the area of sustainable development.
<LI> Promote efficient use of resources in multiple sectors of communities/cities (i.e. residential, transportation, business).
<LI> Expose communities to innovative best practices promoting sustainable living and help communities invest monetary and planning resources wisely.
</OL>
<P><B><I>Community Lifestyle Program</I></B>
<P>The Goal of this program is to launch Global Action Plan's Community Lifestyle Campaign to create neighborhood-based EcoTeams in neighborhoods determined by the City of Baltimore. The Campaign is a neighborhood-based model for helping households adopt more sustainable lifestyle practices and then reach out to their neighbors to do the same. Global Action Plan's workbook, EcoTeam, has been tested in over 10,000 households in the U.S. and Europe. This educational methodology can be documented and transferred to other urban areas. Global Action Plan will also participate in the design of upcoming workshops for the sustainable development efforts.
<P><B><I>Joint Center For Sustainable Communities</I></B> 
<P>This cooperative agreement with the National Association of Counties' and Conference of Mayors' Joint Center will develop a strategy to educate local elected and appointed officials, encourage local policymakers to use the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development's resources to facilitate the adoption of sustainable development strategies, and capitalize on a community's existing assets to integrate economic development and resource protection that strengthens the local economic base and provides a platform for long-term sustainable development activities. The National Association of Counties is the applicant on behalf of the Conference of Mayors.
<P><B><I>Sustainable Communities Support (CESD Internet World Wide Web Site)</I></B> 
<P>This Cooperative Agreement with the National Center for Appropriate Technology is a continuation of work over the past two years to develop, update and enrich the information on the CESD Internet World Wide Web Site. The Web site provides communities a &quot;Tool Kit&quot; of work books, computer programs and data for guidance on sustainable development projects. Since being launched on March 1, 1996, the popularity of the Web site has rapidly increased. The number of Web site &quot;hits&quot; averaged 20,000 monthly in April, May and June, but jumped to 85,000 in July and 76,000 in August, giving evidence of a growing interest in sustainable development by U. S. communities.
<P><B><I>A National Town Meeting On Sustainable Energy Choices</I></B> 
<P>This video teleconference will reach 125 communities in 50 states next Spring with information about energy efficiency and renewable technologies. Renew America sponsored a similar conference in FY 1996 and received excellent reviews for the quality and organization of the workshop.
<P><B><I>Additional Sustainable Development Success Stories</I></B> 
<P>Renew America will identify 50 success stories to supplement existing data on the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development's Web site.

<P><B><I>PLACES</I></B><B><I><SUP>3</SUP></I></B><B><I> Training</I></B> 
<P>The California Energy Commission will provide training to DOE Regional Support Offices on the PLACES<SUP>3</SUP> computer software and method of its use. PLACES<SUP>3</SUP>, an Energy Yardstick, is a community planning tool which takes into account energy usage. This will be a one-time training effort, with the training taking place in Golden, Colorado. A full one-day session and two special half-day sessions are proposed.
<P><B><I>National Energy Aware Planning Guide</I></B> 
<P>The California Energy Commission will provide a 70-page local government information handout or as individual fact sheets, and separate 15-page step-by-step community energy planning process description.
<P><B><I>ICMA Sustainable Communities Outreach and Training</I></B> 
<P>The International City/County Management Association (ICMA) in collaboration with the Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development (CESD), will undertake an outreach strategy to promote sustainable development in communities nationwide. The goal of this project is to build awareness of sustainability and to help local governments integrate sustainability into their day-to-day decision-making process. ICMA will convene a roundtable with CESD, during its annual conference on October 7-8 to stimulate discussion and creative problem-solving of issues facing local governments. In the Spring of 1997, ICMA will coordinate a one-half day education and training session that will focus on the practical application of sustainability techniques in local governments at its state association meeting.
<P><B><I>Florida Energy House</I></B>
<P>Florida Energy House, Inc. will combine a charrette process with a conference to create a proceedings and case study about sustainability, community planning and economic development. This project will focus on creating a town plan for an area in Sarasota County, Florida, where development is under way. The Florida House will partner with several other entities to perform the task.
<P><B><I>Seniors' Resource Center Transit</I></B><B><I>-</I></B><B><I>on</I></B><B><I>-</I></B><B><I>Demand</I></B>
<P>This project will demonstrate the computerized Transit-on-demand system, and improve transportation service for local senior citizens and the physically challenged, while helping reduce energy use, air pollution, and traffic congestion. The Seniors' Resource Center of Jefferson County, CO will implement the first Denver-area field test for the National Renewable Energy Laboratory (NREL) Transit-on-Demand system. The NREL computer-based transportation dispatch and communications system will allow the Center's 16 vehicles to be used more efficiently. It will offer senior citizens and physically challenged customers a timely transportation option by using the Global Positioning Satellite system to identify the closest vehicle and the best route.
<P><B><I>Reduction of Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT)</I></B> 
<P>The City of Boulder, Colorado in an effort to reduce vehicle miles traveled and to educate citizens on alternative transportation options will provide a comprehensive pre-trip resource guide in the Boulder area. This Internet Home Page will include transportation and related services from City Departments as well as the Regional Transit District, Denver Regional Council Of Governments, and the Boulder Energy Conservation Center services.
<P><B><I>Global Environmental Options (GEO)</I></B>
<P>The purpose of this grant with Global Environmental Options (GEO) is to:  (1) conduct an inventory of key existing and planned Web sites as well as key contacts in the printed media on<B> </B>sustainable development, and (2) organize a meeting later this calendar year (scheduled for December 16-17, 1996) to foster better coordination between the various organizations currently engaged in, or planning sustainable development outreach on the Internet. The goal of this project is to identify current information gaps; define opportunities to avoid unnecessary duplication of effort; and encourage enhanced coordination among these various organizations in their currently separate efforts to assist communities better understand and practice sustainable development.

