<HEAD>
<TITLE>nwconfer.htm </TITLE>
<LINK REL="Index" HREF="htindex.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>
<P></P>
<CENTER><H2>Northwest Sustainable Building Technology Conference<BR>-Building With Value-</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER><BR>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
     
<P>Public Technology, Inc. (PTI) and the City of Seattle are the major co-sponsors and organizers of the Northwest Sustainable Building Technology Conference:  Building with Value, to be held October 1997 in Seattle, Washington.  This Northwest conference is the second regional Sustainable Building Technology Conference to be organized by PTI.  The first conference was held in the Mid-Atlantic region in March 1996 as part of PTI&#146;s on-going Sustainable Building Technology Program.  Also, this Northwest Conference will be the second green-building conference for Seattle, which hosted the 1993 Building with Value event.
<H3>Why Build Sustainably?</H3> 
Buildings designed, renovated, constructed, operated and demolished in an 
environmentally sound and energy-efficient manner benefit the environment, 
building owners and the community.  For example, increased energy and water 
efficiency will enhance resource conservation and reduce the need for 
utilities to build new facilities.  The addition of increased day-lighting 
in building design can improve productivity and occupant health. 
Implementing source-reduction and waste-recycling policies can reduce 
disposal costs and prolong local waste-disposal capacity.  Carefully 
considering public transportation access to buildings will reduce traffic 
congestion and improve air quality.
<H3>The goals of the Building with Value conference include:</H3>

<UL>  
<LI>   introduce green-building technologies and sustainable-community concepts 
to public officials, academic representatives, and other public and private 
building owners and managers;

<LI> provide architects, builders, developers and other building-related 
professionals with up-to-date information on the economic and environmental 
benefits of building green;

<LI>provide resources, such as regional experts and product sources, so that 
building owners and managers can take the next steps to implement these technologies;

<LI>provide a forum for interchange of ideas to promote green building between     
government representatives and design and building professionals; and 

<LI> provide the opportunity to highlight local and regional green 
construction-related businesses at the workshops and exhibit hall.
</UL>
     
<H3>Building with Value Conference</H3>     
We expect 400 to 600 participants who will represent a spectrum of public 
and private groups involved in making sustainable building a reality in the 
Northwest.  These include officials from local, state and federal agencies; 
representatives from the building industry; product manufacturers and 
suppliers; architects, engineers and other design professionals; utility 
company employees; and representatives from public school systems, 
universities and colleges.
<P>     
<P>This conference will focus on the Northwest&#146;s climate and its building 
styles 
and development patterns, but it also will appeal to all those interested in 
sustainable building across the country.  The three-day agenda will include 
discussions of green-building principles and case studies, and in-depth 
interactive sessions for participants.
<P>     
<H3>Conference Co-Sponsors and Organizers</H3>     
PTI is the non-profit technology research and demonstration organization of 
the National League of Cities, National Association of Counties, and the 
International City/County Management Association.  PTI&#146;s members represent 
some of the largest cities and counties around the U.S.  The PTI Urban 
Consortium, a select group of 50 cities and counties, make up the membership 
of its task forces.  These focus on four areas:  environment, energy, 
transportation and telecommunications.
<P>     
With its members, PTI is actively involved in testing and adopting 
innovative technologies that benefit local governments.  The Environmental 
and Energy Task Forces have been involved in Sustainable Building Technology 
projects for more than 15 years, and represent some of the leaders in this 
field.  They include Seattle, Austin, Hennepin County, Portland, Denver and 
San Francisco.
<P>     
The City of Seattle&#146;s three utilities-Seattle City Light, Seattle Water 
Department and Seattle Solid Waste Utility-will act as the main Northwest 
regional co-sponsors.  The City, and its citizens, have undertaken a number 
of efforts that indicate their commitment to sustainable principles.  For 
example, the City Utilities are working with the Seattle school district to 
develop a best management practices handbook for resource-efficient design 
and construction of schools.
<P>     
<H3>Development of Conference Sponsorships</H3>
PTI and the City of Seattle are currently contacting public and private 
organizations in the Northwest and nationally to seek their support and 
co-sponsorship for the 1997 Conference.  PTI&#146;s first Sustainable Building 
Technology Conference was co-sponsored by:  U.S. Environmental Protection 
Agency and Department of Energy, Electric Power Research Institute, U.S. 
Green Building Council, George Washington University Institute for the 
Environment, and a local electric utility. Again we are enlisting national, 
regional and local supporters.
<P>     
Co-sponsorship will provide an opportunity to help set the agenda for the 
1997 conference, to be recognized in all conference publicity, and to 
further this and other green building initiatives in the Northwest.
<P>     
To become a co-sponsor of the Northwest Sustainable Building Conference: 
Building with Value contact Michael Wood-Lewis (Environmental Program 
Director) at PTI (202-626-2455 or 
<A HREF="mailto:wood-lewis@pti.nw.dc.us">wood-lewis@pti.nw.dc.us</A>.<BR><BR>

<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<BR>Micheal Wood-Lewis
<BR>Environmental Program Director
<BR>202-626-2455 direct
<BR><A HREF="mailto:wood-lewis@pti.nw.dc.us">wood-lewis@pti.nw.dc.us</A><P></P>
Public Technology, Inc.
<BR>1301 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW
<BR>Wahsington, DC  20004-1793
<BR>202-626-2498 fax
<BR>800-852-4934
<BR><A HREF="http://pti.nw.dc.us">http://pti.nw.dc.us</A><BR>

