<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>1997 National Town Meeting</TITLE>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>
<P></P>
<H2>Announcing the 1997 National Town Meeting:</H2>
<H3>Environmentally Sustainable Energy Choices</H3>

<B><I>Produced by Renew America</I></B>
<BR><B><I>Sponsored by The U.S. Department of Energy</I></B>
<BR><B><I>Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development</I></B><P></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- -----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------><BR>
<P>Many of you participated in the 1996 National Town Meeting to discuss <I>Environmentally </I><I>Sustainable Communities.</I>  There were 89 downlink sites in 39 states with 10,000 citizens and organizations participating.  We hope you will help us exceed this participation in 1997.  The National Awards Council&#146;s Town Meeting Committee recently selected another critical issue for discussion next year.
<P>The 1997 National Teleconference and Town Meeting to be held on <B>February 19, 1997</B> will address <I>Environmentally Sustainable Energy Choices.</I>  In addition to a live audience in Washington, D.C., the ninety-minute interactive video conference is designed to bring together 15,000 viewers from 100 downlink sites to talk with national and community leaders about making environmentally sustainable energy choices.  Community leaders from 47 communities have already confirmed their participation in this town meeting.  You are invited to join them!
<H3>Why Focus on Energy?</H3>
<P>Although many of us think about energy use only during an energy shortage, the choices we make about our everyday energy activities &#151; how we get to work and school, what kind of lighting we buy and what kind of appliances we purchase &#151; have a significant impact on both the economy and our environment.  In fact, many organizations such as Worldwatch believe that energy will be the most important subject of the next decade.
<P>If we are to help ensure a sustainable future for ourselves and our global neighbors, we must work together.  The National Town Meeting&#146;s unique interactive format will enable community members from across the country to discuss problems and share examples of successful environmentally sustainable energy initiatives in both rural and urban areas, and to demonstrate how communities, environmentalists, businesses and government agencies can become partners in promoting sustainable energy choices.
<H3>Join the National Town Meeting</H3>
<P>To help ensure that local communities can focus on energy choices within their own communities, Local Co-Sponsorship Committees can host structured discussions before and after the teleconference to discuss local sustainable energy opportunities.  If your organization would like to serve as a Local Co-Sponsor in your community, contact Robin Durston at 202-232-2252.  Co-Sponsors will be sent organizing and study materials.
<P>During the ninety-minute, national teleconference&#146;s first hour, five panelists representing government, the environment, business and local communities will offer their perspectives on environmentally sustainable energy choices.  The final half hour will feature questions from the viewers.
<P>The invited national panelists and moderator include:
<P><B>The Hon. Hazel O&#146;Leary, </B>Secretary, U.S. Department of Energy
<P><B>S. David Freeman, </B>Chairman, Solar Electric Light Fund (confirmed)
<P><B>Harry V. Quadracci,</B> Chairman and CEO, Quad-Graphics
<P><B>The Hon. Vera Katz,</B> Mayor of Portland, Oregon (confirmed)
<P><B>Amory Lovins,</B> President, The Rocky Mountain Institute (confirmed)
<P><B>Deborah Potter, </B> Moderator, The Poynter Institute for Media Studies (confirmed)
<P><B>Already Confirmed Downlink Sites</B>
<P>Forty-two downlink sites across the country have already been confirmed, including locations in Atlanta, Baltimore, Chattanooga, Chicago, Des Moines, Fayetteville, Golden, Los Angeles, Madison, Minneapolis, Mobile, Philadelphia, Phoenix, Portland, Saint Louis, Salt Lake City, Seattle and Topeka.
<P>For a complete list of current downlink sites and Local Co-Sponsors, contact Robin Durston at 202-232-2252.
