<HEAD>
<TITLE>CESD: BUILDING ENERGY</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A><CENTER><H2><B>BUILDING ENERGY</B></H2></CENTER>
<P></P>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->

<P>
<CENTER>
<P>
<H3><B>Insuring a Sustainable Future</B>
<BR>
<I><B>Two Conferences, Workshops and a Trade Show</B></I>
<BR>
<B>March 12-15, 1997</B>
<BR>
Radisson Hotel and Conference Center
<BR>
Cromwell, Connecticut</H3><P></P>

<B>Architects</B>
<BR>
<B>Builders and Contractors</B>
<BR>
<B>Building Code Officials and Administrators</B>
<BR>
<B>Building Owners</B>
<BR>
<B>Engineers</B>
<BR>
<B>Environmental Professionals</B>
<BR>
<B>Insurers and Financiers</B>
<BR>
<B>Investors</B>
<BR>
<B>Landscape Architects</B>
<BR>
<B>Product Manufactures and Distributors</B>
<BR>
<B>Regional and Urban Planners</B>
<BR>
<B>Students and Educators</B>
<BR>
<B>Utilities</B>
<BR>
<B> and Other Interested in Insuring a Sustainable Future</B></CENTER>

<BR>
<B>NESEA</B>
<BR>
Northeast Sustainable Energy Association
<BR>
50 Miles Street
<BR>
Greenfield, MA 01301-3212
<BR>
TEL 413-774-6051  FAX 413-774-6053
<BR>
email: <A HREF="mailto:nesea@nesea.org">nesea@nesea.org</A>
<P><!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<B><CENTER><H2>BUILDING ENERGY '97: INSURING A SUSTAINABLE FUTURE</H2></CENTER></B>
<P>
<B><H3>Two Conferences, Workshops and Trade Show</H3></B>
<P>
<B>Building Energy '97</B> will again combine the best of NESEA's
Quality Building Conference with NESEA's RENEW '97, bringing together
experts and decision makers from the advanced building and renewable
energy industries to describe how quality construction practice,
emerging technologies and global market opportunities will shape
communities of the future.
<P>
<B>Building Energy '97</B> will provide a launching point for
sustainable development in the next millennium, emphasizing green
buildings and renewable energy as the foundation.  Architects
and builders, code officials, land-use planners and landscape
architects will discuss how communities can work together to make
sustainable development standard practice.  Environmental, industry
and utility professionals will outline the steps for developing
an infrastructure that allows us to step lightly on the planet
as we meet the needs of a growing global population.  Finally,
for the first time at Building Energy, insurance and financial
experts will participate in the analysis of renewable energy and
sustainable building not only as strategies for loss mitigation,
but as the key investment opportunity for &quot;Insuring a Sustainable
Future.&quot;
<P>
<B>The 13th Annual Quality Building Conference</B> will explore
how to build sustainably and be on budget.  Participants will
gather tips on how to design and remodel residential and light
commercial buildings with green building materials and techniques
that are not only cost effective, but also resource efficient.
 A poster session highlighting exemplary sustainable communities
throughout the northeast will be on display.  Presenters for this
year's Quality Building Conference include:
<UL>
	<LI>Terry Brennan, Consultant, Camroden Associates
	<LI>Steve Loken, Center for Resourceful Building Technologies
</UL>


<P>
<I><B>Session topics will include:</B></I>
<UL>
	<LI>Design Tools for Placemaking
	<LI>Marketing of Construction Site Waste
	<LI>Sustainable Yield Forestry
	<LI>Alternative Roof Systems
	<LI>HERS, Builder Certification and Energy Mortgages
</UL>



<B>RENEW '97 will focus on the latest developments in</B> renewable
technologies in the context of real market applications, highlighting
how those technologies can find a niche in an evolving utility
environment as well as a booming global marketplace.  RENEW '97
will also explore how accelerating cost competitiveness has made
renewables the growth industry for the 21st century.  Key presenters
for RENEW '97 include:
<UL>
	<LI>Dr. Jeremy Leggett, Greenpeace International
	<LI>Bill Becker, US DOE, Center for Excellence in Sustainable
	Development
	<LI>Mark Kelley, Building Science Engineering
</UL>

<P>
<I><B>Session topics will include:</B></I>
<UL>
	<LI>Climate Change Equals Market Change
	<LI>Cutting Property Loss With Sustainable Construction
	<LI>Mitigating Insurance Loss in Natural Disasters
	<LI>Opportunities for Renewables in a Competitive Utility Environment
</UL>



<B><H3>Pre-Conference Workshops</H3></B>
<B>March 12, 1997</B>

<BLOCKQUOTE>These Workshops are designed to provide attendees with basic building
science principles and will lay the groundwork for the conference
and advanced workshops.  Topics include:</BLOCKQUOTE>
<UL>
	<LI>Building a Straw Bale Wall (David Eisenberg, Director, Development
	Center for Appropriate Technology; Paul Lacinski, GreenSpace Collaborative)
	<LI>Ecological Landscaping and Wastewater Treatment (Alex Wilson,
	Environmental Building News)
	<LI>Integrated Photovoltaics for Builders and Architects (Steven
	Strong, Solar Design Associates)
	<LI>Surfing the Internet for Renewable Energy Listings
	<LI>Sustainable Design Strategies (Marc Rosenbaum, PE)
</UL>


<B><H3>Advanced Workshops</H3></B>

<B>March 15, 1997
</B>


<UL>
	<LI>ECH Builders Certification Program
	<LI>Sustainable Hotel Retrofit (Steven Strong, Solar Design Associates)
	<LI>Small House Design (Tim Maloney, Architect, One Design)
	<LI>Building Codes and Sustainability (David Eisenberg, Director,
	Development Center for Appropriate Technology)
</UL>


<B><H3>Trade Show, Exhibitors Reception and &quot;My Favorite Tool&quot;
Contest</H3></B>

Products and services for the design, construction and operation
of energy efficient and environmentally sustainable buildings
and communities will be on display during the two-day general
conference.  Exhibits will demonstrate the latest technologies
from across the country.  The exhibit area will be the site of
an evening reception and daily refreshment breaks.  A unique feature
of this year's exhibitor reception will be a contest among product
users, hosted by Terry Brennan and Steve Loken, highlighting favorite
tools and building materials.  This event will be open to the
public at a nominal fee.
<P>
<B><H3>Design Competition</H3></B>

The Quality Building Conference Design Competition recognizes
and publicizes the efforts of builders and designers who incorporate
sustainable and repeatable, energy and resource conservation systems
into their buildings.  Prizes are available for new construction
or remodel projects in each category.  Award-winning projects
will be presented and discussed at NESEA's 1997 Building Energy
conference.  The application deadline is February 15, 1997.  For
a full description of categories, criteria for judging and submission
requirements, please contact NESEA for an Information Request
Form.
<P>
<B><H2>BUILDING ENERGY '97: The Affordable Conference</H2></B>
<BR>
<B><H3>Registration</H3></B>

The registration fee for the two day conference includes admission
to all sessions and plenaries, proceedings, lunches, coffee breaks
and admission to the trade show and exhibitor reception.  There
are substantial discounts for early registration, NESEA members,
and for building tradespeople, architects, non-profits and seniors
as well as for students.  Work exchange scholarships are available
on a first come, first served basis. 
<P>
<B><H3>Accommodations</H3></B>

The Radisson Hotel and Conference Center in Cromwell, Connecticut
will serve as the conference hotel.  The Radisson (Exit 21 off
1-91) offers free parking and shuttle transportation service to
Bradley International Airport and is equipped with an indoor pool,
sauna and exercise facility.  A special conference room rate of
$59-$79 for single occupancy and $69-$89 double occupancy per
night is reserved until 10 February 1997. To reserve a room, please
call the Radisson Hotel and Conference Center at (860) 635-2000
and be sure to mention NESEA to receive the special rate.
<P>
<B><H3>For more information regarding Registration Forms and Membership:</H3></B>

Mail, phone or fax your request to:
<BR>
NESEA
<BR>
50 Miles Street
<BR>
Greenfield, MA 01301-3212
<BR>
413-774-6051 or FAX 413-774-6053

<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=1>
<B><H3>About the Organizers</H3></B>
The Northeast Sustainable Energy Association (NESEA) is the organizer
of Building Energy '97.  NESEA, a non-profit membership organization,
is the nation's leading regional association involved in promoting
awareness, understanding and development of non-polluting renewable
energy technologies.  Headquartered in Greenfield, Massachusetts,
NESEA is celebrating its 22nd year of working successfully in
the fields of building construction, renewable energy and transportation.
 NESEA organizes major technical conferences and the American
<I>Tour de Sol</I> (a road rally championship for electric vehicles),
and publishes the <I>Northeast Sun</I> magazine and the <I>NESEA
Resource Guide.</I>
<P>
<B><H3>Title Sponsor:</H3></B>
Northeast Utilities
<P>


<B><H3>Sponsors:</H3></B>
PNL/Batelle National Labs
<BR>
U.S. Department of Energy: Region 1
<P>

<B><H3>Trade Show Sponsors:</H3></B>
Kawneer Company, Inc.
<BR>
Solarex Corporation
<P>

<B><H3>Supporters:</H3></B>
American Public Power Association
<BR>
The Boston Society of Architects
<BR>
Conservation Services Group 
<BR>
Henry MacLean, AIA, Timeless Architecture (Building Section and Floor Plan)
<BR>
Passive Solar Industries Council
<P>

<H3>Sponsorship Opportunities</H3>
Sponsorship gives your company a leadership opportunity to incorporate
its image and marketing  needs into a high profile, landmark event.
 A wide range of sponsorship opportunities are available, including
conference luncheons and refreshment breaks, design competition
awards, Quality Building Council annual banquet, &quot;My Favorite
Tool&quot; contest, silent auction and workshops.  For a complete
packet of sponsorship opportunities and benefits, contact NESEA
for an Information Request Form.<BR>

