<HEAD>
<TITLE>CESD: SOLAR ELECTRIFICATION 1997</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR = #FFFFFF>
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page =">
<!-- ---------------------------------------------- CT 11-7-96 ----------------------------------------->
<H2><CENTER>International Centre for Application of Solar Energy</CENTER></H2>

<CENTER><B><FONT  SIZE=+2>SOLAR ELECTRIFICATION 1997</FONT></B><BR>
<BR>
<B>First Announcement and Call for Papers and Registration </B>
<BR>
<B>International Conference and Exhibition on Village Electrification</B>
<BR>
<B>Through Renewable Energy</B>
<BR>
<B>March 3-5, 1997</B>
<BR>
<B>Hotel Taj Palace</B>
<BR>
<B>New Delhi, India</B></CENTER>
<P><CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><P></CENTER>
The UNIDO International Centre for Application of Solar Energy
(CASE) invites you to participate in an International Conference
and Exhibition in Village Electrification through Renewable Energy
which will be held at the Hotel Taj Palace in New Delhi, March
3-5, 1997.
<P>
Where conventional grid supply systems cannot be extended economically to remote villages, renewable energy sources offer the greatest promise.  Despite ambitious and expensive rural electrification
programmes in developing nations, two billion people are still without electricity, and so they lack such basics as lighting, communications, primary health care facilities and safe drinking water.  The New Delhi conference will focus on delivering renewable energy solutions to this fundamental need for those living in
developing countries.
<P>
India is a logical venue for this conference because of its exciting opportunities for promoting the use of renewable energy technologies.  Apart from the  scale of the potential market, India's suppliers, project developers and consultants are well equipped to contribute.
<P>
India has made tremendous progress in its industrial and agriculture sectors, however it lags behind in meeting the energy demand.  As a result India is currently facing a severe shortage of power
supply.  There are almost 85,000 unelectrified villages.  It is reported that out of these 85,000 villages, 30,000 villages cannot be electrified by conventional electric grids due to the high cost of the grid extensions.  Renewable energy is the only feasible adoption to energize these villages.  In addition industrial growth
calls for a greater energy demand and raises opportunities for the installation of large capacity wind farms, solar thermal and solar photovoltaic power plants. 
<P>
Because of the important nature of this conference, the Ministry of  Nonconventional Energy Sources (MNES), Rural Electrification Corporation (REC), Indian Renewable Energy Development Agency
(IREDA), Rajasthan Energy Development Agency (REDA), Nonconventional Energy Development Agency of UP (NEDA), Khadi and Village Industries Corporation (KVIC), and several other government and private organizations and industries have extended their support to CASE to organize this conference in New Delhi.
<P>
The scope of the conference will be broad.  The Keynote addresses will be delivered by well known authorities in the field of Renewable Energy, Multilateral Bank and Global Environmental Facility (GEF)
Officials, Project Developers, Senior Indian Government Officials and Consultants.
<P>
Selected quality papers are welcomed from researchers, project developers, policy planners, financing institutions, industries, marketers and consultants on the following topics:
<OL>
<LI>Solar photovoltaic systems 
<LI>Wind energy systems
<LI>Remote area power supplies (RAPS)
<LI>Mini/Micro hydro including river flow turbines and run of the river systems
<LI>Solar thermal power generation
<LI>Health, drinking water and passive rural architecture
<LI>Biomass and biogas
<LI>Rural communication
<LI>Project management
<LI>Remote monitoring techniques
<LI>Financing of renewable energy projects
</OL>

<P>

<P>
The Conference will provide an excellent opportunity to meet with Indian Government, World Bank and GEF officials, researchers, project developers and financiers and the leading players in the field of renewable energy expertise.
<P>
<STRONG>EXHIBITION:</STRONG>
<BR>
Exhibition on the latest renewable energy technologies from Australia, Denmark, Germany, India, Israel, Japan, Netherlands, Singapore, South Korea, Sweden, U.K. and USA will facilitate immediate market
and joint venture opportunities for interested firms.
<P>
<B>INDIA</B>
<BR>
India is the 7th largest country in the world.  It possesses a richness and diversity in culture, people, languages, geographic
and climatic conditions.  A series of economic reforms aimed at deregulating the economy and stimulating foreign investment has moved India firmly into the front of the rapidly growing Asian Region and unleashed the latent strength of a complex and fast changing nation.  It has recognized the need to develop its renewable energy sector and offers a number of significant incentives for the promotion of renewable energy technologies.  The Ministry for Nonconventional Energy Sources is positioned directly under
the Prime Minister and plays an important role in developing renewable energy promotional policies.  The Indian Renewable Energy Development Agency is the banking organization that has been established to
lend soft finance to renewable energy industries and utility projects. There are more than 35 state government nodal agencies which are responsible for program implementation and execution of renewable
energy projects.  The demand for renewable energy is growing at a faster rate than anywhere else in the world and as a result manufacturers of wind turbines and solar equipment are already
establishing joint venture manufacturing with Indian partners. <P>

<STRONG>POST CONFERENCE TOURS:</STRONG> Two special post conference tours have
been planned for Conference participants.
<P>
<B>JAIPUR: </B>
<BR>
Jaipur is the capital city of Rajasthan.  It is known as &quot;Pink City&quot; because most of the old buildings are made from pink coloured stones.  Jaipur is about 250km from Delhi and is famous for its classic architecture, forts and astronomical observatory.  It attracts millions of visitors from India and abroad each year.
<P>
<B>AGRA:</B>
<BR>
Agra is famous for the &quot;Taj Mahal&quot;, Red Fort and Fatehpur
Sikri.  There is no doubt the  Taj Mahal is one of the world's
most desired tourist destinations.  Due to its unique beauty,
it attracts a large number of tourists from all over the world.
 The Taj Mahal is a symbol of love and was constructed by the
Mogul King Shahjehan in the memory of his wife Mum Taj Mahal.


<P><CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><P></CENTER><P>


For more information please contact: Dr. Dilawar Singh, Co-chairman
<BR>
International Conference and Exhibition on Village Electrification
through Renewable Energy
<BR>
c/- CASE, Level 3, 81 St. Georges Terrace, Perth 
<BR>
Western Australia 6000 (Australia)
<BR>
Phone: (+619) 321-7600  Facsimile: (+619) 321-7497
<BR>
Email:  <A HREF="mailto:case@wantree.com.au">case@wantree.com.au</A>

<P><CENTER><IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><P></CENTER>

