<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>barriers.htm</TITLE>
<LINK REL="ToC" HREF="httoc.htm">
<LINK REL="Next" HREF="centexel.htm"></HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<P><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="Center of Excellence for Sustainable Development, a Project of the US DOE's Office of  Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy"></A></P><P>
<CENTER><P><H2>BREAKING THROUGH BARRIERS:</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><P><H3>Balancing Ecology and Economics<BR>1996</H3></CENTER>
</P><CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P><B>THE CHALLENGE</B></P>
<P>How should this parcel of land owned by the military be developed over the long term in order to embrace the concepts of sustainability?  How will the Pensacola Naval Complex embrace new functions and new programs inherited from another base along with its own already &#147;on the board&#148; growth and development?  How will the Pensacola base incorporate the inevitable additions into its existing fabric?  And most importantly, how will impacts on the surrounding community be addressed?  As Stuart Brand aptly explores in his book, <I>How Buildings Learn,</I> This military base must look at how <I>it </I>will learn.</P>
<P>In formulating its new identity, can the Pensacola Naval Complex become more intimately connected with the earth, more energy efficient, more economically productive, and a teacher to us all?  Can the base increase its &#147;value&#148; to the larger community?  Can the base be a model for &#147;sustainable development&#148;?</P>
<P><B>THE PURPOSE</B></P>
<P>&#147;Breaking Through Barriers&#148; is a competition to foster creative interdisciplinary thinking in the area of sustainable design, where economics and environmentalism are inexorably linked.  The competition is a venue for adventurous learning.  Integrated teams will critically assess and propose design solutions to a REAL economic and environmental problem:  an existing military base&#146;s growth and development impacted by the realignments and closures of other bases due to government initiatives and other activities.  This competition will focus on the <B>Pensacola Naval Complex</B> in Florida that is accommodating the services of the Naval Air Technical Training Center relocated from Memphis, Tennessee.</P>

<CENTER><P><TABLE>
<TR><TD><B>JURORS</B></TD><TD><B>SPONSORS</B></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Donald Aitken, Ph.D. </TD><TD>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>William Becker</TD><TD>Naval Facilities Engineering Command(NAVFAC)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Robert Berkebile, FAIA</TD><TD>U.S. Department of Energy (DOE)</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Carol Browner (invited) </TD><TD>Geraghty &amp; Miller, Inc.</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>William D. Browning</TD><TD>Acurex Environmental</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Raymond Dehn, AIAS</TD><TD>Piedmont Olsen Hensley</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>William A. McDonough, AIA</TD><TD>Environmental Building News</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>RADM David J. Nash, P.E., CEC (invited)</TD><TD>Interior Concerns</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Sim Van der Ryn</TD><TD></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Virginia Wetherell (invited)</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE></CENTER>

<P>In cooperation with the AIA Committee on the Environment (AIA COTE) and the American Institute of Architecture Students (AIAS).</P>
<P><B>ELIGIBILITY</B></P>
<P>Participation is open to interdisciplinary teams, members of which shall be enrolled in universities possessing, as a minimum, a resident department of environmental science, engineering, or architecture/design.  Teams should include, but are not limited to, a minimum of four (4) members - one architecture/design student, one environmental science student, one economics student, plus members from any other disciplines such as agriculture, planning political science, engineering or others.</P>
<P>Application shall be through the university&#146;s design or environmental science department.</P>
<P><B>THE DESIGN PROBLEM</B></P>
<P>To develop a new master plan for the Naval Air Technical Training Center and the Adjoining installations in Pensacola, Florida and to design an individual base structure renovation/addition or a new structure appropriate to your master plan.</P>
<P><B>EVALUATION CRITERIA</B></P>
<P>The winning designs will demonstrate an integrated design approach to sustainable development.  The jury will consider creativity and feasibility of ideas and innovations in their overall evaluations.</P>
<P>Successful projects should demonstrate:</P><UL>
<LI>&#147;sustainability,&#148; including use of life-cycle assessment and life-cycle costing strategies,
<LI>a positive impact on the ecology of the site by working with nature to restore biodiversity and balance,
<LI>the effective and efficient use of materials, systems, and other resources,
<LI>energy efficiency with respect to sources and systems, maintenance and operation, and appropriate technologies,
<LI>the concept of "reduce, reuse, recycle,"
<LI>a reduction of &#147;waste&#148;,
<LI>a &#147;healthy&#148; approach to air and water quality, and to overall occupant productivity.
</UL>

<P><B>TIME LINE</B></P>
<TABLE>
<TR><TD>Registration Opens&#151;June 15, 1996</TD><TD>Jury Convenes in Washington&#151;January 10, 1997</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Competition Packets Available<BR>&#151;August 1, 1996</TD><TD>Winners Announced&#151;February 4, 1997</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Submissions Due&#151;December 3, 1996</TD><TD></TD></TR>
</TABLE>



<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>
<P></P>

<P><B>JURY AND AWARDS</B></P>

<TABLE>
