<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>CESD: A Prudent Investment </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>
<P></P>
<H2>A Prudent Investment</H2><P></P>
<B>by Christine Ervin</B>
<BR><B>Assistant Secretary for Energy Efficiency and Renewable Energy</B>
<BR><B>NREL in Review, </B>
<B>Summer 1996</B><P></P>


<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->


<P>In their era of deregulation and budget cutbacks, we continue to hear the argument that the federal government has no business being involved in so-called &quot;free energy markets.&quot;  This sentiment is reflected in the 1997 House budget proposal, which states that &quot;the nation&#146;s energy problems will be solved by the people and industries of this country...not by government spending.&quot;
<P>Now I believe in the power and the magic of the marketplace as much as anyone.  But any student of economics knows that in the real world, cheapest is not always best.  The market forces of the moment don&#146;t always look after the nation&#146;s long-term security interests.  For example, cheap oil may be great for the economy today, but insofar as it encourages the use of more imported oil, it&#146;s not necessarily good for the nation&#146;s long-term security interests, the balance of trade, or the quality of the environment.
<P>Market purists forget that the government is already part of the marketplace simply because it&#146;s the nation&#146;s largest consumer of goods and services.  They claim that federal researchers are trying to impose their own judgments and personal preferences on the private sector.  And they mistakenly conclude that our efforts to develop new energy sources have failed.
<P>To the contrary, government-industry partnerships have made enormous strides in lowering the cost and improving the reliability of renewable energy technologies.  This progress has led Royal Dutch Shell&#146;s strategic planning unit to project that renewable energy will become cost-competitive with conventional energy sources beginning around the year 2020.  By 2050, more than half the world&#146;s energy will probably be supplied by renewable energy technologies.  This scenario is based on a cold, hard analysis of world energy supply and demand options, environmental drivers, and capital markets.  And it will occur naturally, with little government regulation, as the detrimental effects of conventional energy use become obvious.
<P>Continued research is essential to make the transition to this alternative energy future.  But there are immediate benefits as well.  Within the next five years, advances in energy could create more than 300,000 new jobs, reduce U.S. business costs by $9 billion, free up $8 billion of spendable income for American families, and open $425 billion in foreign markets for U.S. goods and services.
<P>We can only reap these benefits by continuing to address the needs of our industry partners.  This is not corporate subsidy or interference with free markets.  It is a prudent investment in new energy industries that will sustain America&#146;s economic development throughout the next century and beyond.  
<P>From the laboratory bench to the global marketplace, we need to broaden and deepen the strategic alliances that will make this future a reality.
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P></P> 
<P><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="/rsc/left_arr.gif"></A></P>
