<HEAD>
<TITLE>CESD: Creating Sustainable Cities</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>

<CENTER><H1>Creating Sustainable Cities</H1>

<!-- ---------------------------------------ct 12/4/96---------------------------------------------->
<H4><I>by Bruce Green</I></H4>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER><BR>
NREL in Review<BR>Summer 1996<P>

<P><I>New approaches to city planning help preserve<BR> the quality of life for future generations</I></CENTER>
<P>Like many older cities in the eastern United States, Newark, NJ, has experienced decades of over-crowding and a depletion of natural resources that reduces the quality of life for many of its citizens.  But this trend is being reversed thanks to a concept called sustainability.  
<P>More than just the latest buzzword in urban planning, sustainability has become a key guiding principle of communities throughout the nation.  
<P>The United Nations defines sustainability as development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their needs as well.  It&#146;s a collective effort on the part of local groups to make sure that urban centers remain livable instead of turning into slums devoid of jobs and economic growth.
<P>Here are two examples of the progress that can be made by adopting a broader vision of urban quality.
<H3>Newark&#146;s Vision Reduces Taxes And Generates Revenue</H3>
<P>Newark&#146;s ground breaking programs include an environmental master plan with specific actions and ordinances to help catapult the community onto sustainable economic ground.  In the past 10 years, this vision has been honored by the United Nations, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, and the International Council for Local Environmental Initiatives.
<P>Some of Newark&#146;s most successful steps toward a sustainable future involve recycling.  A program established in 1987 now helps the city recycle more than 50% of its solid waste, saving taxpayers more than $15.4 million in disposal fees and generating almost $167,000 in revenue from the sale of recycled material.
<P>Two Subsequent ordinances support these recycling efforts.  In 1988, the Municipal Council approved an ordinance requiring proposals for new building developments to incorporate provisions for separating, collecting, and disposing of recyclable materials.  The ordinance applies to new housing developments of 50 or more single-family units, 25 or more multi-family units, or 1,000 square feet or more of commercial/industrial space.  Another ordinance ensures a market for these recycled materials by requiring city agencies to purchase recycled products.
<P>Other changes implemented by the city include:
<BLOCKQUOTE>&#149; Installing high-pressure sodium street lights to replace less efficient fluorescent, incandescent, and mercury-vapor units.
<P>&#149; Adopting a landmark law restricting the use and disposal of ozone-depleting chemicals. 
<P>&#149; Creating an Urban Gardening Program that encourages transformation of vacant lots into community gardens.
<P>&#149; Banning retail food establishments in the city from using two forms of plastic polystyrene and polyvinylchloride unless they recycle at least 60% of their packaging.
 </BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Newark also established a business development program, called &quot;Planet Newark,&quot; for companies in the recycling industry.  The city is already home to more than 70 recycling firms employing more than 1,000 people.  These firms generate millions of dollars in economic development and revenues.  City officials believe that Planet Newark also will create a &quot;ripple effect&quot; of economic activity and increased tax revenues to support additional environmentally-friendly initiatives.
<H3>Partnerships Revitalize Chattanooga</H3>
<P>Concern for future generations also forced city officials in Chattanooga, TN, to consider the concept of sustainability.
<P>&quot;The children weren&#146;t staying,&quot; says Susan Kendall Tillman, director of Chattanooga Venture, an organization formed in 1984 to revitalize the decaying city.  &quot;We had to do something.  The Chattanooga Venture program lifted our goals to a community agenda instead of one sector&#146;s agenda.&quot;
<P>Recently, an innovative program called ReVision 2000 brought together residents from all walks of life, including business people, educators, politicians, parents, and teenagers.  Chattanooga Venture facilitates the program along with various other civic groups.
<P>ReVision 2000 covers topics such as city planning, economic development, environment, transportation, parks, and greenways.   When the group&#146;s goals are fully implemented, Chattanooga could have recycling and waste minimization programs, rail-bus/park-and-ride systems, employers that offer alternative work schedules and job sharing, and waterways free of pollution.
<P>Tillman believes that Chattanooga&#146;s strength is its ability to forge public-private partnerships. 
<P>&quot;It&#146;s amazing how the city has been able to make progress that way,&quot; she says.  &quot;We&#146;re aware of what we have and what we could lose if we don&#146;t become sustainable.&quot;
<H3>Low-Cost Approaches Meet Local Needs</H3>
<P>These examples are just a few of the many innovative, low-cost approaches that local governments are pursuing toward sustainable futures.
<P>&quot;The path to sustainability is different for every city because of the variability in culture and politics,&quot; says Calvin Broomhead, project manager at San Francisco&#146;s Bureau of Energy Conservation.  &quot;Sustainability is about creating partnerships and relationships that meet local needs.&quot;
<P>For more information on how your community can implement sustainability initiatives, contact the Urban Consortium Energy Task Force, 1301 Pennsylvania Avenue NW, Washington, DC 20004, (202) 626-2400.
<P><I>This article was adapted from a fact sheet entitled &quot;Sustainability Protects Resources for </I><I>Future Generations.&quot;  NREL has produced about 30 of these four-to six-page fact sheets to </I><I>explain how local governments can integrate renewable energy and energy efficiency into </I><I>their operations.  Dollar and energy savings are quantified in a case-study format.  For more </I><I>information, contact NREL&#146;s Bruce Green at (303) 275-3621.</I>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
