<HEAD>
<TITLE>CESD: Transit on Demand</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">
<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>

<!-- -------------------------------------------ct      11/27/96------------------>
<H1>Transit on Demand</H1>
<H4><I>by Linda Brown</I>, NREL in Review, Summer 1996</H4>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<P><I>New satellite-based technology links personal computers with shuttle vans, taxis, and other </I><I>fleet vehicles for improved transportation efficiency</I>
<P>Senior citizen Ann Wright remembers the days when new-fangled automobiles frightened the carriage horses on Denver&#146;s dirt roads.  Now she and other physically challenged residents of Jefferson County, CO, are preparing to ride the information highway via a computer- and satellite-based technology called &quot;transit on demand.&quot;
<P>It&#146;s all part of a new research demonstration program sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) to help meet the growing pressures of traffic congestion and energy use in the 21st century.
<P>&quot;In this country alone, more than 123 million vehicles spew out almost 720 million tons of air pollutants every year, and the numbers are rapidly increasing,&quot; said Assistant Secretary of Energy Christine Ervin.  &quot;New computerized transportation technologies can double the efficiency of existing vehicle fleets and that means fewer vehicles on the road while reducing oil consumption and improving air quality.&quot;
<P>Transit on demand makes it easy for prospective passengers to enter ride requests on an Internet home page.  The request travels by phone line to a central computer, where it&#146;s converted to a digital signal and bounced off a global positioning satellite to a shuttle van or other fleet vehicle.  An on-board computer and transmitter allow the vehicle&#146;s driver to acknowledge the request and inform the prospective passenger of any schedule changes as they occur.
<P>The use of computers to organize vehicle routes will go a long way toward reducing the total number of vehicle miles traveled on our nation&#146;s highways.  Even more benefits would accrue by using fleet vehicles powered by clean-burning ethanol or electric batteries charged by photovoltaic panels.
<P>DOE will provide $140,000 to fund the 18-month-long cooperative research project with Jefferson County&#146;s Seniors on Wheels program.  Technical issues now being addressed include signal transmission in urban &quot;canyons&quot; and the development of software that will allow fleet dispatchers to track and coordinate multiple fleet vehicles.  
<P>Transit on demand is one of three pilot projects in the new Vehicle Miles Traveled program, which is managed by DOE&#146;s Denver Regional Support Office with technical assistance from NREL.  Other projects include the development and installation of interactive transportation kiosks in Boulder, CO, and methods for monitoring and forecasting transportation trends in Denver.
<P>For more information on cooperative research opportunities, contact Ernie Oakes manager of DOE&#146;s Denver Regional Support Office, (303) 275-4817.
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P></P>
<CENTER>
<IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>
<!-- ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<P></P> 
<P><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG ALIGN="BOTTOM" SRC="/rsc/left_arr.gif"></A></P>
