<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sustainability in Seattle</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY BACKGROUND="/rsc/027.jpg">

<A HREF="/index.html">
<IMG ALIGN=middle SRC="/rsc/photow8.gif" ALT="= NCSD Home Page ="></A>

<CENTER><H2>Sustainability in Seattle</H2>

<H3>Turning Best Practice Into Common Practice</H3>

<H4><I>Gary Lawrence</I></H4></CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN="MIDDLE" SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"></CENTER>

<!-- --------------------------11/22/96 ct----------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<BR><P>The ideas, techniques and values embodied in the terms sustainability and sustainable development represent, for many, a preferred future in which human settlements exist in harmony with the Earth's natural systems.  Some see sustainability not as a utopian future but, instead, the necessary framework if we are to have any future at all.  Others see the call for sustainability as alarmist nonsense perpetuated by those who wish to impose their anti-progress values upon others.</P>


<P>Those who are engaged in these intellectual debates about sustainability, together, represent a pretty small portion of human society.  Most of us never use the words, if we have heard them haven't a clue what they mean to whom, and spend our time trying to figure out how to survive instead of debating the consequences of today's decisions for future generations.</P>


<P>Embodied within the concepts are issues related to consumption, distribution, fairness, equity, health, stewardship, aspiration, growth, future and a variety of other processes, values and physical laws.  The words are used in conjunction with discussions of sectoral and multi-sectoral issues: eco-systems, urbanization, agriculture, natural resource management, etc.  The concepts are being promoted as the standards by which human endeavors ought to be judged.  We haven't, nor have the communities in which they are being used, yet come to terms with what they mean, however.</P>

<P>The same could be said for the tool we propose to use in judging if we are becoming more sustainable indicators.  Indicators of sustainability are being developed by local authorities and national committees around the world in preparation for Habitat II.  A variety of interesting models are being developed which can tell us, based upon our adopted notion of sustainability, if things are getting better or worse.  Knowing how things are going turns out to be very much different than deciding to change how things are going, however.</P>


<P>In Seattle, Washington USA we find, through a lot of luck, some good decisions, and the luxury of what used to be an abundant natural margin for error, that discussions of sustainability and sustainable development are possible when making many of the choices we face.  We have a highly educated population who care about the natural environment; an abundance of resources (including capital); we haven't lived here long enough to have irrevocably lost what nature has given us; and we have political systems which encourage the involvement of citizens in decision&#173; making.  Even here, however, old habits, myths and the desire for stuff makes sustainability a hard sell.  Nevertheless, we have made some progress and learned some things about urban sustainability.  This paper is about the nature of sustainability and indicators within an urban context and some of the experiences in Seattle as the community has tried to become more sustainable.</P>
<P></P>

<P><H3>What Is Urban Sustainability?</H3>Sustainability is simple to say but hard to describe.  The two defining characteristics of sustainability-enhancing decisions are that they are holistic and long&#173;term.  That is, our choices-ranging from major public policy decisions to personal, day-to-day lifestyle choices-are more sustainable if they are based at least in part on two considerations:</P>
<P></P>

<OL>
<LI> the impacts they are likely to have on the entire system in which we are operating (i.e., economic, social, and environmental), not just on one or two of the parts; and
<LI> the impacts they will or could have on future generations, not just our own.
</OL>

<P>Implicit within the concept of sustainability are some powerful ideas.  One implicit notion is that we, as individuals, are part of a continuum of life and we have a responsibility to ensure that our species survive.  This idea has often been associated with religious thoughts about stewardship and/or with bio-sociological theory about innate drives for species survival.  While for many of us it is rational and obvious that we need to think about whether we have a future, it doesn't seem to be part of our consciousness in day-to-day practice.  Much of human behavior suggests that we think of ourselves as discrete events rather than as part of a continuum.  We behave as though the goal of life is to get and use as much as we can in order to optimize our own experience even if it has harmful consequences for the future.</P>


<P>Another implicit notion is that we have stewardship responsibility for species other than our own. Our unique ability to reason does, many believe, create a special obligation for us to use reason on behalf of the species who cannot.  Again many of our behaviors to date suggest a disconnection between this theory and the choices we make day-to-day.</P>

<P>A third notion is that the capacity of the world to produce the necessities of life is finite.  Sustainability thinking assumes that it is possible, if not probable, that we can cause the demise of our own species as well as other species through poor decisions on consumption of the necessities of life.</P>
<P></P>

<P>And, finally, there is a notion that in the long-term we all share the consequences of our individual choices.  If the world is a system of which we are all a part then my unsustainable choices affect the present and future of everyone.  It appears that this notion, too, could use some translation into our daily life.</P>


<P>There are a number of working definitions of sustainable development and sustainable communities.  The City of Seattle defines sustainability as 'the long&#173;term social, economic, and environmental health of our community.'<SUP>1</SUP>  We define a sustainable city as one that 'thrives without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their needs.'<SUP>2</SUP>  In general terms, the City's definition is quite consistent with the definitions used by the UN and President Clinton's Council on Sustainable Development.</P>


<P>At the core of these definitions is the concept of the city as a system within a system-a web of social, economic, and ecological phenomena operating within a similar but larger regional, national, and global system.  In this definition we also recognize that neighborhoods must prosper within the web of the city system.</P>


<P><H3>Relative Or Absolute</H3>Some, Seattle included, make an important distinction between relative and absolute sustainability.  Absolute sustainability involves clearly defined and demarcated numerical limits or carrying capacities: a geographic area is not sustainable unless it identifies those limits, and then stays within them.  Relative sustainability is based on the concept of limits as well; it recognizes that those limits exist, and that current trends if unaltered, will exceed the limits in some uncomfortably short time frame.  But, unlike absolute sustainability, relative sustainability does not depend on the actual quantification of those limits; it is more concerned with continuous improvement in the trends than it is with the analysis and specification of the limits.  The goal is to achieve ever-increasing degrees of sustainability.  The focus is on those characteristics of sustainability that we want to maximize (e.g. diversity, citizen empowerment, sense of community, etc.) and, conversely, those un-sustainable characteristics or trends we want to minimize (e.g. resource consumption, pollution, inequitable distribution of wealth, etc.).</P>

<P>One can question the legitimacy of calling a plan 'sustainable' when it pursues relative sustainability as a goal.  For some there is no acceptable measure of a sustainable future except numeric goals for some absolute 'steady&#173;state' in which human population is balanced with other species and the Earth's capacity to provide the resources necessary for life.  I believe that, with regard to urban sustainability, it is more important to choose a path and start down that path than it is to spend a lot of time arguing about the specific destination.  The complexity of our urban systems, particularly in relationship to the rural systems which provide the calories and the natural resources which provide the other forms of energy which make the urban systems possible, makes it very difficult if not impossible to define 'sustainability' for any particular human settlement.  However, the inability of our minds or models to understand this level of complexity cannot be an excuse for not trying to become more sustainable.</P>


<P><H3>More Sustainable</H3>
Let us pretend for a moment that we are within a community of people who have decided, despite not knowing what an absolute sustainable future might be, to make their community more sustainable.  We would go through the process of understanding our likely future (what we will become if the status quo is maintained given what we know or think we know today) and then defined a preferred future-a vision-for what we want to become instead.  Based upon knowing the future we are headed for and the future we want, we then produce a plan to get us from where we are today to where we would prefer to be.</P>


<P>Many communities have reached this point.  They have had a vision and they have developed a plan.  Few of these plans have driven changes in practice or resource allocation.  Fewer yet have developed the mechanisms by which they can measure their progress and adjust their plans to keep making progress in the face of new information or circumstances.  This is where sustainability indicators come into play.</P>


<P>Indicators can tell us whether, for some particular problem or issue, based upon the available information, things are getting better or worse relative to our goals.  They can be a critical part of a community's initiatives toward a more sustainable future.  On the other hand, they can be aggregations of data that cost<I> </I>a lot of money to<I> </I>collect and serve no real purpose at all.  Knowing something and deciding to do something about that which we know are two very separate things.  If the indicators are to<I> </I>be useful in inspiring change toward some preferred future, they will need to<I> </I>address the differences between data, information, meaning and action.</P>


<P>Most institutions, be they governments, NGOs, businesses or whatever, collect data.  Most of the data never gets used and much of it is probably of<I> </I>little use to<I> </I>anyone to<I> </I>begin with.  Sometimes an analyst will use it in developing a report explaining what the data mean.  Discussions of Gross Domestic Product are a common example, with the relevant bank collecting data and supplying its meaning to the masses.</P>


<P><H3>Data, Information, Meaning, Action</H3>

The difficulty with this normal method is that people seem to resist changing their behaviors based upon someone else's meaning.  A United States example of this phenomenon is found in our attempts to reduce vehicle trips per household and vehicle miles traveled.  We collect lots of data on the environmental and human health consequences of air quality degradation associated with the use of the automobile.  Scientists report that their measurements (data) show that things are getting worse and, based upon this data, public agencies tell people that they should drive less. When the data tells us that things are really bad, we take action to make driving more difficult. This hasn't worked so far.</P>


<P>Among the reasons it hasn't worked is that the data collected hasn't been translated into information that non&#173;scientists can understand (how big is a part per billion?).  Therefore individuals can't reach an independent conclusion that the problem means something to them.  Unless individuals can decide for themselves what the information means they are unlikely to be willing to consider changing their behaviors (act upon the information).</P>

<P>I belabor this point because of the need to put indicators within both the context of knowing and the context of action.  Indicator projects that collect data and tell people what the data mean are not likely to lead to more sustainable communities.  Indicator projects which provide information and let people within the community decide what it means for them and how they want to change things in response seem to work better.  The indicators have to allow individuals and communities to 'own' the problem that needs to be solved and participate in identifying the solutions they are willing to accept.</P>


<P>In Seattle a citizens' organization has developed indicators of sustainability which complement the City's planning and budgeting by measuring progress toward or away from some preferred future rather than measuring progress toward some absolute end&#173;state.  In this case a citizens organization got the data and decided for themselves what it meant.  They use their indicators to hold themselves and their institutions accountable for actions which make the community sustainable.  They understand that indicators are inherently political in that they result in actions which change resource allocations at the community level.  They have created indicators through which it is possible to tell whether the things that matter to them and to the rest of the community are getting better or worse.</P>


<P>Seattle is one example of a community which has tried to become more sustainable by defining a vision, planning to achieve that vision, and taking specific actions to achieve that vision.  All of these steps involve a partnership between the business community, the institutions of government. neighborhoods, and interest groups.  It has been messy but it seems to be working.</P>


<P><H3>Seattle's Experience</H3>
In the last five years or so, sustainability in Seattle has moved from the musings of environmental activists to institutional practice within City government.  The pursuit of greater relative sustainability is now a matter of City policy in Seattle.  Sustainability has emerged as a key organizing principle and decision&#173;making parameter for City plans, policies, and actions, primarily through the adoption in recent years of two major policy documents: the City's Environmental Action Agenda (adopted by the City Council in October 1992), and the Comprehensive Plan (titled 'Toward A Sustainable Seattle,' and adopted by the city Council in July 1994).</P>

<P>How did this happen?  In large part, the emergence of sustainability on the public agenda in Seattle is the confluence of three things:</P>


<P><H4><I>Citizen action through Sustainable Seattle</I></H4>


Sustainable Seattle is 'a voluntary network and civic forum working to improve the region's long-term cultural, economic, environmental and social health and vitality.'<SUP>3</SUP>  A small group of innovators started Sustainable Seattle in 1991 following a one-day conference conducted by the Global Tomorrow Coalition.  Since then, the group has grown in numbers, activities, and stature.  As a first task, the non&#173;government, volunteer&#173;driven organization developed and published a set of 'indicators of sustainable community'-economic, environmental, and social measures showing ways in which the city and the region are moving toward or away from sustainability.  These indicators, and the community&#173;based process by which they were developed, were instrumental in putting the concept of sustainability on the 'radar screen' in Seattle, and, in particular, within city government.  Sustainable Seattle took on many other projects as well, including the creation of a policy team whose goal was to target local policy debates and attempt to infuse sustainability into those debates.</P>

<P>It is important to understand the theory behind the indicators of sustainability developed by Sustainable Seattle.  It was their choice to not simply measure things but instead to describe the direction of the community in a way which might compel individuals to take action.  The 40 trends which are measured in their reports cover a full range of cultural, economic, environmental and social issues that will determine our future as a city and region.  Taken together, they provide a snapshot of a city where perceived quality of life is high, but where long-term trends are undermining many of the things people love most about living here.<SUP>4</SUP></P>


<P>These citizen-developed indicators attempt to mirror the complexity within the City's comprehensive plan.  'These indicators can also provide insights into linkages, the ways in which different parts of our cultural, economic, environmental, and social systems affect each other.  By understanding linkages, we can find more creative and comprehensive solutions to the problems we face.'<SUP>5</SUP></P>

<P><H4><I>Activism Within The City Government</I></H4>

A small group of change agents within city government began work to incorporate the concept of sustainability into the City's business.  My own contribution as the Planning Director was to seize upon a new requirement to develop a comprehensive plan for the city (see below), and, with leadership from Mayor Norm Rice and assistance from staff, turn it into a forum for developing the beginnings of a sustainability agenda for the City.</P>



<P><H4><I>State Government Prescriptions</I></H4>
The state legislature in 1990 passed a Growth Management Act, which required the fastest growing jurisdictions in the state to develop comprehensive growth management plans, including plans for transportation, land-use, capital facilities, economic development, and utilities.  The law grew out of a widespread perception in the state that growth in Washington state-and in particular, in Western Washington-had been sprawling out of control for a decade or so, wreaking havoc on environmental quality, housing affordability, and other facets of society. The Growth Management Act fundamentally changed local government's responsibilities for comprehensive planning, it required comprehensive plans that simultaneously address the relationships between land-use, transportation, capital facilities, housing, and public utilities.  In addition, each city's plans were required to be consistent with the plans in neighboring jurisdictions, and with country and regional plans and policies.</P>


<P>The legislation also altered the discretion and decision&#173;making powers of local governments. Under the GMA, the City is required to adopt capital facility plans which are consistent with the Comprehensive Plan.  Further, no City expenditures can be inconsistent with the City's adopted plan.  Policies adopted by the City are no longer advisory or statements of intent, they create legal obligations enforceable through the judicial system.  And, the plans can only be amended once per year, by law.</P>

<P>It was the confluence of these three things that proved to be a recipe for change in Seattle.  City government was pushed in the direction of more comprehensive planning by the Washington State Growth Management Act, and toward thinking about sustainability by the non&#173;government organization Sustainable Seattle.  And there were enough change agents within city government for those nudges and pushes to make a difference.</P>


<P>There are a number of projects or programs in Seattle that, taken together, show a dramatic shift toward more sustainability&#173;sensitive planning, budgeting, and decision&#173;making. These include:</P>


<P><B>Environmental Action Agenda--</B>The first step toward integrating environmental issues into urban policy is to better integrate among environmental issues themselves.  Historically, cities (and all levels of government for that matter) have addressed environmental issues in a piecemeal fashion. This is partly due to the way U.S. environmental laws are written, and partly due to the administrative structures that were created to implement those laws.  In 1990 Seattle embarked on the Environmental Priorities Project, a process of looking at environmental quality and environmental management more holistically.  This was the first comparative risk-based environmental strategic planning effort by any local government in the country.  Its goal was to create a single vision for environmental management in the City, to comparatively assess the barriers to achieving that vision and reach consensus in the community about priorities and what to do about them.  The City's Environmental Action Agenda was proposed by the Mayor in October 1992, and unanimously adopted by the City Council a month later.</P>

<P><B>The Seattle Comprehensive Plan--</B>The key objective of the Comprehensive Plan, also known as the 'Urban Village Strategy,' is changing individual behavior to make a more sustainable society more likely.  It assumes that there will be no sustainable future unless individuals within our society choose that future.  Therefore, the plan seeks to make behavioral change easier or more attractive.</P>


<P>At its core are two goals.  One is to make it easier for people to change their behaviors by providing them with alternatives which do less harm but appeal to their core values.  The other is to influence the market place so that people make more money doing things that are good for society and less money doing things that harm it.  The plan does this by adopting policies, strategies, and investment practices that should result in denser, more walkable neighborhoods with more flexible and personalized public transport.  The urban village strategy focuses on making more compact and less consumptive living more attractive by providing better amenities such as parks, libraries community centers, transportation facilities, cultural amenities and educational infrastructure. We are increasing the densities for jobs and housing allowed within the villages, and reducing the development capacity outside the villages.  We are changing the uses allowed within the villages, and reducing the development capacity outside the villages so that, like it was 30 years ago, housing will be above shops and oriented towards the streets and sidewalks rather than towards backyards.  We are increasing the public share of the cost of basic infrastructure inside the villages, and increasing the private share outside, so as to make infill development within villages more profitable.</P>


<P>This comprehensive plan was adopted by the City Council in the summer of 1994.  Its adoption was not without controversy.  Many neighborhoods resist the notion that advantage for public investment ought to be given to those neighborhoods which are developing in compact, pedestrian and transit&#173;oriented ways.  The Council recognized, however, that the majority of the Seattle's citizens supported their efforts.  This support has been reflected in subsequent elections-those politicians which supported the plan have been re-elected, while candidates who ran for election in opposition to the plan were defeated.</P>


<P><B>Neighborhood Planning Project--</B>The current step in moving the City toward increased sustainability is a period of intensive planning at the neighborhood level. A new, 15-person office has been created in the Executive Department to support neighborhood planning efforts that are consistent both with the overriding vision of the Comprehensive Plan (i.e., a sustainable Seattle), and with the particular needs and wants of the neighborhoods themselves.</P>


<P>Seattle has a long history of active citizen involvement. It was clear from the start of these efforts toward a more sustainable future that without citizen 'ownership' of both the vision for a preferred future and the policies which will take us there we had little chance of long-term success. Therefore, the development of the City's comprehensive plan from the onset envisioned citizen-based planning efforts to translate the city-wide policies at the neighborhood level.</P>


<P>There are currently 110 recognized Neighborhood Councils within the City.  These Councils are advisory to the City government but wield significant political power.  However, the City determined that it could not manage the complexity of a neighborhood planning process with so many different groups.  Therefore, the neighborhoods have been aggregated into eleven planning areas with the Presidents of the individual Neighborhood Councils serving as the Board for the planning areas.  Each planning area has been granted City funds to hire their own planners to work with the City government in carrying out this program.  Those who develop plans consistent with the City's overall plan will be in line for capital and service improvements of their choosing.  Those who don't will be ineligible for locally determined investments.</P>


<P><B>Seattle Commons--</B>The Seattle Commons is a citizen-proposed urban redevelopment project in the South Lake Union area of Seattle, just north of the downtown retail core.  The vision is of a large park bordered by mixed-use development-a place where people could live, work, and play without needing a car.  A great deal of thought and work is going into planning a 'sustainable' neighborhood, since this offers a unique opportunity to create one virtually from scratch.  The Mayor's proposed plan was completed in early 1995.  The public was asked in September of 1995 to approve a property tax increase to pay for the public share of the capital improvements. Fifty-one percent of the voters rejected the tax increase so the future of the project is uncertain.  It is likely that the scope of the project will be reduced and placed back before the voters.</P>


<P>In the meantime, the University of Washington and Sustainable Seattle are working to develop neighborhood-based sustainability indicators which will be adopted by neighborhoods within the Seattle Commons area so that whatever happens in this area will focus on a more sustainable future.</P>


<P><B>Strategic Capital Investment Plan--</B>The City is working toward better coordination of its strategic capital investment planning.  The new process is governed by the vision and values embodied in the Comprehensive Plan.  The GMA requires that the capital plan be consistent with the comprehensive plan.</P>


<P><B>Strategic Management Initiative--</B>The City also is accelerating its work in developing accountability measures-both broad, quality-of-life indicators and more program&#173;specific performance measures-that will help us better evaluate the effectiveness of our activities and expenditures in achieving our stated goals and vision for a sustainable city.</P>


<P><B>Office of Management and Planning Finally--</B>City government was substantially reorganized in an attempt to achieve greater consistency between our plans and our budgets.  The Office of Management and Budget and the Planning Department have been merged into one Office of Management and Planning, located in the Executive Department.</P>


<H3>Some Lessons Learned</H3>

<P>There are some general lessons that can be learned from the City of Seattle's efforts toward sustainability.  Below are some of the factors which seemed to empower our actions and some which had the opposite effect.</P>


<H4><I>Empowering Factors</I></H4>
What were some of the empowering factors in the process-internal or external forces acting in our favor?  Internally, we benefited a great deal from three internal factors and two external ones.

<H4>Internal</H4>

<P><I>Strong political support and leadership.</I>  No major initiative in a large city-especially one entailing as much fundamental change as sustainability-can succeed without the obvious. sustained support of powerful and effective political leaders.  Seattle Mayor Norm Rice has provided that leadership in affecting change in Seattle.  Members of Seattle's City Council, particularly Council President Jim Street, also have been essential.</P>


<P><I>Strong leadership from the Planning Department </I>(director and staff).  Staff needed to move beyond neutrality to advocacy for the future envisioned by the City's political leadership.  Such advocacy increased risk for the staff by putting their objectivity into question.  The conflicts within the department mirrored one of the major planning debates within the U.S. should planners say what 'ought' to happen or just describe possible futures?  Seattle's planners determined that arguing for a preferred, sustainable future was worth the risk given the political leadership shown by members of the City Council and by the Mayor.</P>


<H4>External</H4>

<P><I>Strong environmental consciousness of citizens.</I>  Environmental stewardship is akin to religion in the Pacific Northwest in general, and Seattle in particular.</P>


<P><I>Bold but flexible state legislation.</I>  A new state law provided a 'window of opportunity' for incorporating sustainability concerns into the City's planning efforts.  The roles of this legislation are discussed in more detail below.</P>


<H4><I>Disempowering factors</I></H4>

<H4>Internal</H4>

<P><I>Bureaucracy and fragmentation in City government.</I>  Local governments' organizational structures are not particularly conducive to promoting sustainability.  Unfortunately, Seattle's organizational structure is not an exception (although important changes are being made, such as the creation of a new Neighborhood Planning Office and an Office of Management and Planning, see above).  Sustainability is an integrative concept: it encourages holistic thinking about the economy, the environment, and the social fabric.  City governments are divided into departments or agencies of various shapes and sizes, each with its own relatively narrow mission, agenda, budget, and constituency.</P>


<P><I>Electoral politics.</I>  Similarly, electoral politics in the U.S.--with their relatively short terms of office, the arbitrarily drawn political boundaries, and the fragmented organization of<I> </I>legislative committees-are not well-suited for promoting sustainability.  Sustainability is about thinking long-term about the implications of today's decisions on future generations.  Most elected officials, because of the nature of the political process, have difficulty thinking past their next re-election. This phenomenon has given rise to an alternative to the NIMBY (not in my back yard) syndrome -- the so-called NIMTOO (not in my term of office) syndrome.</P>


<P>While this is a barrier in Seattle as well, Mayor Norm Rice has set a new standard for leadership by setting a vision for the future, and putting in place changes in pursuit of that vision, many of them bold and risky, and many involving outcomes that will occur long after his tenure as the city's highest-ranking elected official is over.</P>


<P><I>Corporate culture.</I>  Sectoral specialization makes it difficult to gain support for holistic approaches, and the reward systems in bureaucracies typically do not value risk-taking.</P>


<H4>External</H4>

<P><I>Fear of change/fear of the unknown.</I>  Sustainability is about individuals changing their own behaviors.  For many, the only positive change is that which other people make.  Sustainability must be discussed in a non-threatening way.</P>


<P><I>Parochialism.</I> It is difficult to get people to think beyond their own personal and immediate needs and wants, and focus on the longer term and the public good.  In Seattle's growth management planning process, this difficulty has manifested itself most starkly in the debate over increasing densities in designated urban villages.  A few neighborhoods have vehemently opposed the concept, not because they think it is a bad idea for the city and region, but because they fear what it will mean for their particular neighborhood.</P>


<P><I>Perverse incentives.</I>  (e.g. inaccurate price signals, hidden subsidies). There are a number of laws, regulations, and policies, particularly at the federal government level, that, together conspire to be a traitor to cities trying to reign in urban sprawl.  The most obvious examples of this are the myriad subsidies-some hidden, some not-for private cars, ranging from inaccurately low gasoline prices to federal support for road and highway construction in the suburbs.</P>


<P><I>Lack of national leadership.</I>  U.S.<I> </I>cities are just beginning to get leadership from the federal government on sustainability.  President Clinton's Council on Sustainable Development in March 1996 published recommendations on how the Nation might have a more sustainable future.  A reformed President's Council will undertake programs to encourage adoption of these recommendations.  In addition, the U.S. Department of Commerce, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, and the White House Office on Science and Technology have all undertaken individual programs in the name of a more sustainable future for the U.S.  There is an initiative underway within the U.S. Conference of Mayors and the National Association of Counties to work with the President's Council to implement the recommendations of the President's Council on Sustainable Development at the local level.</P>


<H3>Conclusion</H3>

<P>In conclusion let me suggest some key points which local communities might consider in moving toward a more sustainable future.  These points come more from experience than from theory.  And, most of them are the result of lessons learned very painfully in the process of making a lot of mistakes.</P>


<H4><I>Answer 'what' before trying to answer 'how.'</I></H4>

Too often we jump into discussions about how to solve a particular public policy problem before we answer the question  'What are we trying to accomplish?'  In doing so, we run the risk of developing and implementing solutions to problems that do not respond to a widely perceived need, and/or that do not appropriately take into consideration the values of those whose actions are necessary to make implementation effective and successful.  Identifying those values, and coming to some consensus about what the problem is that you are trying to solve, are essential first steps.

<H4><I>Recognize that sustainability is a political choice, not a technical one.</I></H4>
Much of the discussion around sustainability has to do with the techniques we might apply to reduce consumption or mitigate the effects of our behaviors.  The techniques and tools are very valuable but only if the community chooses to use them.  At the heart of a more sustainable community are the choices that individuals and households make about how to live their lives.  It is the role of the individual to make these choices.  It is the role of institutions to make more sustainable choices possible.  Sustainability is not about technological improvement, it is about political courage.  The institutions have to have the courage to work collaboratively to empower the individual to make choices on behalf of family and community.  The individual has to have the courage to use the power granted in a way that benefits the society as well as the individual.  Both institution and individual have to have the courage to make and admit to mistakes in the pursuit of a better future.  Recognizing this is an important first step on the road to change.

<H4><I>Recognize that good planning has a moral as well as technical foundation.
</I></H4>

<P>Good planning, planning for a sustainable future, is about peoples' lives.  Not only the lives of people today, but the lives of those who will follow us.  We spend much of our time talking about the attributes of communities (transport, housing, sanitation systems, governance structures, etc.). None of these are ends in themselves.  They are means toward the only legitimate end goal for our communities-the quality of life of the people who will live there.  If you are not thinking about the question 'will this make life better or worse for the people who will live here today and those who will live here in the future' when you are making planning decisions you are only doing part of your job.</P>


<H4><I>Rather than focusing entirely on trying to change self interests, develop ways to use it to the advantage of the public good.
</I></H4>
<P>For example, devise economic incentives that make saving (or making) money synonymous with saving the environment.  The variable can rate structure built into Seattle's garbage and recycling programs is an excellent example.</P>

<H4><I>Recognize what government does well, and what it doesn't.</I></H4>

<P>Pursue the former; avoid the latter.  Just as discretion is often the better part of valor, invisibility is often the better part of leadership.  There will be many problems and opportunities each community will confront on the road to a more sustainable future. You need to pause and decide who within your community has the greatest chance to be successful in getting the problem solved or realizing the opportunity.  In many cases the answer will be an NGO or other community institutions rather than the local government itself.  The role City government played (or, more accurately, didn't play) in bringing the Seattle Commons and Sustainable Seattle into the public spotlight is an excellent example.</P>


<P>In general, local governments and bureaucracies try to avoid risk.  The political costs of mistakes or failures can be very high for elected officials or senior bureaucrats.  NGOs and community organizations are much more willing to try things without being absolutely sure they will work. And they will be much more willing to admit that it didn't work and try something new. In-so-far as we don't really know what works or doesn't work within any given community, this experimentation is critical to success.</P>


<P>There is a saying that 'the only way to get power is to give it away.'  I think that is true for community sustainability.  By empowering others you not only get community ownership of the problems and solutions, but you increase the status of the local government as the source of empowerment.</P>


<H4><I>It is better to be well-prepared for an opportunity that never comes than to be ill-prepared  opportunity when it arises.</I></H4>

<P>Sustainable Seattle, the City of Seattle, and the state legislature all got involved in the sustainability issue at roughly the same time, though in different ways, and without much knowledge of the others' efforts.  But Sustainable Seattle was ready for the opportunity to influence the public agenda when it arose, just as the City was poised to take advantage of the opportunity that was provided (but not required) by the state Growth Management Act.</P>

<H4><I>Make sure that the indicators you use to measure your progress have an emotional as well as scientific basis.</I></H4>

<P>There is an expression in the U.S., MEGO (My Eyes Glaze Over) that describes how most of us relate to pages of data and statistics.  Too many of the indicators of sustainability measure in great detail the attributes of the problem and describe those attributes in a way that is not accessible to people within the community whose behavioral change is the key to progress.  We often produce pages of data and then tell people what the data mean.</P>


<P>For indicators to be successful they must compel people to act.  Most people are not compelled to act unless they can decide for themselves what the information means.  An example might be helpful.</P>


<P>One of the indicators of the sustainability of every human society is the quality of the water supply.  We have the capacity to measure the attributes of our water supply in parts per billion and more.  However, most of us don't really have the background to know why, hypothetically, 10 parts per billion might be bad and 5 parts per billion is acceptable.  In this hypothetical case, we have the data but it is doesn't inspire people to change their behaviors and to hold their institutions accountable for different choices.</P>

<P>Sustainable Seattle measures water quality by linking it to something about which we in the Pacific Northwest part of the U.S. do get emotional, the number of salmon that return to our rivers and streams each year.  We know that the life of salmon is linked very closely to the quality of our water.  When water quality goes down, so do the fish runs.  Salmon are important to us culturally and economically.  Therefore, when the salmon runs diminish we demand action.</P>

<P>People can understand that there are less salmon much more easily than they can understand scientific measurements.  In each culture there are things which are important to the people.  Try to find ways to link what is being measured to things that people care about.</P>


<H3>Acknowledgments</H3>

<P><I>The Author would like to thank Steve Nicholas for his work developing the frame work for this paper and Sarah Philips for her work in making it readable.  And, as always, l am greatly appreciative of the support of my colleagues in the College of Architecture and Urban Planning at the University of Washington.</I></P>


<B>Notes</B>

