Kline has written other valuable articles and reports regarding sustainability, including <b>"Why 
Sustainable Community Indicators? People Need a Reality Check"</B> from the <I>Wingspread Journal</i>, 
Volume 18, Issue 2, Spring 1996.  The article is  available on-line at: <BR>

<a href="http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/articles/wings/realchec.html">http://www.sustainable.doe.gov/articles/wings/realchec.html</a>

<BR><BR><BR><BR>



<b>2. <a name="b">Chattanooga, Tennessee</b>
<P>

Faced with a declining economy and widespread concern about the quality of life in Chattanooga, 
a group of over 50 community leaders met in 1984 to find solutions.  In response, they created a 
nonprofit organization called Chattanooga Venture to help the community rethink its collective 
image and start making progress towards becoming a more attractive, healthy, economically-sound 
place to live.
<P>

In 1985, Chattanooga Venture initiated a five-month process called Vision 2000 through which 
over 1,700 people in the community cooperated to create a vision for Chattanoogas future.  The 
Vision 2000 program set forty goals for improving Chattanooga and the lives of its citizens over 
the next 15 years.  The goals included the following:
<P>

1. Creating a positive self image for the community
<P>
2. Making the downtown vital and livable 
<P>
3. Alleviating substandard housing
<P>
4. Solving problems with air, water, toxic waste, and noise pollution;
<P>
5. Improving communication between diverse groups
<P>
6. Improving community member access to the arts
<P>

While Chattanooga did not choose indicators to measure progress toward the goals, they did complete 
a self assessment in 1992 to examine the results of the initiated projects.  In 1993, the goal setting 
process was repeated through Revision 2000 -- Take Charge Again.  Revision 2000 established 27 
goals in the following areas:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Beautification<BR>			
Crime and Safety<BR>		
Development and Planning<BR>
Economic Development<BR>								
Environment<BR>			
Health<BR>				
Historic Preservation<BR>
Job Training<BR>			
Multi-culturalism<BR>		
Parenting and Family<BR>		
Riverfront<BR>			
Social and Human Services<BR>	
Tourism<BR>				
Workplace</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Citizen Involvement and Public Information<BR>	
Culture and Arts<BR>		
Downtown<BR>
Education<BR>
Government Structure<BR>
Youth<BR>
Housing<BR>
Leadership<BR>
Neighborhoods<BR>
Parks and Greenways<BR>
Small Business<BR>
Sports, Events, Recreation<BR>
Transportation</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain report and contact information:</u>
<p>
Chattanooga Venture<BR>
506 Broad Street<BR>
Chattanooga, TN  37042<BR>
(615)  267-8687
<BR><BR>

For more information, see the <B>Chattanooga Venture Web site:</b>
<a href="http://www.chattanooga.net/SUSTAIN/pcsd_briefing_book/particihousing_venture.html">http://www.chattanooga.net/SUSTAIN/pcsd_briefing_book/particihousing_venture.html</a>
<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>3. <a name="c">Jacksonville, Florida</b>
<P>

In 1985, over 100 volunteers met under the leadership of the Jacksonville Community Council to 
develop a model for monitoring the quality of life in Jacksonville and Duval County, Florida.  
The outcome established nine quality of life "elements" with indicators for each section.  
Jacksonvilles "elements" are:
<BR>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Education<BR>
The Economy<BR>	
Public Safety<BR>
Natural Environment<BR>
Health</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Social Environment<BR>
Government/Politics<BR>
Culture/Recreation<BR>
Mobility</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR>

Specific indicators were selected within each element and data were collected for each indicator 
from the mid 1970s through 1984.  The data was compiled and analyzed for the first "Life in 
Jacksonville: Quality Indicators for Progress 1985" report.  Annual updates have been published 
since the original report.
<P>

<U>To obtain report and contact information:</u>
<p>
Jacksonville Community Council, Inc.<BR>
2434 Atlantic Blvd., Suite 100<BR>
Jacksonville, FL  32207<BR>
(904)  396-3052
<BR>

For more information, see the <B>Jacksonville Quality of Life Web site:</b>
<a href="http://www.unf.edu/~clifford/jcci/qip.htm">
http://www.unf.edu/~clifford/jcci/qip.htm</a>
<BR><BR>
<B>4. <a name="d">Pasadena, California</b>
<P>

As part of the California Healthy Cities Project, the Pasadena Public Health Department in 1990 
called together a cultural cross-section of 150 residents and civic professionals to determine 
Pasadenas relative health and well-being.  The outcome was a 1992 report, titled "The Quality 
of Life in Pasadena: an Index for the 90s and beyond," which established 10 broad categories for 
civic well-being.
<P>

Specific indicators are organized within the following 10 categories:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>1. Environment<BR>
2. Education<BR>
3. Arts and Culture<BR>
4. Community Safety</b>
</td><td valign=top>		
<B>5. Health<BR>
6. Economy and Employment<BR>
7. Recreation and Open Spaces</b>	
</td><td valign=top>		
<B>8.  Alcohol, Tobacco, Drugs<BR>
9.  Housing<BR>
10. Transportation</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain report/for more information:</u>
<p>
City of Pasadena<BR>
Public Health Department<BR>
100 North Garfield Avenue<BR>
Room 136<BR>
Pasadena, CA  91109<BR>
(818)  405-4392
<BR><BR>

Presently, there is no Web site for the Pasadena indicator project.  

<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>5. <a name="e">San Francisco, California</b>
<p>

In 1993, the San Francisco Board of Supervisors established a Commission on San Franciscos Environment 
to draft and implement a sustainability plan for San Francisco.  To gain wide public participation 
and support for the plan, several commissioners and community members formed Sustainable San Francisco, 
a collaboration of city agencies, businesses, environmental organizations, elected officials, and 
concerned individuals.
<P>

As of Summer 1996, the plan is in draft form and is gaining public comment.  An integral part of 
the plan is a section on indicators.  Over 50 indicators were chosen in the following categories:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Air Quality<BR>
Energy, Climate Change, and Ozone Depletion<BR>	
Hazardous Materials<BR>
Parks, Open Spaces, Streetscapes (The Urban Forest)<BR>		
Transportation<BR>
Economy and Economic Development<BR>
Risk Management (Activities of High Environmental Risk)<BR>
Environmental Justice</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Biodiversity<BR>
Food and Agriculture<BR>
Human Health<BR>
Solid Waste<BR>
Water and Wastewater<BR>
Municipal Expenditures<BR>
Public Information and Education</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain the report/for more information:</u>
<P>
Beryl Magilavy, Organizer<BR>
Sustainable San Francisco<BR>
1155 Ellis Street<BR>
San Francisco, CA  94109<BR>
(415)  775-0396

<BR><BR>

For more information, see the <B>Sustainable San Francisco Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.igc.apc.org/sustainable/">http://www.igc.apc.org/sustainable/</a>

<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<b>6. <a name="f">San Jose, California</b>
<P>

In 1995, the City of San Joses Environmental Services Department formed a Sustainability Indicators 
Team to begin the process of evaluating and developing quantifiable and relevant indicators of 
sustainability.  In a February 1996 report, "Sustainability Indicators for the City of San Jose," 
the team identified 52 preliminary indicators in the following categories:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Population and Housing<BR>
Economics<BR>
Land Use<BR>	
Water Use<BR>
Air Quality</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<b>Water Quality<br>
Waste Management<br>
Energy<br>
Transportation</B>
</TD></TR>
</table>

<BR><BR>

According to the report, time and resource constraints at San Joses Environmental Science 
Department prevented inclusion of crime, welfare, education, and other social aspects in the 
program.  With the initial report as a foundation, San Jose plans to continue the work on indicators.
