<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>8. <a name="h">Seattle, Washington</b>
<P>

Sustainable Seattle is a volunteer network and civic forum working to improve the regions long-term 
cultural, economic, environmental, and social health and vitality.  The network/forum grew out 
of a one-day conference  in 1990 sponsored by the Global Tomorrow Coalition in which a diverse 
group of community leaders met to discuss the idea of citizens choosing their own ways of 
measuring long-term community well-being.
<P>

In 1991, a group of committed volunteers led the process of developing indicators for Seattle.  
The first set of indicators were published in "Indicators of Sustainable Community 1993."
<P>

Continued work and refinement over the next two years resulted in "Indicators of Sustainable 
Community 1995," the first complete survey of key long-term trends affecting the Seattle areas 
sustainability.  The forty indicators were selected and researched by over 270 citizen 
volunteers to cover a full range of cultural, economic, environmental and social issues.  
The report establishes five primary categories for the indicators: Environment, Population and 
Resources, Economy, Youth and Education, and Health and Community.
<P>
 
The 1995 report revealed the following sustainability trends in Seattle:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>14 indicators signified Seattle moving away from sustainability;<BR>
18 indicators were stable or did not reveal a trend;<BR>
8 indicators demonstrated improvement.</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain the report and contact information:</u>
<p>
Sustainable Seattle<BR>
Metrocenter YMCA<BR>
909 Fourth Avenue<BR>
Seattle, WA  98104<BR>
(206)  382-5013 

<BR><BR>

A full listing of the 1993 indicators and a partial listing of the 1995 indicators is available 
at the <B>Sustainable Seattle Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.scn.org/sustainable/indicators.html">http://www.scn.org/sustainable/indicators.html</a>

<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>9. <a name="i">Willapa Bay Watershed, Washington</b>
<P>

The Willapa Bay Alliance (WBA) was founded as a non-profit organization in 1992 on the belief 
that locally-based science, economic research, and education can assist the people of Pacific 
County to address the economic and environmental challenges facing the region.  In 1995, WBA 
completed a three-year research project that gathered data on the regions environmental, economic, 
and social conditions from nearly eighty government, private, and non-governmental agencies.
<P>

The data was analyzed and compiled into eleven primary indicator categories for a report titled 
"Willapa Indicators for a Sustainable Community." The aim of the indicator project is better 
understanding of past trends so that the community can influence the future direction of 
development of the Willapa Bay Watershed region.  The eleven primary indicator categories 
reflecting key concerns and challenges are the following:
