<center><font size=+3>STATE INDICATORS PROGRAMS</font></center>
<P>
<B>10. <a name="m">Minnesota</b>
<P>

In 1991, Governor Arne H. Carlson initiated the "Minnesota Milestones Program" on the premise 
that defining shared vision, setting goals and measuring results would lead to a better future 
for Minnesotas people.  Thousands of Minnesotans contributed to the planning process by 
attending one of 45 meetings across the state, completing surveys, reviewing draft documents or 
writing letters.  The result in 1992 was the development of a citizen-based, 30-year plan titled 
"Minnesota Milestones: A Report Card for the Future" which established 20 goals with 79 indicators, 
or milestones, to assess progress.  
<P>

The 20 goals created by Minnesota Milestones include the following:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
1.  Minnesota children will not live in poverty<BR>
2.  Families will provide a stable environment for their children<BR>
3.  All children will come to school ready to learn<BR>
4.  Minnesotans will excel in basic academic skills<BR>
5.  Minnesotans will be healthy<BR>
6.  Minnesota communities will be safe, friendly, and caring<BR>
7.  People who need help will receive it<BR>
8.  People with disabilities will participate in society<BR>
9.  Minnesotans will value all cultures, races and ethnic backgrounds<BR>
10. Minnesota will sustain above-average economic growth<BR>
11. Minnesotans will have the advanced education and training to make the state a leader in the global  economy<BR>
12. All Minnesotans will have a reasonable standard of living<BR>
13. All Minnesotans will have decent, safe and affordable housing<BR>
14. Small cities, rural and urban areas will be economically viable<BR>
15. Minnesotans will act to protect and enhance their environment<BR>
16. Minnesotans will improve the quality of the air, water and earth<BR>
17. Minnesotas environment will support a rich diversity of plant and animal life<BR>
18. Minnesotans will have the opportunities to enjoy the states natural resources<BR>
19. People will participate in government and politics<BR>
20. Government in Minnesota will be cost-efficient and services will be designed 
      to meet the needs of the people who use them
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>Contact Information</u>
<p>
Minnesota Planning <BR>
658 Cedar Street<BR>
St. Paul, MN  55155<BR>
(612)  296-3985

<BR><BR>

Two progress reports have been published in follow-up to the general plan.  All three documents 
with specific indicator information are available for downloading from the <B>Minnesota Planning 
Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.mnplan.state.mn.us/press/mileston.html">
        http://www.mnplan.state.mn.us/press/mileston.html</a>

