<B>15. <a name="l">Toronto, Ontario, Canada</b>
<P>

In 1992, the Institute for Social Research at York University prepared a feasibility analysis for 
modeling quality of life indicators for Canadian municipalities.  The analysis resulted in a set 
of measures for assessing urban quality of life called the Community Oriented Model of the Lived 
Environment (COMLE).  The COMLE model is based on the realization that our health depends on the 
quality of the social, physical and economic environment, and on equal access to the opportunities 
they provide. 
<P> 

In 1993, Toronto, along with Fort McMurray and Quebec City, became involved in a pilot test of 
the COMLE model.  A key result of the pilot test was Torontos first State of the City report 
called <I>Modeling Quality of Life Indicators in Canada: A Pilot Test of Quality of Life Indicators 
in Toronto.</i>  The report established indicators in the following categories:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Economic Life<BR>	
Transportation</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Environment<br>
Education</b>	
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Safety<BR>
Housing	</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Community Health</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To order the report and contact information:</u>
<p>
Healthy City Toronto<BR>
20 Dundas Street West, Suite 1036<BR>
Toronto, Ontario, Canada  M5G 2C2

<BR><BR>

For more information, see the <B>City of Toronto Quality of Life Report Web site (available 
Fall 1996).</b>

