<CENTER><P>
<IMG SRC="/rsc/mrule.gif"><BR>  </P></CENTER>
<center><font size=+3>GLOBAL INDICATOR PROJECTS </font></center>
<P>
<B>16. <a name="o">Agenda 21</b>
<P>

In 1992, the United Nations Conference on Environment and Development (UNCED), better known as 
the Earth Summit, was held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil.  Over 170 countries cooperated to produce 
treaties on climate change and biological diversity, a set of forestry principles, and an 
extensive plan called Agenda 21 for sustainable development now and into the 21st century.
<P>

Within Agenda 21 is a proposal to develop indicators for sustainable development.  The objective 
is to make indicators accessible worldwide to decision makers at the national level by defining 
sustainability indicators, elucidating their methodologies, and providing training and other 
capacity-building activities.
<P>

<U>To obtain the report and contact information:</u>
<p>
Secretariat of the United Nations<BR>
Commission on Sustainable Development<BR>
United Nations Plaza, Room DC2-2270<BR>
New York, New York  10017<BR>
(212)  963-3170

<BR><BR>

For more information, see Agenda 21, Chapter 40 "Information for Decision Making" at the <B>United 
Nations Agenda 21 Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="gopher://gopher.un.org/00esc/cn17/1995/off/95-18.en">gopher://gopher.un.org/00esc/cn17/1995/off/95-18.en</a>

<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>17. <a name="q">Development Watch</b>
<P>

Development Watch emerged as a working concept from the 1992 Earth Summits Agenda 21 plan for 
sustainable development.  A program of the United Nations Development Program (UNDP), Development 
Watch aims to provide decision- and policy-makers with tools for analyzing the environmental, 
institutional, social, and economic variables that will facilitate sustainable development.
<P>

Development Watch will not gather new data, but will instead use existing data to assist national 
level decision makers identify the appropriate indicators that reinforce sustainable development 
policy.  The program is underway with pilot projects in Bolivia, Botswana, Costa Rica, Malaysia, 
Morocco, Tunisia, South Africa, and Ukraine to compile and analyze indicators related to 
national level sustainable development planning and decision making.
<P>

<u>To obtain reports and contact information:</u>
<p>
Secretariat of the United Nations<BR>
UNDP<BR>
United Nations Plaza<BR>
New York, NY 10017<BR>
(212)  906-5182

<BR><BR>

For more information, see the <B>UNDP Development Watch Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.undp.org/undp/devwatch/">http://www.undp.org/undp/devwatch/</a>

<br><br><br><br>

<B>18. <a name="p">Earthwatch</b>
<P>

Earthwatch is a program of the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) to "coordinate, harmonize, 
and integrate the observing, assessment and reporting activities across the UN system in order to 
provide environmental and appropriate socio-economic information for national and international decision-making 
on sustainable development and for early warning of emerging problems requiring international action."
<P>

Earthwatch is charged with developing global indicators to monitor natural and human systems in 
the following categories:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Quality of Human Life<P>
Biodiversity<P>
Atmospheric quality<P>
Oceans and coastal areas</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Risks of Biotechnology<P>
Freshwater Resources<P>
Accumulation of wastes</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain reports and contact information:</u>
<p>
United Nations Environment Program<br>
Box 30552<br>
Nairobi<br>
Kenya<br>
2542 621 234

<br><br>

For more information and to download the latest Earthwatch Report, see the <B>UNEP Earthwatch 
Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.unep.ch/earthw.html">http://www.unep.ch/earthw.html</a>

<BR><BR><BR><BR>

<B>19. <a name="r">Worldwatch Institute</b>
<P>

The Worldwatch Institute (WWI) is an international non-profit organization dedicated to fostering 
the evolution of an environmentally sustainable society through inter-disciplinary non-partisan 
research on emerging global environmental issues.  WWI publishes in a highly regarded annual 
report titled <U>Vital Signs: The Trends That Are Shaping Our Future</u> that analyzes the major ecological, 
economic, and social forces affecting the World.
<P>

In <U>Vital Signs 1996,</u> 14 researchers collaborated to present 33 key indicators which 
incorporate data from 1950 through 1995 in the following areas:
<P>

<table cellspacing=20>
<tr><td width=50></td><td valign=top>
<B>Food Trends<P>
Energy Trends<P>
Agricultural Resource Trends<P>
Atmospheric Trends</b>
</td><td valign=top>
<B>Economic Trends<P>
Transportation Trends<P>
Social Trends<P>
Military Trends</b>
</td></tr>
</table>

<BR><BR>

<U>To obtain report or for more information:</u>
<p>
Worldwatch Institute<BR>
1776 Massachusetts Avenue, N.W.<BR>
Washington, D.C.  20036<BR>
(202)  296-7365

<BR><BR>

For more information, see the <B>WWI Web site:</b><BR>
<a href="http://www.worldwatch.org/pubs/vs/vs96/index.html">
         http://www.worldwatch.org/pubs/vs/vs96/index.html</a>

